CREATE TABLE `aggregator_feed` (
  `fid` int(11) NOT NULL AUTO_INCREMENT COMMENT 'Primary Key: Unique feed ID.',
  `title` varchar(255) NOT NULL DEFAULT '' COMMENT 'Title of the feed.',
  `url` text NOT NULL COMMENT 'URL to the feed.',
  `refresh` int(11) NOT NULL DEFAULT '0' COMMENT 'How often to check for new feed items, in seconds.',
  `checked` int(11) NOT NULL DEFAULT '0' COMMENT 'Last time feed was checked for new items, as Unix timestamp.',
  `queued` int(11) NOT NULL DEFAULT '0' COMMENT 'Time when this feed was queued for refresh, 0 if not queued.',
  `link` text NOT NULL COMMENT 'The parent website of the feed; comes from the <link> element in the feed.',
  `description` longtext NOT NULL COMMENT 'The parent website’s description; comes from the <description> element in the feed.',
  `image` longtext NOT NULL COMMENT 'An image representing the feed.',
  `hash` varchar(64) NOT NULL DEFAULT '' COMMENT 'Calculated hash of the feed data, used for validating cache.',
  `etag` varchar(255) NOT NULL DEFAULT '' COMMENT 'Entity tag HTTP response header, used for validating cache.',
  `modified` int(11) NOT NULL DEFAULT '0' COMMENT 'When the feed was last modified, as a Unix timestamp.',
  `block` tinyint(4) NOT NULL DEFAULT '0' COMMENT 'Number of items to display in the feed’s block.',
  PRIMARY KEY (`fid`),
  UNIQUE KEY `title` (`title`),
  KEY `url` (`url`(255)),
  KEY `queued` (`queued`)
) ENGINE=InnoDB AUTO_INCREMENT=2 DEFAULT CHARSET=utf8 COMMENT='Stores feeds to be parsed by the aggregator.';
/*!40101 SET character_set_client = @saved_cs_client */;

Video by Innovate Kentucky.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>LEXINGTON, Ky. (April 8, 2013) —</strong> The See Blue STEM camp, open to Kentucky students currently in 4<sup>th</sup> through 7<sup>th</sup> grades, is currently accepting registrations for its week-long day camp.&nbsp; Students will participate in hands-on projects in the subjects of science, technology, engineering and math (STEM).</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The camp will host current 4<sup>th</sup> and 5<sup>th</sup> grade students June 3-7, 2013 and current 6<sup>th</sup> and 7<sup>th</sup> grade students June 10-14, 2013, on UK\'s campus.&nbsp; Registration can be completed online at <a href=\"http://education.uky.edu/STEM/content/seebluestemcamp\">http://education.uky.edu/STEM/content/seebluestemcamp</a>.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The camp was started in 2010 by Craig Schroeder, a mathematics and science teacher at&nbsp; Beaumont Middle School in Lexington.&nbsp; It is a collaboration between the <a href=\"http://www.engr.uky.edu/\">UK College of Engineering</a>, <a href=\"http://education.uky.edu/\">UK College of Education</a>, and the<a href=\"http://p20.education.uky.edu/\"> Kentucky P20 Innovation Lab</a>. The camp is also fortunate enough to be partially funded for this summer by the <a href=\"http://www.kentuckymathematics.org/\">Kentucky Center for Mathematics</a>.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>\"My goal would be for them to find something they really enjoy to be their career, something that they’re passionate about,\" Schroeder said. \"I know they have fun during this week, but hopefully they go back and say \'oh that was really exciting, I want to do more in that area.\'\"</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>This year\'s camp will feature UK STEM faculty from the departments of&nbsp;Physics and Astronomy, Neurobiology, Biology, Marketing and Supply Chain, Engineering, and STEM Education. The students will also have the opportunity to learn about STEM concepts through the use of LEGORobotics, including a competition at the end of the week.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Margaret Mohr-Schroeder, associate professor of mathematics education in the <a href=\"http://education.uky.edu/STEM/\">UK Department of STEM Education</a>, based in the College of Education, says collaboration at UK is key in making the camp a success. \"We are excited about the group of faculty and STEM topics this year. The students will be engaged in a variety of STEM areas they do not typically see day-to-day. (April 9, 2013) —</strong> Faculty and students from the <a href=\"http://education.uky.edu/\">UK College of Education</a> recently held their annual math night to the joy of teachers, students and parents at Lexington\'s Beaumont Middle School.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>\"I truly do not have enough words to accurately describe how valuable math night was for our students,\" said Brooke Powers, mathematics teacher at Beaumont. \"It provided students and their families with an opportunity to play math games together. Having parents come in for a fun, positive experience is a great way to build positive relationships with parents which only further benefits students.\"</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Family Math Night (FMN) began in the spring of 2008 to help satisfy the college’s desire to provide more outreach with local schools that involve preservice teachers in more informal activities with the schools. Coordinated by Associate Professor Margaret Mohr-Schroeder, Craig Schroeder (then a graduate student in the College of Education), and former faculty member Tim Jacobbe, the first FMN was held at Booker T. Washington Academy where 200 students and parents took part in a variety of mathematics activities. Since then, FMNs have been held at Clark Middle School and Beaumont Middle School, with other sites targeted for future events.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Mohr-Schroeder says that FMNs are great experiences for both the families involved and the college’s preservice teachers.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>\"Through Family Math Nights, the schools have been able to bring families into the school and have them participate in mathematics games that are fun and enjoyable for everyone in the family,\" Mohr-Schroeder said. \"The parents are always very excited about the event, and it is a lot of fun to watch them interact with their children. The events also allow our preservice teachers to gain \'informal\' field experience hours in a different kind of setting. They love the fast-paced nature of the night and are always surprised at the number of families who attend and participate. It also gets them to think differently about the mathematics they teach, especially in terms of how they can turn \'boring\' content into something fun, challenging and relevant.\"</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>For more information on the UK College of Education\'s mathematics and other STEM-related education programs, visit <a href=\"http://education.uky.edu/STEM/.\">http://education.uky.edu/STEM/.</a></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>MEDIA CONTACT: </strong>Jenny Wells, <span style=\"white-space: nowrap;\" class=\"baec5a81-e4d6-4674-97f3-e9220f0136c1\">(859) 257-5343<a style=\"margin: 0px; border: currentColor; left: 0px; top: 0px; width: 16px; height: 16px; right: 0px; bottom: 0px; overflow: hidden; vertical-align: middle; float: none; display: inline; white-space: nowrap; position: static !important;\" title=\"Call: (859) 257-5343\" href=\"#\"><img style=\"margin: 0px; border: currentColor; left: 0px; top: 0px; width: 16px; height: 16px; right: 0px; bottom: 0px; overflow: hidden; vertical-align: middle; float: none; display: inline; white-space: nowrap; position: static !important;\" title=\"Call: (859) 257-5343\" src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" /></a></span>; Jenny.Wells@uky.edu&nbsp;</p>',1365174873,'29630 at http://uknow.uky.edu'),(3,1,'CAER-mentored Projects Win at Recent Science Fairs','http://uknow.uky.edu/content/caer-mentored-projects-win-recent-science-fairs','Keith Hautala','<span class=\"sw_img_wrap\"><a class=\"sw_img_a\" href=\"http://uknow.uky.edu/sites/default/files/multi-walled_carbon_nanotube.png\"><img class=\"sw_img\" src=\"http://uknow.uky.edu/sites/default/files/imagecache/ctac_thumb/multi-walled_carbon_nanotube.png\" /></a></span> <!--break--><p><strong>LEXINGTON, Ky. (April&nbsp;9, 2013) —</strong> Four local high school students who were mentored by University of Kentucky Center for Applied Energy Research scientists have proved that experience gained by working in laboratories with mentors is invaluable.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Valerie Sarge, a junior at Paul Laurence Dunbar High School, placed first in the Energy and Transportation category at the Central Kentucky Regional Science and Engineering Fair, going on to win first place in the same category at the state competition. This qualifies her to go on to Intel’s International Science and Engineering Fair (ISEF) to be held in Phoenix. Sarge was mentored by John Anthony, chemistry professor and CAER faculty associate. In her work with the solar energy group, Sarge is using organic compounds called furan-based materials. These can be derived from agricultural waste products to create new semiconductors for use in low-cost solar cells. She has been working on synthesis, but may soon move toward creating solar cells.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Will Kimmerer, from Sayre School, won top awards at the regional and state fairs in the Environmental Science category, including second in the Physical Sciences category. Kimmerer obtained carbon material samples for use in his project from CAER and worked closely with CAER Director Rodney Andrews during the project. He was selected for the I-SWEEP 2013 conference (International Sustainable World Energy Engineering Environment Project) in Houston, where he will present his work. Additionally, he was selected for the Stockholm Junior Water Award.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Two Dunbar CAER interns placed well at the regional level and went on to compete at the state competition. Rohin Lohe placed first in the \"Engineering: Materials and Bioengineering\" category, and went on to place third at the state competition. Lohe will compete at the Kentucky Junior Academy of Sciences on April 27. John Luan won in the “Energy and Transportation” category at regionals.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Matt Weisenberger, associate director for carbon materials, is mentoring Lohe with a project titled \"Finite Element Analysis of Heat Conduction through Interfaces: Modeling and Experimental Verification with Stainless Steel, Copper, and Multiwall Carbon Nanotube Arrays as Thermal Interface Materials.\" Lohe has been conducting his research at CAER laboratory facilities and working directly with the carbon materials research staff in completing the tests.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Finally, Luan\'s project included part of the expertise gained while working with CAER’s electrochemical power sources group under the direction of Associate Director Steve Lipka. value=\"transparent\" />\n    <!-- Fallback content -->\n      <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=txWOe8QlzhQ\"><img src=\"/sites/default/files/emvideo-youtube-videoseries_6.jpg\" alt=\"See video\" title=\"See video\"  width=\"425\" height=\"350\" /></a>  </object>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div></div></p><p>Video by UK Public Relations and Marketing.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>LEXINGTON, Ky. (April 8, 2013)</strong> — Although there is only one Earth Day observed every year in April, the University of Kentucky actually celebrates its sustainability initiatives throughout the month and remembers its commitments to the university and the community every day of the year.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Advancements in ensuring a better world for future generations have been made in virtually every area of the campus community, from improved management of its facilities, to the advancements in its research labs, and to sharing these goals in the classrooms.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>“Through our energy conservation efforts, including our Campus Energy Savings Project and the enhancements of our Delta Room where energy consumption is monitored continuously, UK saves more than $5 million annually,” said Shane Tedder, sustainability coordinator for UK.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The <a href=\"http://www.sustainability.uky.edu/node/24\">Campus Energy Savings Project</a> includes changing old lighting technology to a more energy efficient design, replacing high flow plumbing fixtures with low flow design, and upgrading existing mechanical HVAC systems in 61 buildings on campus. Electrical consumption constitutes the largest percentage of UK\'s carbon footprint and the Campus Energy Savings Project reduced the university’s electrical consumption by 11.2 percent in those buildings, while steam usage was reduced by 29.1 percent and domestic water by 14.5 percent. The project will save 19,811 US tons of CO2 on an annual basis. Watch a&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.sustainability.uky.edu/node/184/\">video</a>&nbsp;explaining how the project works.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The <a href=\"http://www.sustainability.uky.edu/files/Videos/12_Deltapercent20Room.wmv\">Delta Room</a> is a sophisticated manned control center that monitors the university’s energy usage 24 hours a day, 365 days a year. &nbsp;It centrally controls lighting and temperature in the majority of campus buildings using conservation techniques when the buildings are not in use. &nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>In addition to several panel discussions and the numerous experts brought to campus to address sustainability issues with the campus community, the <a href=\"http://www.sustainability.uky.edu/Home\">Office of Sustainability</a> this year expanded its support of two-wheeled transportation with bike safety programs, bike lanes on city streets near campus and additional bike repair stations. It also launched this year an expanded outdoor recycling pilot project and a new recycling coordinator was recently added to the Facilities Management staff.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>“Via pilot projects, we hope to transition to single stream recycling rather than source separated as is currently in place and to increase our composting efforts,” Tedder said.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>This year, <a href=\"http://sustainability.uky.edu/PSAC\">the President’s Sustainability Advisory Committee</a> has tackled such issues as the role sustainability will play in the upcoming selection of a food service provider for UK, the development of a Climate Action Plan for the university, the inclusion of sustainability issues in UK’s revised Master Plan, and ideas for integrating sustainability into the curricular and co-curricular experience.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The <a href=\"http://sustainability.uky.edu/SSC\">Student Sustainability Council</a> has also been active, expanding old conservation projects while also developing new ones. The council was formed to supervise the distribution of the Environmental Stewardship Fee, in order to responsibly advance the theory, practice and reality of sustainability at UK. Its 2012-13 funded projects included expanded outdoor recycling in heavily traveled areas such as the Student Center and the William T, Young Library, 22 water bottle-filling stations, a campuswide sustainability survey, Earth Days in the Bluegrass events, an environmental issues spring event, support of a Political Ecology Working Group Conference and support of other events and activities.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Much of the year’s work of these groups and individuals culminates in the monthlong celebration of Earth Day. Nearly every day in April features a speaker, a forum, a film, a workshop, or a summit that focuses on a sustainable future for the university, the state, the nation and the world. For a complete calendar of events, including the popular annual Earth Day Fair on April 22, visit <a href=\"http://www.sustainability.uky.edu/edbg\">http://www.sustainability.uky.edu/edbg</a>.</p>',1365403829,'29643 at http://uknow.uky.edu'),(6,1,'Boone Center Grill on Terrace Open to All for Lunch','http://uknow.uky.edu/content/boone-center-grill-terrace-open-all-lunch','Kathy Johnson','<span class=\"sw_img_wrap\"><a class=\"sw_img_a\" href=\"http://uknow.uky.edu/sites/default/files/boone_center_lunch_options.jpg\"><img class=\"sw_img\" src=\"http://uknow.uky.edu/sites/default/files/imagecache/ctac_thumb/boone_center_lunch_options.jpg\" /></a></span> <!--break--><p><strong>LEXINGTON, Ky. Young Library.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>“Our goal is to create the best possible dining services operation for the University of Kentucky,” said Eric N. These forums are designed to continue the dialogue already taking place, while also allowing everyone involved to ask questions about the process and our commitment to creating an even stronger dining services operation for our students, faculty, staff and visitors.”</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The <a href=\"http://www.uky.edu/DiningRevitalization/news.html\">Dining Revitalization Committee</a> created to review options to transform dining on campus recently recommended the university move forward with requests for proposals (RFPs) from potential business partners. The committee includes representatives from UK faculty, staff and the student body.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>In an email to dining services employees last week, Monday wrote, \"Fully exploring how a partnership with a third party would make such an operation a reality is the responsible course to take.\"</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Responding to concerns and questions previously raised by students, university and local community groups interested in sustainability and other issues, the committee recommended that certain commitments be included in the RFP, including:</p><p>·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Ensuring that current full-time UK dining employees will have employment opportunities with either the university or the selected business partner, if the university administration and the Board of Trustees ultimately take that path. The 10-week program offers instruction to women and minority business owners to help them compete in the construction industry. &nbsp;Program participants must be a minority or women owned business with at least 51 percent ownership in a construction-related business.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>This year’s graduates are:</p><p>&nbsp;</p><ul><li>Jakendricks Bradley (All In, Inc.)</li></ul><div><ul><li>Dametrius Drake (Lexington General Contracting &amp; Services)</li></ul><ul><li>Cindy England (Somethin Bloomin, LLC)</li></ul><ul><li>Caroline E. Program participants learned the necessary tools to grow their business despite an uncertain economy and had an opportunity to network with one another and prime contractors, building relationships that they can draw upon in the future.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The Minority and Women Training Program began in 2001 as a way to increase opportunities for women and minority business owners and graduated more than 100 entrepreneurs state-wide.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>In 2011 a partnership was formed between the Blue Grass Airport, Fayette County Public Schools, Lexington Fayette Urban County Government (LFUCG), Messer, BEX Construction, UK Facilities Management and the Kentucky Small Business Development Center to restart the program. “We recognized a real need for this program in our communities,” said Marilyn Clark, LFUCG minority business enterprise liaison. “By working together we were able to bring the program back and serve more minority and women business owners.”</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>For more information on the Minority and Women Construction Training Program contact Dee Dee Harbut at <a href=\"mailto:DHarbut@uky.edu\">DHarbut@uky.edu</a> or Marilyn Clark at <a href=\"mailto:MClark@lexingtonky.gov\">MClark@lexingtonky.gov</a>.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p align=\"center\">&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>MEDIA CONTACT:&nbsp;&nbsp; The students are representing UK against teams from all of Kentucky’s public universities for the best business plans and business concepts based on their ideas for innovative products and services.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The following are the undergraduate and graduate student teams. These UK teams were recent winners of the University of Kentucky Venture Challenge competition held in February.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><u>UK Undergraduate Teams</u></p><p><strong>Latta Fasteners</strong> – Matt Dieruf, Electrical Engineering Senior<br /> Business plan to produce a new type of screw specifically for industries that require both routine maintenance and coatings to protect screws during operation.<br />&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Control My ADHD</strong> – Grant Weherley, Economics Senior<br /> Business concept for a subscription-based online resource including video lessons for adults living with ADHD.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><u>UK Graduate Teams</u></p><p><strong>TerraCast Technologies</strong> – MBA students Jordan Denny, Jarrod Willis, Lee Goatley, and Jordan Laycock<br /> Business plan to reclaim mountaintop sites by growing switchgrass for biofuel production.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>EARlyTAG</strong> – MBA students Kaitlyn Foree, Jeffrey Billion, Nathan Miles, William Templeton, and Alex Hart, Agricultural Economics Junior<br /> Business concept to dramatically reduce costs related to livestock illness with new symptom-detection technology.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The public is invited to the Lexington Center, Level 3 on Friday, April 12, at 4 p.m.&nbsp;to see the students’ tabletop exhibits on their proposed business ventures.&nbsp; The public can also attend the elevator pitch contest, which begins at 5:30 p.m. The elevator pitch contest will feature one member from each team who will pitch their idea in 60 seconds or less before a panel of expert judges.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>On Saturday, April 13, beginning at 8 a.m., the teams make their formal presentations to the judges. UK achieved a Bronze level designation and was one of only nine new universities to be named in the fall 2012 award class. The award gives UK the distinction of being the only Bicycle Friendly University in Kentucky.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The Bicycle Friendly University program recognizes institutions of higher education for promoting and providing a more bicycle-friendly campus for students, employees and visitors. Applicants are judged on their initiatives in five categories: engineering, education, encouragement, enforcement and evaluation and planning.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Eric Monday, executive vice president for finance and administration, praises the university’s efforts. “Being recognized by the League of American Bicyclists is an honor and a tribute to the leadership and effort of the <a href=\"http://www.uky.edu/pts/BAC\">Bicycle Advisory Committee</a>, <a href=\"http://www.uky.edu/pts/\">Parking and Transportation Services</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.sustainability.uky.edu/\">Office of Sustainability</a>. We are proud of the strides the University of Kentucky has made in improving bicycling on campus and feel confident that the future is bright for biking on campus.”</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The list of Bicycle Friendly Universities includes just 44 colleges in 25 states. Along with being the first Kentucky university to earn the designation, UK is just the second Southeastern Conference school to make the list. The University of South Carolina earned bronze status in March 2012.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The League of American Bicyclists named the first class of Bicycle Friendly Universities in March 2011. At that time, UK received an honorable mention. In the 19 months between receiving honorable mention status and the Bronze award, UK has made great strides in making campus a more bicycle friendly place to live and work. These efforts have included the establishment of dedicated bicycle funding and the formation of the Bicycle Advisory Committee (BAC), the addition of 1.5 miles of bike lanes on and around campus through collaboration with Lexington Fayette Urban-County Government, and upgrading 20 percent&nbsp;of the campus bicycle parking spaces to a more efficient rack style. Other notable bicycle-related events include the creation of a bike education-oriented K Week event, Pedalpalooza, which focuses on improving bicycle skills and knowledge, and the installation of four do-it-yourself fix-it stations around campus.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Stuart Kearns, associate director of Transportation Services for Parking and Transportation Services and chair of the BAC, says, “UK’s campus is continually becoming a more bike-friendly place to live, work and attend classes. The BAC is excited about upcoming projects designed to provide additional connectivity to our growing bike network and improve and expand campus bicycle parking.”</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>As part of the University’s annual <a href=\"http://sustainability.uky.edu/edbg\">Earthdays in the Bluegrass</a> celebration, PTS and its partners will be holding Bike Week April 14-20. The goals of the SECU initiative include highlighting the endeavors and achievements of SEC faculty and universities; advancing the merit and reputation of SEC universities outside of the traditional SEC region; identifying and preparing future leaders for high-level service in academia; increasing the amount and type of education abroad opportunities available to SEC students; and providing opportunities for collaboration among SEC university personnel.</em></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p>',1365632377,'29742 at http://uknow.uky.edu'),(19,1,'UK International Center Identifies University\'s Greatest Global Opportunities','http://uknow.uky.edu/content/uk-international-center-identifies-universitys-greatest-global-opportunities','Sarah Geegan','<span class=\"sw_img_wrap\"><a class=\"sw_img_a\" href=\"http://uknow.uky.edu/sites/default/files/flags_3.jpg\"><img class=\"sw_img\" src=\"http://uknow.uky.edu/sites/default/files/imagecache/ctac_thumb/flags.jpg\" /></a></span> <!--break--><p><strong>LEXINGTON, Ky. (April 12, 2013)</strong> <strong>— </strong><a href=\"http://www.uky.edu/international/\">The University of Kentucky International Center</a> (UKIC) is leading the development of a new strategic plan that will align with UK President Eli Capilouto’s priorities of enhancing educational excellence and seeking external funding to support that enhancement.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>To focus UKIC’s strategic planning, <a href=\"https://hs.as.uky.edu/users/carvalho\">Susan Carvalho</a>, associate provost for international programs, has organized a process to identify geographic hubs that offer the greatest opportunities to meet President Capilouto’s priorities.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>“We are in an environment of finite resources,” Carvalho said. “The International Center needs to focus its resources towards a few strategic, geographic hubs that will create real synergies for UK.”</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>In consultation with Interim Provost Tim Tracy, Carvalho asked the International Advisory Committee (IAC), a group of faculty and administrators representing each of the university’s colleges, to identify seven geographic regions where UK has the greatest strategic opportunity. The IAC then nominated nearly 100 faculty members — who are active in those geographic regions — to serve on committees for each of the seven regions.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>“This process puts people, faculty and experts around the table who may have never met before,” Carvalho said. “This creates synergy across UK’s departments and colleges. It’s the kind of conversation that universities ought to be having.”</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The committees will identify three to four geographic hubs where UK\'s strengths and external opportunities converge. Once the hubs are identified, the IAC will explore opportunities that will align with Capilouto’s priorities, and ways to position UK faculty to maximize those opportunities, focusing on infrastructure such as an office there and/or here, travel money, strategic hiring and partnerships in the region.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The IAC will also identify three to four second tier hubs, where UK may not currently have the strength to compete for external opportunities, but toward which the university should focus for future planning.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The goal is to have the hubs identified by May, a report that identifies strategic opportunities in these hubs by the end of August, and a UKIC strategic plan in place by the time UK develops its new campus wide strategic plan for 2014-2019.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>In order to accomplish the president’s priorities, Carvalho believes UK must celebrate and build upon the principles of “comprehensive internationalization,” which have been defined as follows:</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>“Comprehensive internationalization (CIZN) is a commitment, confirmed through action, to integrate international, global, and comparative perspectives throughout the teaching, research, and service missions of higher education. It is a means to advance the core learning, discovery, and engagement objectives of higher education in a 21st century context.” (Hudzik &amp; McCarthy 2012, Leading Comprehensive Internationalization iv.)</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>CIZN will enhance education excellence by bringing meaningful international elements into the curriculum, creating excellent study abroad opportunities, and by recruiting talented international students to UK and will support that excellence through sustainable revenue sources, such as grants and international student tuition.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;“We are working to get broad support on this process so that we have something in place by the time the new provost arrives,” said Carvalho. “Although we are in an environment with finite resources, there is passion for growing and serving our students better. This kind of prioritization is essential and energizing for the entire campus.”</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>MEDIA CONTACT:</strong> Sarah Geegan, <span style=\"white-space: nowrap;\" class=\"baec5a81-e4d6-4674-97f3-e9220f0136c1\">(859) 257-5365<a style=\"margin: 0px; border: currentColor; left: 0px; top: 0px; width: 16px; height: 16px; right: 0px; bottom: 0px; overflow: hidden; vertical-align: middle; float: none; display: inline; white-space: nowrap; position: static !important;\" title=\"Call: (859) 257-5365\" href=\"#\"><img style=\"margin: 0px; border: currentColor; left: 0px; top: 0px; width: 16px; height: 16px; right: 0px; bottom: 0px; overflow: hidden; vertical-align: middle; float: none; display: inline; white-space: nowrap; position: static !important;\" title=\"Call: (859) 257-5365\" src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" /></a></span>; <a href=\"mailto:sarah.geegan@uky.edu\">sarah.geegan@uky.edu</a></p><p>&nbsp;</p>',1365697670,'29750 at http://uknow.uky.edu'),(20,1,'Child Development Center of the Bluegrass\' UK Campus Location Provides Convenience, Quality Care','http://uknow.uky.edu/content/child-development-center-bluegrass-uk-campus-location-provides-convenience-quality-care','Kristi Lopez','<span class=\"sw_img_wrap\"><a class=\"sw_img_a\" href=\"http://uknow.uky.edu/sites/default/files/cdc_jane_heck.jpg\"><img class=\"sw_img\" src=\"http://uknow.uky.edu/sites/default/files/imagecache/ctac_thumb/cdc_jane_heck.jpg\" /></a></span> <!--break--><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>LEXINGTON, Ky. to better accommodate the work schedules of both UK employees, particularly nurses working 12-hour shifts, and other Central Kentucky parents, said Vanover.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Serving children ages 6 weeks to five years old, the 22,000-square foot new facility opened its doors last August and accommodates more than triple the number of children at its previous location on Springhill Drive.&nbsp; The facility is also supported by an energy-efficient geothermal system.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The CDC\'s campus location also offers convenience for many student teachers from the UK College of Education who assist and observe at the CDC as well as for occupational therapy and physical therapy students from UK who complete clinical practicum experience at the center.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Recently, the CDC also received a grant from Toyota Motor Manufacturing in Kentucky for a music therapy program that is provided by music therapy students at the UK College of Fine Arts.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>\"I\'m already amazed at the creative programs and activities that Jane is being offered even at less than a year old,\" said her mother Sarah.&nbsp; \"But it is also the wonderful teachers and assistants that make it the perfect fit for our family.\"</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Openings are currently available for children of both UK and non-UK employees.&nbsp; For more information or to schedule a tour of the facility, go to <a href=\"http://www.cdcbg.org/\">http://www.cdcbg.org/</a> or call 859-218-2322.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Media Contact:</strong> Kristi Lopez, 859-323-6363 or <a href=\"mailto:kristi.lopez@uky.edu\">kristi.lopez@uky.edu</a></p><p>&nbsp;</p>',1365710647,'29753 at http://uknow.uky.edu'),(21,1,'WUKY\'s \'UK Perspectives\' Features Planners of \'A Taste of Africa\'','http://uknow.uky.edu/content/wukys-uk-perspectives-features-planners-taste-africa','Kathy Johnson','<span class=\"sw_img_wrap\"><a class=\"sw_img_a\" href=\"http://uknow.uky.edu/sites/default/files/wuky_rocks_cropped_79.jpg\"><img class=\"sw_img\" src=\"http://uknow.uky.edu/sites/default/files/imagecache/ctac_thumb/wuky_rocks_cropped.jpg\" /></a></span> <!--break--><p><strong>LEXINGTON, Ky. (April 15, 2013)</strong> <strong>— </strong>A delegation of 20 UK students, hospital administrators, faculty and staff recently returned from Cuba, where through an <a href=\"http://www.uky.edu/international/educationabroad\">Education Abroad</a> program they explored the country’s unique health care system.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The delegation, led by Peter Berres, retired assistant dean for student affairs in the College of Health Sciences, and Claudia Hopenhayn, associate professor in the College of Public Health, met with a broad range of health care professionals, from family doctors to some of the top medical specialists in the country.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>“Cuba was rarely in the media for my generation,” Brigid Cecil, a public health master\'s student, said. “But I did know that Cuba’s health care system is known as one of the best in the world, in terms of being cost beneficial.”</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The 50-year U.S. embargo has left Cuba with few resources. To be effective, the country has invested in prevention and health promotion at all levels of its health care system.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>“For example, in Havana there is a family physician for each four-block area,” Berres said. “The physician cares for entire families — they go to their homes, they live in same communities and they know their patients. The knowledge of families from generation to generation among these physicians is highly valuable for preventative care.”</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Unlike many developing countries, Cuba does not have a shortage of physicians. There is a doctor for every 170 residents in Cuba, which is the second highest ratio in the world according to the World Health Organization. The surplus allows Cuban physicians to spend one to two years working in countries that are in dire need of medical care.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>In addition to exporting its physicians, Cuba is also helping countries develop their health care infrastructure through the Elam Latin American School of Medicine.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>“Elam started out as a humanitarian effort for hurricane devastated Central American countries, and soon developed into a permanent training site for a wider range of countries,” Hopenhayn said. “There are currently about 50 U.S. students studying there; we met one student from Wyoming who is glad to get a free medical education, while learning Spanish.”</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Berres added that U.S. medical students who have been trained in Cuba, have a very high rate of passing the Medical Licensing Examination in the U.S.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The delegation also noted some of the disadvantages of Cuba’s health care system, such as the quality of its medical facilities.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>“Many of the problems with Cuba’s health care system are associated with the American embargo,” Berres said. “This prevents them from having access to the latest pharmaceutical and technological advances, so many of their facilities are very basic.”</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Despite the embargo, Cuban research laboratories are developing innovative procedures, such as a vaccine for lung cancer and a treatment for diabetes that can prevent amputations.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>“They have things that we as U.S. citizens — because of the embargo — do not have access to,” Sarah Yeiser, a master\'s student in public health, said. “It is not just a one-way relationship; we have an opportunity to benefit from Cuba.”</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The delegation met with many Cubans who shared their thoughts about their country and its health care system.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>“Everyone we spoke with was willing to discuss the problems in Cuba with us, including their low salaries and scarcity of certain products,” said Hopenhayn. “Yet they all praised their health care and educational systems, which are free for all citizens. Cuba may not be perfect, but Cubans seemed very proud of what their country has achieved.”</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Education Abroad Director Anthony Ogden said that it had been a long time since UK has planned a program in Cuba. Nonetheless Ogden is looking forward to offering&nbsp;Berres\' and Hopenhayn’s Cuba program again next year.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>MEDIA CONTACT:</strong> Sarah Geegan, <span style=\"white-space: nowrap;\" class=\"baec5a81-e4d6-4674-97f3-e9220f0136c1\">(859) 257-5365<a style=\"margin: 0px; border: currentColor; left: 0px; top: 0px; width: 16px; height: 16px; right: 0px; bottom: 0px; overflow: hidden; vertical-align: middle; float: none; display: inline; white-space: nowrap; position: static !important;\" title=\"Call: (859) 257-5365\" href=\"#\"><img style=\"margin: 0px; border: currentColor; left: 0px; top: 0px; width: 16px; height: 16px; right: 0px; bottom: 0px; overflow: hidden; vertical-align: middle; float: none; display: inline; white-space: nowrap; position: static !important;\" title=\"Call: (859) 257-5365\" src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" /></a></span>; <a href=\"mailto:sarah.geegan@uky.edu\">sarah.geegan@uky.edu</a></p>',1365712708,'29755 at http://uknow.uky.edu'),(24,1,'Latest Historical Marker Honors Student Competitions','http://uknow.uky.edu/content/latest-historical-marker-honors-student-competitions','Carl Nathe','<span class=\"sw_img_wrap\"><a class=\"sw_img_a\" href=\"http://uknow.uky.edu/sites/default/files/historical_marker_dedication_cropped.jpg\"><img class=\"sw_img\" src=\"http://uknow.uky.edu/sites/default/files/imagecache/ctac_thumb/historical_marker_dedication_cropped.jpg\" /></a></span> <!--break--><p><strong>LEXINGTON, Ky. (April 15, 2013) — </strong>University of Kentucky President Eli Capilouto joined the president of the <a href=\"http://sweb.uky.edu/StudentOrgs/SDC/\">UK Student Development Council</a>, Jonathon Nunley, <a href=\"http://history.ky.gov/\">Kentucky Historical Society</a> Marker Program Coordinator Becky Riddle&nbsp;and others this afternoon in dedicating the latest addition to the Live Blue Legacy historical marker program.&nbsp; The marker is made possible through donations from members of the Class of 2012.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>This historical highway marker, the 19th in a series, pays tribute to UK student traditions dating back more than 100 years.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>An early rivalry between freshman and sophomore classes on the UK campuses was the annual \'Flag Rush\' competition where one class would defend their flag from being captured by a rush of competitors.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Replacing the flag rush in 1913 was the \'Tug of War\' across Clifton Pond.&nbsp; Students were granted a half-holiday for the annual drenching, and crowds could reach more than 2,000 for the event. &nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The dedication ceremony and unveiling of the marker took place at a site located near the William T. Young Library on the UK campus. &nbsp;A reception followed.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Since 1994, the Live Blue Legacy Program has supported the placement of Kentucky Historical Society Highway Markers across the UK campus.&nbsp; The Live Blue Legacy Program is administered by the Student Development Council, whose members solicit gifts from members of the graduating class, in this case the Class of 2012.&nbsp; These funds are used to purchase, install and dedicate a marker in the name of that particular class.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Potential topics for the markers are selected from an approved list by the UK Historical Marker Committee, which is chaired by the associate director of annual giving/Student Development Council advisor.&nbsp; A list of three potential marker topics is presented to members of the graduating class and a vote determines the final topic.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Nunley said, \"This is a very exciting time of the year for the Student Development Council (SDC) and the university.&nbsp; We are incredibly lucky to be able to erect a historical marker every year which is funded entirely by students.&nbsp; SDC takes great pride in the rich tradition that our university and Commonwealth provide us as students every day and this marker is our way of showing it.\"</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>\"We\'re proud of this longstanding partnership with UK and deeply appreciate the generous gifts made by each graduating class to share a piece of UK and Kentucky history through the marker program,\" Riddle said.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>This UK historical marker project is done in cooperation with the Kentucky Historical Society and the Kentucky Transportation Cabinet.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The Student Development Council has raised more than $110,000 for the marker program and student scholarships since the inception of the Live Blue Legacy Program.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p align=\"center\">&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong><u>MEDIA CONTACT:</u></strong>&nbsp; (April 16, 2013) </strong>− University of Kentucky students, staff and faculty will have the opportunity to stand out, speak up and seize control at UK\'s third annual Kick Butts Day from 11 a.m. - 2 p.m. on Tuesday, April 16, outside the Rose Street walkway to the W.T. Young Library.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The goal of Kick Butts Day is to bring awareness to the issue of tobacco use and how it impacts Kentuckians.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>\"Nearly 8,000 people die each year in Kentucky due to smoking,\" said Fadyia Lowe, tobacco treatment specialist at <a href=\"http://ukhealthcare.uky.edu/uhs/\">University Health Service</a>. \"That\'s 22 people per day.\"&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>To illustrate the huge number of people who lose their lives to tobacco, there will be a display of white sheets covered with handprints, with each handprint representing five lives lost each year. Some of the handprints will be in black paint to represent the 30 percent of UK students who use tobacco.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Two hundred remaining hand prints are needed to represent the almost 1,000 lives lost each year in Kentucky among nonsmokers exposed to secondhand smoke. Information and resources will be available on how to stop using tobacco or how to help someone else quit. &nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Join members of the men’s and women’s soccer team as they kick around the soccer ball, play a round of tobacco jeopardy or corn hole. There will be plenty of free giveaways for students including food, free fountain drink coupons from campus dining locations and T-shirts from UK\'s <a href=\"http://getinvolved.uky.edu/register/Search/Details.aspx?Id=50ca9073-3a6e-4f1d-86e7-7893947d9951\">Student Heath Advisory Council (SHAC)</a>. &nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Students, faculty, and staff can also learn more about <em>Tobacco-free Take Action!</em>, an effort to increase compliance with UK’s tobacco-free policy. To report violations of UK’s tobacco-free policy, please email <a href=\"mailto:ReportTFviolation@uky.edu\">ReportTFviolation@uky.edu</a>.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Kick Butts Day is sponsored by University Health Service, the College of Pharmacy Student Health Advisory Council, and the Tobacco-free Campus Initiative Task Force. &nbsp;For more information on UK’s tobacco-free policy, go to <a href=\"http://www.uky.edu/Tobaccofree\">www.uky.edu/Tobaccofree</a></p><p>Follow us on Twitter @UHSPAWS and @UKTakeAction</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Like us on Facebook@ <a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/UKstudenthealth\">https://www.facebook.com/UKstudenthealth</a></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Media Contact:</strong> Ann Blackford at <a href=\"mailto:ann.blackfrord@uky.edu\">ann.blackfrord@uky.edu</a> or <span style=\"white-space: nowrap;\" class=\"baec5a81-e4d6-4674-97f3-e9220f0136c1\">859-312-3587<a style=\"margin: 0px; border: currentColor; left: 0px; top: 0px; width: 16px; height: 16px; right: 0px; bottom: 0px; overflow: hidden; vertical-align: middle; float: none; display: inline; white-space: nowrap; position: static !important;\" title=\"Call: 859-312-3587\" href=\"#\"><img style=\"margin: 0px; border: currentColor; left: 0px; top: 0px; width: 16px; height: 16px; right: 0px; bottom: 0px; overflow: hidden; vertical-align: middle; float: none; display: inline; white-space: nowrap; position: static !important;\" title=\"Call: 859-312-3587\" src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" /></a></span>.</p><p>&nbsp;</p>',1366050841,'29823 at http://uknow.uky.edu'),(26,1,'Author, Journalist John Egerton to Receive Award for Intellectual Achievement','http://uknow.uky.edu/content/author-journalist-john-egerton-receive-award-intellectual-achievement','Whitney Hale','<span class=\"sw_img_wrap\"><a class=\"sw_img_a\" href=\"http://uknow.uky.edu/sites/default/files/egerton_books_-_see_knowledge.jpg\"><img class=\"sw_img\" src=\"http://uknow.uky.edu/sites/default/files/imagecache/ctac_thumb/egerton_books_-_see_knowledge.jpg\" /></a></span> <!--break--><p><strong>LEXINGTON, Ky. (April 16, 2013) </strong>— Writer and alumnus <a href=\"http://www.newsouthbooks.com/bkpgs/detailauthor.php?author_id=2594\">John W. Egerton</a> will receive the 2013 <a href=\"http://libraries.uky.edu/\">University of Kentucky Libraries</a> Award for Intellectual Achievement. The award will be presented at the UK Libraries Annual Dinner scheduled for April 19, at <a href=\"http://www.marriott.com/hotels/travel/lexky-griffin-gate-marriott-resort-and-spa/\">Griffin Gate Marriott</a>, located at 1800 Newtown Pike. As part of the dinner, Egerton will talk about the place of libraries and the future of paper in the cyber age.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The UK Libraries Award for Intellectual Achievement recognizes high intellectual achievement while encouraging education and promoting creativity throughout the Commonwealth. Candidates must have been born in Kentucky or studied, worked or lived in Kentucky for at least three years and have demonstrated intellectual excellence in a scientific, artistic, literary, social or humanitarian venue or who have produced some original work or contribution of lasting value. Past recipients of the UK Libraries Award for Intellectual Achievement include Wendell Berry, James Still, Bobbie Ann Mason, William Markesbery, John Anthony and Adalin Wichman.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Nominated by <a href=\"https://ci.uky.edu/ci/users/dean\">Dean Dan O\'Hair</a>, of the <a href=\"https://ci.uky.edu/ci/\">UK College of Communication and Information</a>, Egerton was a little surprised to learn he won such a prestigious state honor joking, \"I assumed they had somehow confused me with Wendell Berry or some true intellectual.\"</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Egerton, one of the nation’s most successful independent journalists and nonfiction authors, started writing at a young age. \"I got my first byline at the age of 7, and from then on, \'writer\' was my designated occupation,\" said the award winner, who has penned more than 300 articles and columns in numerous publications, including The New York Times and The Washington Post.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Born in Atlanta, Ga., in 1935, and raised in Cadiz, Ky., Egerton began his college studies at Western Kentucky University before serving in the U.S. Army from 1954 to 1956. Two years later, he received his bachelor\'s degree in topical studies from UK. Egerton remained at the university and earned his master\'s degree in <a href=\"http://polisci.as.uky.edu/\">political science</a> in 1960. During his time at UK, he was editor of the <a href=\"http://kykernel.com/\">Kentucky Kernel</a> for a year and later served as a writer in the university\'s public relations department working with the Kentucky Research Foundation.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>A resident of Nashville, Egerton is well known for his coverage of education, race relations and social-cultural issues, even the world of food, in his native South. After leaving Kentucky, he took a job writing for Southern Education Report and its successor, Race Relations Reporter, of Nashville. Egerton later served as editor of both publications and Southern Voices before taking a writing job at Atlanta\'s <a href=\"http://www.southerncouncil.org/\">Southern Regional Council.</a> He also served as a journalist-in-residence at Virginia Polytechnic Institute and State University and a lecturer in American studies at the University of Texas, Austin.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Outside journalism, Egerton is a critically acclaimed award-winning author. His books include <em>The Americanization of Dixie</em> (1974); <em>Generations</em> (1983), which won the W. D. Weatherford and Lillian Smith book awards; <a href=\"http://uncpress.unc.edu/books/T-1103.html\"><em>Southern Food</em></a> (1987), which was named Book of the Year by the International Association of Culinary Professionals; and <a href=\"http://uncpress.unc.edu/browse/book_detail?title_id=1088\"><em>Speak Now Against the Day</em></a> (1994), for which he received the Robert F. Kennedy Book Award.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Writing about his homeland was second nature to Egerton. \"The South is a large part of who I am — more than a place, it is a state of mind in constant conflict with itself. You can\'t dwell on being a Southerner for long without entering the conflict — and if there\'s an exit from it, I haven\'t found it yet.\"</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Egerton is one of the founders of the <a href=\"http://southernfoodways.org/\">Southern Foodways Alliance</a> in the Center for the Study of Southern Culture at the University of Mississippi, which established&nbsp;the John Egerton Prize in 2007 to recognize artists, writers, scholars and others, including artisans and farmers, whose work in the American South addresses issues of race, class, gender, and social and environmental justice, through the lens of food.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Egerton has also written and edited two books of history and photography about his adopted home city, Nashville, and one work of fiction, <em><a href=\"http://www.newsouthbooks.com/bkpgs/detailtitle.php?isbn_solid=1588382028\">Ali Dubyiah and the Forty Thieves</a>, </em>a political satire, which was published in 2006. Egerton is a member of the <a href=\"http://jat.uky.edu/ky-journalism-hall-of-fame.html\">Kentucky Journalism Hall of Fame</a> and the UK Alumni Association\'s <a href=\"http://www.ukalumni.net/s/1052/semi-blank-noimg.aspx?sid=1052&amp;gid=1&amp;pgid=1484\">Hall of Distinguished Alumni</a>.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>As Kentucky’s premiere research library and one of the leading academic libraries in the United States, UK Libraries provides the foundation for student learning and faculty teaching and research.&nbsp;UK Libraries provides access to a wealth of information critical to academic success, including online books, journals, databases, unique collections and more.&nbsp;<a href=\"http://libraries.uky.edu/WTYL\">William T. Young Library</a>&nbsp;is open 24/5 with space for more than 4,000 patrons to study in quiet or participate in active group learning.&nbsp;The faculty and staff in Young Library and our nine branch libraries are committed to meeting today’s information needs across the Commonwealth.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>MEDIA CONTACT:&nbsp;</strong>Whitney Hale,&nbsp;<span style=\"white-space: nowrap;\" class=\"baec5a81-e4d6-4674-97f3-e9220f0136c1\">(859) 257-8716<a style=\"margin: 0px; border: currentColor; left: 0px; top: 0px; width: 16px; height: 16px; right: 0px; bottom: 0px; overflow: hidden; vertical-align: middle; float: none; display: inline; position: static !important;\" title=\"Call: (859) 257-8716\" href=\"#\"><img style=\"margin: 0px; border: currentColor; left: 0px; top: 0px; width: 16px; height: 16px; right: 0px; bottom: 0px; overflow: hidden; vertical-align: middle; float: none; display: inline; position: static !important;\" title=\"Call: (859) 257-8716\" src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" /></a></span><a title=\"Call: (859) 257-8716\" href=\"http://uknow.uky.edu/content/uk-libraries-celebrates-asia-center%E2%80%99s-10th-anniversary-origami#\"><img style=\"border: currentColor; width: 16px; height: 16px; vertical-align: middle; float: none;\" title=\"Call: (859) 257-8716\" src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" /></a>;&nbsp;<a href=\"mailto:whitney.hale@uky.edu\">whitney.hale@uky.edu</a></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>In memory of the 2011 Award for Intellectual Achievement recipient, Lexington artist Adalin Wichman, UK Louie B. <!--break--><p><strong>LEXINGTON, Ky. (April 16, 2013)</strong> — Sometimes the University of Kentucky is referred to as a campus community. In fact, if UK’s employees and students were incorporated as a town separate from the surrounding city of Lexington, they would count as the state’s fifth largest city, edging out Covington by a few hundred (approximately 41,000 to 40,640).</p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p>Like any other community, the university is vulnerable to suffering the loss of its citizens.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Since the spring of 2010, the campus has honored those that UK has lost with a simple yet touching memorial service called UK Remembers. Honoring staff, faculty, retirees, students and alumni who have died since the previous spring, UK Remembers 2013 will be held from 12:15 to 12:45 p.m. Wednesday, April 17, on the North Lawn, beside the Main Building.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>UK staff member Carl Nathe will moderate the event. (April 16, 2013)</strong> — Bet you’ve never been invited to a birthday party for a sculpture. Well, now you have.</p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p>We know it’s hard to believe (they grow up so fast these days), but the University of Kentucky’s newest celebrity statue is turning 1 this month. To celebrate, all UK faculty, staff and students are invited to a “birthday” celebration honoring Bowman, the Wildcat sculpture, from noon to 2 p.m. Thursday, April 18, at Wildcat Alumni Plaza across from Memorial Coliseum on Avenue of Champions. This special event will celebrate the one-year anniversary of Bowman’s unveiling as a campus landmark.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Birthday cake and refreshments will be served. Attendees are asked to bring a camera to take pictures with the birthday cat and check out the personalized brick pavers that make the plaza UK’s tradition of legacy.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Bowman, a 7 foot tall, 9 foot long intricately detailed bronze Wildcat sculpture, a project spearheaded by the UK Alumni Association, was unveiled to the university community April 20, 2012. Bowman’s location on Wildcat Alumni Plaza is meant to serve as a gathering place for students, alumni and friends of the university as well as a friendly ambassador to campus visitors. In the fall of 2012, UK students voted to name the sculpture Bowman in honor of John Bowman, a lawyer and educator in 19th century Kentucky, who was the founder of what is now the University of Kentucky. &nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>For more information about Wildcat Alumni Plaza, visit <a href=\"http://www.ukalumni.net/wildcatalumniplaza\">www.ukalumni.net/wildcatalumniplaza</a> or follow Bowman on Twitter at <a href=\"http://www.twitter.com/wildcatbowman\">www.twitter.com/wildcatbowman</a></p><p>&nbsp;</p>',1366062445,'29838 at http://uknow.uky.edu'),(29,1,'Three Candidates for UK Provost Announced','http://uknow.uky.edu/content/three-candidates-uk-provost-announced','jay blanton','<span class=\"sw_img_wrap\"><a class=\"sw_img_a\" href=\"http://uknow.uky.edu/sites/default/files/provost_candidate_trio_2.jpg\"><img class=\"sw_img\" src=\"http://uknow.uky.edu/sites/default/files/imagecache/ctac_thumb/provost_candidate_trio_2.jpg\" /></a></span> <!--break--><p><strong>LEXINGTON, Ky. (April 18, 2013)</strong> –&nbsp;<a href=\"http://aaas.as.uky.edu/\">The African American and Africana Studies Program</a> (AAAS) at the <a href=\"file:///C:/Users/gsli222/AppData/Roaming/Microsoft/Word/uky.edu\">University of Kentucky</a> and the <a href=\"http://mcl.as.uky.edu/\">Department of Modern &amp; Classical Languages, Literatures and Cultures</a> (MCLLC) have combined forces to organize a special event, <em>In Search of our Hearth: Reinventing the Odyssey, </em>which will take place April 19-20 at various campus locations.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Speakers include: <a href=\"http://mcl.as.uky.edu/users/jco236\">Jacqueline Couti</a>, assistant professor of <a href=\"http://mcl.as.uky.edu/french-italian\">French and Italian studies</a>; Ebony Patterson, assistant professor of fine arts/painting; Jackie Murray, assistant professor of classics (Skidmore College); and <a href=\"https://history.as.uky.edu/users/kornbluh\">Mark Lawrence Kornbluh</a>, dean of the <a href=\"http://www.as.uky.edu/\">College of Arts and Sciences</a>.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>These events will explore the interdisciplinary nature of humanities and arts. The presentations represent current rethinking on the nature of the humanities in the 21st century. On Thursday&nbsp;<span style=\"font-family: tahoma, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">at 4:15 p.m. </span><span style=\"font-family: tahoma, sans-serif; font-size: 13px;\">in the Room 103 Main Building,&nbsp;</span>Jackie Murray will examine the connections between classical authors and writers of color. On Friday <font size=\"2\" face=\"Tahoma\">at 5 p.m. in</font>&nbsp;<span style=\"font-family: tahoma, sans-serif; font-size: 10pt;\">the Centre Theater in the Student Center,&nbsp;</span>the panelists will highlight the connections between Homer’s <em>Odyssey </em>and the diasporic black experience.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>In 1977, the renowned artist Romare Bearden created a series of collages based on the <em>Odyssey</em>. In his book <em>Romare Bearden: A Black Odyssey</em>, Robert O’Meally argues that the characters in the classic epic resonate with the African-American experience. The motif of wandering grief and the search for one’s hearth and home are paralleled in the ancient poem and in Bearden’s contemporary art.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The conclusion of Friday evening will feature black Greek organizations. Traditionally black Greek letter organizations rarely examine their connection to \"real\" black Greeks or the culture and history of Greece that acknowledges Africa\'s influence, beyond the Greek letters in the names of their organizations or memorizing the Greek alphabet. Using Romare Bearden\'s <em>Odysseus </em>series as an entry point, this event seeks to bring the artistic, academic and social aspects of black Greeks into the same space and examine the rich history, overlaps and surprises between the traditions.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p> Representatives from UK fraternities and sororities will demonstrate \"stepping\" and discuss what it means to be black and Greek in 2013. <a href=\"http://www.deltasigmatheta.org/suspension.htm\">Delta Sigma Theta</a> and <a href=\"http://www.phibetasigma1914.org/\">Phi Beta Sigma</a> are celebrating their 100 year anniversaries this year and next. These centennial celebrations are the perfect time to examine the origins of these offspring of the ancient mystery school system.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>MEDIA CONTACT:</strong> Sarah Geegan, <span style=\"white-space: nowrap;\" class=\"baec5a81-e4d6-4674-97f3-e9220f0136c1\">(859) 257-5365<a style=\"margin: 0px; border: currentColor; left: 0px; top: 0px; width: 16px; height: 16px; right: 0px; bottom: 0px; overflow: hidden; vertical-align: middle; float: none; display: inline; white-space: nowrap; position: static !important;\" title=\"Call: (859) 257-5365\" href=\"#\"><img style=\"margin: 0px; border: currentColor; left: 0px; top: 0px; width: 16px; height: 16px; right: 0px; bottom: 0px; overflow: hidden; vertical-align: middle; float: none; display: inline; white-space: nowrap; position: static !important;\" title=\"Call: (859) 257-5365\" src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" /></a></span>; sarah.geegan@uky.edu&nbsp;</p>',1366292579,'29877 at http://uknow.uky.edu'),(31,1,'International Law Firm Bingham McCutchen Opens at UK\'s Coldstream Research Campus','http://uknow.uky.edu/content/international-law-firm-bingham-mccutchen-opens-uks-coldstream-research-campus','Carl Nathe','<span class=\"sw_img_wrap\"><a class=\"sw_img_a\" href=\"http://uknow.uky.edu/sites/default/files/coldstream_home-banner-1a.jpg\"><img class=\"sw_img\" src=\"http://uknow.uky.edu/sites/default/files/imagecache/ctac_thumb/coldstream_home-banner-1a.jpg\" /></a></span> <!--break--><p><strong>LEXINGTON, Ky. (April 18, 2013)</strong> — Governor Steve Beshear today joined local leaders and officials from Bingham McCutchen LLP for a ribbon-cutting and grand opening ceremony at the ‘Bingham Building’ in the University of Kentucky’s <a href=\"http://www.uky.edu/coldstream/\">Coldstream Research Campus</a> Business Park in Lexington.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>“Bingham McCutchen is a company with a rich history and a promising future,” said Gov. Beshear. “Today’s ribbon-cutting represents the unlimited potential for Bingham’s success in Lexington, and we know this will be a perfect fit for the Commonwealth and the firm.”</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Bingham handles various legal issues for Fortune 100 companies and financial service firms. The global company has 1,000 lawyers and 900 staff employees in 14 major offices across the world.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>“The winner’s circle is more crowded here today than it will be in a couple of weeks at the Derby,” said Lexington Mayor Jim Gray. “But just as we are known as the Horse Capital of the World, we will now also be known as the place Bingham McCutchen chose over 300 other cities. We’ve crossed the finish line first in this race, and we’re ready to race again, and always to go the extra mile.”</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>University of Kentucky President Eli Capilouto joined the governor and mayor in welcoming Bingham to Lexington.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>“The University of Kentucky was excited to be a part of the attractive package that brought Bingham McCutchen to the Bluegrass,” Capilouto said. “We look forward to further developing fruitful partnerships between the people at Bingham and UK’s faculty, staff and students across several colleges and departments.”</p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p>Bingham’s 45,000-square-foot global services center in Lexington will house approximately 250 administrative support staff positions, including finance and accounting, human resources, information technology, marketing, operations, and risk management. The building includes redundant power and communications systems, multiple collaboration zones in an open-plan concept, as well as a micro-market offering fresh food and beverages.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>“As of today, Bingham’s Global Services Center is officially up and running in the Bluegrass,” said Bingham Chairman Jay Zimmerman, noting that the center will eventually house approximately 250 Bingham employees. “We look forward to being an active member of the Lexington business community.”</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Bingham Chief Operating Officer L. Tracee Whitley added that the major drivers in securing the on-time opening of the Global Services Center were the strong collaboration between Bingham and Lexington and the dedication of Bingham’s employees.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>“In addition, the significant amount of work and care invested by our employees during this transitional time has been exceptional,” said Whitley, noting that their dedication enabled the firm support operations to function seamlessly during the months while establishing the center.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>“This grand opening for the ‘Bingham Building’ at UK’s Coldstream Research Campus is good news for central Kentucky,” said Sen. (April 22, 2013) </strong>— The <a href=\"http://gatton.uky.edu/Content.asp?PageName=AUAccountancy\">Von Allmen School of Accountancy</a>, part of the <a href=\"http://www.uky.edu/\">University of Kentucky</a> <a href=\"http://gatton.uky.edu/\">Gatton College of Business and Economics</a>, is sponsoring an Honesty, Integrity, and Professionalism (HIP) event in conjunction with the establishment of a student chapter of the <a href=\"http://www.centerforpublictrust.org/\">Center for the Public Trust (CPT)</a> at UK on April 25 and 26.&nbsp;<br />&nbsp;</p><p>The HIP event will start on the evening of Thursday, April 25.&nbsp; Then, on Friday morning, keynote speaker and former HealthSouth CFO <a href=\"http://aaronbeam.net/\">Aaron Beam</a> will address Von Allmen School students, faculty, and staff on the topic of \"I should have said no.\" &nbsp;In 2002, Beam confessed to a $2.7 billion fraud against the company and served time in federal prison. &nbsp;He now travels around the country telling his story in the hopes that students will better understand how unethical behavior can become rationalized and justified.&nbsp; He also explains the serious consequences resulting from such behavior.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Other sessions at the HIP event will address additional topics such as forensic accounting, living an integrated life, the anatomy of a fraud, and the power of ethical behavior.&nbsp; These sessions will be led by nationally renowned experts including Alfonzo Alexander, president of the National Association of State Boards of Accountancy (NASBA) Center for the Public Trust, and UK accounting faculty member Jeff Payne.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>“In my industry career, I worked on a number of securities fraud investigations, and I understand the fine line between unethical behavior and what might appear to be legal behavior,\" said David Blackwell, dean of the Gatton College.&nbsp; (April 22, 2013)</strong> <strong>— </strong>Students from Shanghai University (SHU) will get a taste of the bluegrass this week as the UK <a href=\"http://american-studies.as.uky.edu/\">American Studies Program</a> in the <a href=\"http://www.as.uky.edu/\">College of Arts and Sciences</a> will host a summit for SHU students on Monday, April 22.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Shanghai University is home to one of approximately 10 <a href=\"http://uknow.uky.edu/content/uk-faculty-and-students-share-appalachian-culture-china\">American Studies Centers</a> in China. Funded by a grant from the Public Affairs Section of the U.S. Embassy in Beijing, and pioneered through a joint-venture agreement between SHU and UK, the center began operation in 2011.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><a>Since then the facility has served to emphasize the diversity of American culture and experience, to broaden Chinese understanding of American culture and to foster intellectual and cultural exchange. UK\'s primary contribution involves providing a perspective of the American South and Appalachia through symposia, lectures and other events. This partnership also facilitates Shanghai students coming to visit UK.</a></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The Shanghai student summit will take place from 3-5:30 p.m. in the Student Center, Room 363. Eighteen graduate students: 10 from SHU and eight from UK, will deliver short presentations of their research. The roundtable format invites discussion from the audience. &nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>UK professor <a href=\"https://english.as.uky.edu/users/avdool2\">Andy Doolen</a>, director the American Studies Center in Shanghai, said that events like this are central to the mission of the UK-SHU partnership.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>\"The purpose of the center is to try and counter Hollywood stereotypes of the United States by bringing them a more nuanced version of American society,\" Doolen said. \"Our center is rare because most U.S.-China exchanges revolve around business and technology, whereas this facility explores the more profound cultural connections and relationships between Kentucky, the U.S. and China.\"</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Last March and last May, the American Studies Center sent cohorts of UK students and faculty to the center to engage, interact and present their research to their counterparts in Shanghai.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>UK faculty that have presented at the center include Richard Schein and Patricia Ehrkamp from the Department of Geography; Doug Boyd, director of the Louie B. Nunn Center for Oral History; Ron Pen <a>from the School of </a>Music; Frank X Walker and Michelle Sizemore from the Department of English; Mary Anglin from the Department of Anthropology; and Arturo Alonzo Sandoval from the College of Fine Arts.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>These events will continue to facilitate the academic and cultural exchange between the University of Kentucky and Shanghai University. (April 23, 2013)</strong> <strong>— </strong>UK students Anil Erol, Holly Poore and Heidi Vollrath will conduct research that takes them across the globe this summer.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><a href=\"http://www.uky.edu/international/educationabroad\">Education Abroad</a> at UK&nbsp;(EA) and the&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.uky.edu/UGResearch/\">Office of Undergraduate Research</a>&nbsp;(UGR) awarded the three UK students with an <a href=\"http://www.uky.edu/UGResearch/UGRAS.html\">Undergraduate Research Abroad Scholarship (UGRAS)</a>&nbsp;to support their international independent research projects during the summer session.&nbsp;The scholarships are the result of a new collaboration between EA and UGR to support experienced undergraduate researchers as they explore their academic interests abroad &shy;– with the support of their UK faculty mentors.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p>“Research has no boundaries,” Diane Snow, director of UK’s Office of Undergraduate Research, said. “A researcher’s interests can take them across this country, or across the globe to find answers.”&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Anil Erol is a mechanical engineering student, who will complete his project, <em>Determination of Permeable &amp; Thermal Dispersion in a Porus Medium</em>, in Turkey with the support of&nbsp;Assistant Professor <a href=\"http://www.engr.uky.edu/research/researchers/haluk-karaca/\">Haluk Karaca</a>.<br />&nbsp;</p><p>Holly Poore is a psychology student, who will complete her project, <em>Improving Learning from Text: Cognitive Factors in Knowledge Acquisition Through Reading</em>, in the Netherlands with the support of&nbsp;Professor <a href=\"https://psychology.as.uky.edu/users/milich\">Richard Milich</a>.<br />&nbsp;</p><p>Heidi Vollrath is a management and pre-vet student, who will complete her project, <em>Primates are All Brain and No Brawn: An Investigation into tissue trade-offs</em>, in Spain with the support of&nbsp;Assistant Professor <a href=\"http://www.mc.uky.edu/neurobiology/research/magda.asp\"> Magdalena Muchlinski</a>.</p><p style=\"margin-left: 11.25pt;\">&nbsp;</p><p>“While these international projects will enhance the student’s research capacity here at UK, their UK mentor’s research program will also be enhanced,” Snow said.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The institutional benefit of undergraduate research is only a part of why Anthony Ogden, director of Education Abroad at UK, deems the scholarships a smart investment.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>“As a research 1 institution, we are investing in students to ensure they graduate with the knowledge and skills to engage with their discipline on the world stage,\" Ogden said. \"Conducting research abroad will help students learn the demands and rigor of their field in a way they wouldn’t at UK, or even in the U.S.”</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Ogden said that undergraduate students who participate in research abroad programs often go on to pursue graduate or professional degrees in their fields. These experiences not only foster necessary skills in a given field, but they also lay the foundation for a student’s professional network.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The UGRAS awardees are planning to pursue their research after graduation as well.</p><p>Erol hopes to continue his research at the graduate level and one day teach mechanical engineering as a professor. Poore plans to pursue a&nbsp;doctorate in clinical psychology, and Vollrath knows her anatomy research project will help make her dream of becoming a veterinarian a reality.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>For more information visit the&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.uky.edu/UGResearch/UGRAS.html\">Undergraduate Research Abroad Scholarship website</a>.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>MEDIA CONTACT:</strong> Sarah Geegan, <span style=\"white-space: nowrap;\" class=\"baec5a81-e4d6-4674-97f3-e9220f0136c1\">(859) 257-5365<a style=\"margin: 0px; border: currentColor; left: 0px; top: 0px; width: 16px; height: 16px; right: 0px; bottom: 0px; overflow: hidden; vertical-align: middle; float: none; display: inline; white-space: nowrap; position: static !important;\" title=\"Call: (859) 257-5365\" href=\"#\"><img style=\"margin: 0px; border: currentColor; left: 0px; top: 0px; width: 16px; height: 16px; right: 0px; bottom: 0px; overflow: hidden; vertical-align: middle; float: none; display: inline; white-space: nowrap; position: static !important;\" title=\"Call: (859) 257-5365\" src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" /></a></span>; <a href=\"mailto:sarah.geegan@uky.edu\">sarah.geegan@uky.edu</a></p>',1366658078,'29945 at http://uknow.uky.edu'),(39,1,'Speak Up for WUKY:  Send Testimonials, Poems, Interviews and More','http://uknow.uky.edu/content/speak-wuky-send-testimonials-poems-interviews-and-more','Kathy Johnson','<span class=\"sw_img_wrap\"><a class=\"sw_img_a\" href=\"http://uknow.uky.edu/sites/default/files/wuky_rocks_cropped_81.jpg\"><img class=\"sw_img\" src=\"http://uknow.uky.edu/sites/default/files/imagecache/ctac_thumb/wuky_rocks_cropped.jpg\" /></a></span> <!--break--><p><strong>LEXINGTON, Ky. King, where the live stream will be shown on a large screen.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>During the forums, each candidate will speak briefly and then take written questions from the audience.
