The video presentations will be archived and available on the Provost search website – <a href=\"http://www.uky.edu/Provostsearch\">www.uky.edu/Provostsearch</a> – until Friday evening.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p>',1366737805,'29970 at http://uknow.uky.edu'),(42,1,'Making a Difference in a Student\'s Life','http://uknow.uky.edu/content/making-difference-students-life','Jenny Wells','<span class=\"sw_img_wrap\"><a class=\"sw_img_a\" href=\"http://uknow.uky.edu/sites/default/files/teachers_who_made_a_difference_2_0.jpg\"><img class=\"sw_img\" src=\"http://uknow.uky.edu/sites/default/files/imagecache/ctac_thumb/teachers_who_made_a_difference_2.jpg\" /></a></span> <!--break--><p><strong>LEXINGTON, Ky. (April 24, 2013) —</strong> When she was a sophomore in high school, Danette Wilder had a problem: she was late to her biology class almost every morning. Her school was located near downtown Detroit, and traveled as much as 25 miles daily to get back and forth. In order to get to school, she had to take as many as three different buses and walk two miles.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Her biology teacher, Delois Wynne, was unaware of her situation, and was frustrated that Danette was consistently late to her class. One day, she put her foot down.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>\"She told me it was unacceptable, and was very strong about it,\" said Wilder. \"I hated knowing I had disappointed her.\"</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Wilder had looked up to Ms. Wynne from the first day of class, when she shared her personal success story with her students.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>\"She graduated high school when she was only 16 and went to college, just like Martin Luther King Jr. did,\" Wilder said. \"I was very impressed by that, and was motivated to be just like that.\"</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>In order to not be late anymore, Wilder woke up even earlier than usual to make the long journey into the city.&nbsp; One morning, when it was still dark outside, Ms. Wynne was driving to school when she noticed Wilder sitting at a bus stop.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>\"I pulled over and asked what she was doing out there so early,\" said Ms. Wynne. \"She told me she lived out that way and wanted to make sure she wasn\'t late anymore for my class. I said \'child, get in this car and let\'s go to school\' and gave her a ride. I didn\'t mean to hurt her feelings by calling her out for being late.\"</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>From that moment on, Ms. Wynne became a teacher who made a difference in Wilder\'s life.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>\"She put two and two together and realized the challenge I had getting to school,\" Wilder said. \"So from that point on, she said she\'d give me a ride. And she did - everyday for the rest of the year.\"</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>But Ms. Wynne\'s support went beyond the daily rides to school. She became what Wilder describes as \"an extension of a parent.\"</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>\"My parents were very supportive and encouraging, but they didn\'t have the educational background to guide me,\" Wilder said. \"That\'s where Ms. Wynne came in. She gave me the actual tools to succeed, kept my mind active, and encouraged me. She taught me the impact of first impressions, the importance of being on time, and that being different or standing out doesn’t make you odd — it makes you a LEADER. She really changed my life.\"</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Wilder ended up graduating second in her class, and went on to earn a degree in electrical engineering from Old Dominion University.&nbsp; Since then, she has worked for Fortune 500 companies like Toyota, Corning and Siemens, gaining valuable corporate experience.&nbsp; She then started her own business, SealingLife, Inc., which is a manufacturer and distributor of sealing, packing and assembly solutions in Lexington.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>To recognize the extraordinary influence Ms. Wynne has had on her life, Wilder will honor her this Saturday at the annual <a href=\"http://education.uky.edu/Community/TWMAD\">Teachers Who Made a Difference</a> ceremony.&nbsp; Part of the <a href=\"http://education.uky.edu/\">University of Kentucky College of Education</a>, the program gives individuals the means to thank an educator who has impacted their lives. Now in its 15th year, the program will honor more than 150 educators.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>\"When I found out she was honoring me as a \'Teacher Who Made a Difference,\' it brought tears to my eyes, I was so humbled,\" said Ms. Wynne.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Teachers Who Made a Difference is not a competition. Each year, all submissions are accepted up to a predetermined limit with each being honored that year. Also each year, the program is assisted by a spokesperson who helps get the word out. In the past, John Calipari, Dermontti Dawson, Tubby Smith, Lee T. Todd Jr., Kyle Macy, and Dan and Cheri Issel have led the charge. In 2012 and again this year, UK Women’s Basketball Coach Matthew Mitchell has served as spokesperson.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>\"There has to be someone in a child\'s life that gives them a story to motivate them,\" said Wilder. \"That\'s what Ms. Wynne did for me. She told me her life story and encouraged me to make the most of mine. You never forget those stories. I can\'t say in simple words how much I appreciate her.\"&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Ms. Wynne retired from teaching in 2008, after 43 years. She and Wilder still keep in contact.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>\"I considered my students as my little sisters and brothers — I was their big sister instead of their teacher,\" said Ms. Wynne. \"I always wanted them to go on and do more than I had done.\"</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>\"I reflect on Ms. Wynne continuously throughout my life accomplishments,\" Wilder said. \"She was supportive, a mentor and more importantly — a great role model.\"</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Submissions for the 2014 program will be accepted beginning in December 2013 at <a href=\"http://education.uky.edu/Community/TWMAD\">education.uky.edu/Community/TWMAD</a>.</p>',1366742809,'29971 at http://uknow.uky.edu'),(43,1,'Classics Students \"see blue.\" While Deciphering Medieval Scripts','http://uknow.uky.edu/content/classics-students-see-blue-while-deciphering-medieval-scripts','Sarah Geegan','<span class=\"sw_img_wrap\"><a class=\"sw_img_a\" href=\"http://uknow.uky.edu/sites/default/files/squiggles.jpg\"><img class=\"sw_img\" src=\"http://uknow.uky.edu/sites/default/files/imagecache/ctac_thumb/squiggles.jpg\" /></a></span> <!--break--><p><strong>LEXINGTON, Ky. (April 24, 2013)</strong> <strong>— </strong>For graduate students Christie Pavey and William Little, paleography doesn\'t represent something antiquated or remote, but rather something fresh and exciting.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The two&nbsp;<a href=\"https://mcl.as.uky.edu/\">Classics</a>&nbsp;students, who also participate in the&nbsp;<a href=\"https://mcl.as.uky.edu/latin-institute\">Institute for Latin Studies</a>&nbsp;at UK, were recently awarded fellowships to study abroad, in an aim to practice deciphering ancient and medieval scripts.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Though they are from very different parts of the country, both Pavey and Little decided to study at UK for the unique approach to learning that the Institute for Latin Studies provides for its students. The program is attractive because it focuses on actively reading, writing, and speaking Latin.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Pavey, who received her undergraduate degree at Calvin College in Grand Rapids, Mich., said “I was drawn to UK by the Institute for Latin Studies.&nbsp; Mastery of the Latin language was a high priority for me, especially for my future academic endeavors, so I wanted to study at a place where I could be immersed in the language.”</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Little received his undergraduate degree from Harvard University.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>“You can learn about medieval scripts and manuscripts all you like, but at the end of the day you need to have a close knowledge of the language,\" Little said. \"In fact, UK is really one of the very few places at present in the world where such opportunities can be found.”</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>This program is in part what helped both students receive their fellowships to research in other countries.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>For six weeks this summer, Pavey will study at the&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.ascsa.edu.gr/index.php/gennadius/medieval-greek-summer-session\">Gennadius Library</a>&nbsp;in Athens through the Leventis Foundation scholarship.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>“In addition to learning Medieval Greek, I&nbsp;will be learning Greek paleography,\"&nbsp;she said.&nbsp; \"That is —&nbsp;I will learn how to decipher the \'squiggles\' that medieval scribes used to record both ancient and medieval texts.”</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>She will be given close access to the manuscripts at the library which, in her words, \"will make the subject even more alive.\" She credits her success to those in the departments of Classics and&nbsp;<a href=\"https://history.as.uky.edu/\">History</a>&nbsp;at UK who have been helpful and influential to her in her studies.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Similarly, Little will be studying in Toronto for six weeks through the&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.pims.ca/academics/diploma.html\">Pontifical Institute for Mediaeval Studies</a>. At the end of the program, he will receive a diploma in manuscript studies. He explained the program as study in paleography but added that “other important and practical skills taught are codicology, dealing more with the physical construction of manuscripts; diplomatics, the study of mainly official documents from the Middle Ages; and textual editing.”</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>He wants to work toward closely and properly editing manuscripts that haven’t been given the care they deserve.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>“This program will familiarize me with the sciences that are prerequisites to a proper use of these manuscript sources,\" Little said. \"So, it will not only be enjoyable for me, but also of immediate and practical value.”</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>When asked why she enjoys studying paleography, Pavey responded, “There is little in the world better than holding and reading the same book held and read centuries ago by a scholar just like me. Discovering just who made that little twist of the pen, and why it was important to him or her. It\'s absolutely thrilling!”</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Both Pavey and Little hope to obtain doctorate degrees in the future and go on to teach at the university level.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>MEDIA CONTACT:</strong> Sarah Geegan, <span style=\"white-space: nowrap;\" class=\"baec5a81-e4d6-4674-97f3-e9220f0136c1\">(859) 257-5365<a style=\"margin: 0px; border: currentColor; left: 0px; top: 0px; width: 16px; height: 16px; right: 0px; bottom: 0px; overflow: hidden; vertical-align: middle; float: none; display: inline; white-space: nowrap; position: static !important;\" title=\"Call: (859) 257-5365\" href=\"#\"><img style=\"margin: 0px; border: currentColor; left: 0px; top: 0px; width: 16px; height: 16px; right: 0px; bottom: 0px; overflow: hidden; vertical-align: middle; float: none; display: inline; white-space: nowrap; position: static !important;\" title=\"Call: (859) 257-5365\" src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" /></a></span>; <a href=\"mailto:sarah.geegan@uky.edu\">sarah.geegan@uky.edu</a></p>',1366663222,'29952 at http://uknow.uky.edu'),(44,1,'Kentucky Leads Winter SEC Academic Honor Roll','http://uknow.uky.edu/content/kentucky-leads-winter-sec-academic-honor-roll','Carl Nathe','<span class=\"sw_img_wrap\"><a class=\"sw_img_a\" href=\"http://uknow.uky.edu/sites/default/files/uk_logo_white_stan_18.jpg\"><img class=\"sw_img\" src=\"http://uknow.uky.edu/sites/default/files/imagecache/ctac_thumb/uk_logo_white_stan.jpg\" /></a></span> <!--break--><p><strong>LEXINGTON, Ky. (April 24, 2013) — </strong>H. Dan O’Hair, interim senior vice provost for Student Success, dean of the <a href=\"http://ci.uky.edu/ci/\">College of Communication and Information</a>, and professor in the Department of Communication, was invited by the Consortium of Social Science Associations (COSSA) to speak at a congressional briefing on April 25.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The briefing, titled <em>Social Science Research on Disasters: Communication, Resilience, and Consequences</em>, will focus on risk communication, human resilience, and the social and political consequences of both natural and man-made disasters. With support from the Coalition for National Science Funding (CNSF), the House Search and Development Caucus, and other agencies, social and behavioral scientists are able to conduct important research on these tragedies and the effect on the public.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>O’Hair will be one of three scholars featured at the congressional briefing. He will speak about disaster communication and the role of message strategies during times of crises. His research examines how extreme events, media, and message strategies interact to affect human decision-making, and the impact of the media on message dissemination.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>O’Hair has published over 90 research articles and authored 15 books in the areas of communication, risk management, public relations, business communication, and terrorism. His research has been supported through several awards from the National Science Foundation, and recently includes the examination of content, channels, and comprehension of messages for the hurricane warning system. Under his leadership, the UK College of Communication and Information established a Division of Risk Sciences and now offers a Graduate Certificate in Risk Sciences for professionals seeking formal crisis planning and communication training.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>“It is a distinct honor to speak with members of Congress about the importance of our research and the role it plays in securing the health and safety of the American people,” said O’Hair. “By informing federal officials about the challenges, appropriate responses, and implications of communication during disasters, we can justify their spending and continue to develop effective strategies for saving lives.”&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>O’Hair will be joined by Roxane Cohen Silver, professor of psychology and human behavior at the University of California-Irvine, and Elizabeth Frankenburg, professor of sociology and public policy at Duke University.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>COSSA is an advocacy organization that promotes attention to and federal funding for the social and behavioral sciences. It serves as a bridge between the academic research community and the Washington policymaking community. Visit <a href=\"http://www.cossa.org/\">www.cossa.org</a> for more information on COSSA and their congressional briefings.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>MEDIA CONTACT</strong>: Erin Berger at <span style=\"white-space: nowrap;\" class=\"baec5a81-e4d6-4674-97f3-e9220f0136c1\">859-257-7805<a style=\"margin: 0px; border: currentColor; left: 0px; top: 0px; width: 16px; height: 16px; right: 0px; bottom: 0px; overflow: hidden; vertical-align: middle; float: none; display: inline; white-space: nowrap; position: static !important;\" title=\"Call: 859-257-7805\" href=\"#\"><img style=\"margin: 0px; border: currentColor; left: 0px; top: 0px; width: 16px; height: 16px; right: 0px; bottom: 0px; overflow: hidden; vertical-align: middle; float: none; display: inline; white-space: nowrap; position: static !important;\" title=\"Call: 859-257-7805\" src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" /></a></span> or <a href=\"mailto:erin.berger@uky.edu\">erin.berger@uky.edu</a>.</p><p>&nbsp;</p>',1366836125,'30003 at http://uknow.uky.edu'),(48,1,'Student Commencement Speakers Rosado, Glaser to Represent Class of 2013','http://uknow.uky.edu/content/student-commencement-speakers-rosado-glaser-represent-class-2013','Sarah Geegan','<span class=\"sw_img_wrap\"><a class=\"sw_img_a\" href=\"http://uknow.uky.edu/sites/default/files/flags_and_seats.jpg\"><img class=\"sw_img\" src=\"http://uknow.uky.edu/sites/default/files/imagecache/ctac_thumb/flags_and_seats.jpg\" /></a></span> <!--break--><p><strong>LEXINGTON, Ky. King Building.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The forum can also be seen on UKNow via live stream beginning at 4 p.m. (Requires Windows Media Player; Mac users may need to install Flip4Mac to view.)</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Riordan is a frequent national commentator on leadership development and workplace diversity. The Daniels College of Business, with about 3,000 students, is the eighth oldest business school in the country and is nationally ranked in publications such as Businessweek, The Financial Times, U.S. News &amp; World Report and Forbes.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>If capacity is reached at the forum site, an overflow room has been established in Room 205 of the Little Fine Arts Library, just across from M.I. King, where the live stream will be shown on a large screen.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>During the forum, the candidate will speak briefly and then take written questions from the audience. (April 26, 2013)</strong>&nbsp;<strong>— </strong>Kentucky’s recovery from the recent economic recession continues to be a slow one. To help Kentuckians continue to improve their finances, the University of Kentucky Managing in Tough Times (MITT) initiative is hosting the Financial Resiliency and Responsibility Conference May 16 at the Fayette County office of the UK Cooperative Extension Service.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The conference begins at 10 a.m. EDT and ends at 3 p.m.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>“The conference is designed to help community leaders work with local clientele on issues related to managing finances, financial frauds and scams, estate planning and financial issues unique to women,” said Jeanne Davis, UK extension program coordinator and co-leader of MITT.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The conference targets county extension agents and community partners who assist individuals and families with financial management and education. UK financial experts will provide research-based information about ways conference participants can help Kentuckians maximize their resources in the new economy, with the goal of aiding economic resurgence in their local communities.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>“The Financial Resiliency and Responsibility Conference offers the opportunity for educators, industry professionals and community partners to work together to meet the needs of clientele as we continue to navigate uncertain economic times,” said Jennifer Hunter, UK assistant professor for family financial management and co-leader of MITT. “The extended period of slow economic recovery has been difficult on many Kentuckians; however, helping individuals understand how current money management practices affect household financial stability can help clientele adapt to the new financial normal and promote financial stability regardless of economic conditions.”</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Becky Nash, Taylor County extension agent for family and consumer sciences, said the conference will provide important information for grassroots financial education efforts in Kentucky.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>“In a tight economy, prices are increasing while paychecks are shrinking, even disappearing,” she said. “Extension has resources to share with individuals and families to help them make the best decisions they can. The challenge is always how to get this information to folks so that they can apply it. We have to work together to get this job done.”</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Registration for the Financial Resiliency and Responsibility Conference is available at <a href=\"http://www2.ca.uky.edu/moneywise/frrc/index.htm\">http://www2.ca.uky.edu/moneywise/frrc/index.htm</a> and is limited to 100 participants. The cost is $10 per person. The team works with extension agents in every county to provide family financial management resources, teaching tools and modules and Web-based resources including social media.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The Fayette County Cooperative Extension office is located at 1140 Red Mile Place in Lexington.</p><p align=\"center\">&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>CONTACT</strong>:&nbsp; Katie Pratt, 859-257-8774; Carl Nathe, 859-257-3200.</p><p>&nbsp;</p>',1366917547,'30015 at http://uknow.uky.edu'),(51,1,'Extra Trash Collection Days Added Around Campus','http://uknow.uky.edu/content/extra-trash-collection-days-added-around-campus','Gail Hairston','<span class=\"sw_img_wrap\"><a class=\"sw_img_a\" href=\"http://uknow.uky.edu/sites/default/files/trash_collection.jpg\"><img class=\"sw_img\" src=\"http://uknow.uky.edu/sites/default/files/imagecache/ctac_thumb/trash_collection.jpg\" /></a></span> <!--break--><p><strong>LEXINGTON, Ky. (April 26, 2013)</strong> — As the end of the spring semester 2013 approaches, the great exodus of students and others affiliated with the University of Kentucky officially begins.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>With the spring flowers, crops of extra trash – a broken chair, a box of throw-away kitchen gadgets, curtains that should never cover another window, old T-shirts and other miscellaneous whatever’s -- will soon start appearing on the curbs of the neighborhoods surrounding campus.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>To relieve the eyesores and prevent city fines, Lexington’s Division of Waste Management has added two extra days to their trash removal schedule in the areas marked on the attached maps. In addition to regular pick-up days, these neighborhoods will have two additional collection days, Saturday, April 27, and Saturday, May 4.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Lexington\'s Division of Waste Management arranged the extra collections \"to prevent sidewalks and streets around campus from becoming unsightly and dangerous,\" said Esther Moberly, recycling program specialist.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>\"We encourage students to continue to be good neighbors even as though move away,\" she added.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>To take advantage of this opportunity, place waste on the curb after 4 p.m. the day before, (Friday evening, April 26) and (Friday evening, May 3). Don’t forget to take advantage of the regular collection day that week in your neighborhood.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>All waste must be bagged and inside the appropriate cart. Large items can be placed on the curb besides the cart. But do not dispose of loose materials or trash in cardboard boxes left on the curb.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>You could receive a substantial fine if you leave trash on the curb <u>before</u> 4 p.m. the day before trash collection.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>If your household items – like furniture, kitchen ware, clothing and other property – are still serviceable, consider donating them to charities, like Goodwill (859-806-7951) or ReStore (859-252-2224, ext. 101).</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Please see the maps accompanying this article to see the neighborhoods affected.</p>',1366984207,'30018 at http://uknow.uky.edu'),(52,1,'A Celebration of \'Firsts\' and New Beginnings','http://uknow.uky.edu/content/celebration-firsts-and-new-beginnings','Sarah Geegan','<span class=\"sw_img_wrap\"><a class=\"sw_img_a\" href=\"http://uknow.uky.edu/sites/default/files/fristscholars2_0.jpg\"><img class=\"sw_img\" src=\"http://uknow.uky.edu/sites/default/files/imagecache/ctac_thumb/fristscholars2.jpg\" /></a></span> <!--break--><p><strong>LEXINGTON, Ky. (April 29, 2013)</strong> – While this May is the first time graduates will wear blue gowns at the <a href=\"http://www.uky.edu/Commencement/\">commencement ceremony</a>, graduating senior Anthony Cadle will be experiencing several personal \"firsts\" when he walks across the stage on May 5. Not only is he the first member of his family to graduate from college, he will also be the first graduate of the University of Kentucky\'s <a href=\"http://www.uky.edu/UGE/FirstScholars/\">First Scholars Program</a>.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"line-height: 19px;\">Cadle will graduate in three years with a Bachelor of Arts in </span><a href=\"http://www.as.uky.edu/economics\" style=\"line-height: 19px;\">Economics</a><span style=\"line-height: 19px;\"> from the </span><a href=\"http://www.as.uky.edu/\" style=\"line-height: 19px;\">College of Arts and Sciences</a><span style=\"line-height: 19px;\">&nbsp;along with minors in </span><a href=\"http://www.as.uky.edu/college-history\" style=\"line-height: 19px;\">history</a><span style=\"line-height: 19px;\"> and </span><a href=\"http://gatton.uky.edu/undergraduates/Content.asp?PageName=UBusMinor\" style=\"line-height: 19px;\">business</a><span style=\"line-height: 19px;\">. The Dayton, Ky. native has been active during his time on campus in several activities including the Leadership Development Program and in his role as a football equipment manager for the </span><a href=\"http://www.ukathletics.com/sports/m-footbl/kty-m-footbl-body.html\" style=\"line-height: 19px;\">men\'s varsity team</a><span style=\"line-height: 19px;\">.</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"line-height: 19px;\">\"I owe everything that I am and am going to be to the First Scholars Program,\" said Cadle who credits the program for providing him with many resources and mentors dedicated to making his transition to college smooth. \"It was hands down the greatest thing that ever happened to me.\"</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"line-height: 19px;\">First Scholars was initiated in 2010 through a $1.1 million grant from the Texas-based </span><a href=\"http://www.uky.edu/UGE/FirstScholars/contact.html\" style=\"line-height: 19px;\">Suder Foundation</a><span style=\"line-height: 19px;\">, an organization that strives to raise graduation rates among students whose parents have no education beyond high school.</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"line-height: 19px;\">\"I wouldn\'t say that the program \'held my hand;\' I\'m kind of a free spirit that way,\" Cadle said. \"Rather, being in First Scholars was like bowling with the guard rails up. You\'re the one throwing the ball, but you have people making sure you\'re heading in the right direction.\"</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"line-height: 19px;\">Students chosen to participate in First Scholars receive a scholarship of $5,000 per year and are required to be active on campus and participate in its mentorship program. &nbsp;</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"line-height: 19px;\">\"The program is intense. It invests a lot in its students, and therefore expects its students to return on that investment. It makes sure we take advantage of what UK has to offer,\" Cadle said.</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"line-height: 19px;\">The program not only provides academic resources, but also provides an avenue for networking with similar students. Each year, the program accepts 20 students who remain involved throughout their undergraduate careers.</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"line-height: 19px;\">\"The friends I made through the program were one of the biggest assets,\" Cadle said. \"We are a family — a close-knit community. I\'ll probably talk to these people and have friendships with them for the rest of our lives.\"</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"line-height: 19px;\">While Cadle is sad to miss senior year with his First Scholar friends, he is excited for what the future has in store.</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"line-height: 19px;\">\"I have worked my entire life for college graduation, so all of a sudden it\'s like, \'What\'s next?\' It is surreal that I am actually even here. But It is an exciting, exciting feeling,\" Cadle said.</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"line-height: 19px;\">Cadle\'s family is very excited and proud of his accomplishments, and his two younger brothers have followed in his footsteps to attend college.</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"line-height: 19px;\">Cadle hopes to pursue a career in economic analysis within the U.S. government or work for a nonprofit organization. (April 29. 2013) —</strong> University of Kentucky Information Technology (UKIT) will upgrade the Microsoft&nbsp;Live@edu&nbsp;cloud email service to Microsoft Office 365 on Tuesday, May 7.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Following this upgrade, UK students who currently have a&nbsp;Live@edu&nbsp;account will have two separate accounts: a UK-branded Microsoft Office 365 account and a personal Microsoft Account. All existing email, contacts, files, and other personal information will migrate in the transition.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>After May 7, the Microsoft Office 365 account will be used for UK-branded cloud email, contact lists, and calendars. Students will continue to use their current Live@edu&nbsp;username and password and will be able to access their email through Microsoft\'s Outlook web app, Outlook Live, or through many popular desktop and mobile email clients, including Outlook and Apple Mail. Email addresses will not change. The UK logo is not shown when logging into the Office 365 account online, but UKIT will administer this account. Account creation and password resets through the UK User Account Manager will remain the same.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Other Microsoft cloud tools and services, including SkyDrive, Messenger, and Office Web Apps, will be provided using a personal Microsoft Account. This is a free consumer account that will be automatically created using the student\'s existing&nbsp;Live@edu&nbsp;user name and password. This account is separate from the Office 365 account and will be administered by Microsoft, not UK. Students will be able to log in at&nbsp;<a href=\"https://skydrive.live.com/\">https://skydrive.live.com</a>&nbsp;to access their SkyDrive files and other Microsoft cloud-based tools and services, although file sharing within the UK domain will be discontinued. After initial set up, passwords for the Office 365 and Microsoft Accounts must be managed independently. UKIT will not have access to reset personal Microsoft Account passwords.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Newer versions of Internet Explorer and Microsoft Outlook are required to use Microsoft Office 365. Students using Internet Explorer 7 or earlier must upgrade to a newer version of Internet Explorer to use Outlook Live. Users of Microsoft Outlook 2003 or earlier desktop software must upgrade to Outlook 2007 or later.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Please note: the Microsoft Lync service for instant messaging and online meetings will continue to be available using the UK link blue account username and password. This upgrade does not affect the Microsoft Campus Agreement or software provided through&nbsp;<a href=\"http://download.uky.edu/\">http://download.uky.edu</a>.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>For more Office 365 information, visit&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.uky.edu/ukit/help/Office365FAQ\">http://www.uky.edu/ukit/help/Office365FAQ</a>&nbsp;or contact the UKIT Service Desk at 859-218-HELP (4357).</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p>',1367004562,'30025 at http://uknow.uky.edu'),(54,1,'Nicholson Wins Kentucky Literary Award','http://uknow.uky.edu/content/nicholson-wins-kentucky-literary-award','Whitney Hale','<span class=\"sw_img_wrap\"><a class=\"sw_img_a\" href=\"http://uknow.uky.edu/sites/default/files/cropped_the_kentucky_derby_colon_how_the_run_for_the_roses_became_americas_premier_sporting_event_by_james_c._nicholson.jpg\"><img class=\"sw_img\" src=\"http://uknow.uky.edu/sites/default/files/imagecache/ctac_thumb/cropped_the_kentucky_derby_colon_how_the_run_for_the_roses_became_americas_premier_sporting_event_by_james_c._nicholson.jpg\" /></a></span> <!--break--><p style=\"\"><strong style=\"line-height: 19px;\">LEXINGTON, Ky. (April 29, 2013)</strong><span style=\"line-height: 19px;\"> — </span><a href=\"http://www.kentuckypress.com/\" style=\"line-height: 19px;\">University Press of Kentucky</a><span style=\"line-height: 19px;\"> author James C. Nicholson, an alumnus and part-time </span><a href=\"http://history.as.uky.edu/\" style=\"line-height: 19px;\">history</a><span style=\"line-height: 19px;\"> instructor at the University of Kentucky, has been named as the recipient of the Southern Kentucky Book Fest’s </span><a href=\"http://www.sokybookfest.org/KY-Literary-Award\" style=\"line-height: 19px;\">Kentucky Literary Award</a><span style=\"line-height: 19px;\"> for his book </span><em style=\"line-height: 19px;\"><a href=\"http://www.kentuckypress.com/live/title_detail.php?titleid=2731\">The Kentucky Derby: How the Run for the Roses Became America’s Premier Sporting Event</a></em><span style=\"line-height: 19px;\">. First awarded in 2003, the Kentucky Literary Award is a celebration of Kentucky literature.</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Eligible books for the Kentucky Literary Award include those written by Kentuckians or books with a substantial Kentucky theme. The award is given to fiction and nonfiction titles in alternating years. Nicholson was announced at the “Meet the Authors” event held on April 19, the evening before the <a href=\"http://www.sokybookfest.org/About\">Southern Kentucky Book Fest</a>. This year, two other UPK titles were named among the five finalists, including <em><a href=\"http://kentuckypress.com/live/title_detail.php?titleid=3011\">A Few Honest Words: The Kentucky Roots of Popular Music</a></em> by Jason Howard and <em><a href=\"http://kentuckypress.com/live/title_detail.php?titleid=2948\">Arab and Jewish Women in Kentucky: Stories of Accommodation and Audacity</a></em> by Nora Rose Moosnick.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>In <em>The Kentucky Derby</em>, Nicholson offers a look at the evolution of the Derby as well as its international, national and regional importance. He details the Derby’s existence as an intersection of past traditions and contemporary culture, for both Kentuckians and Americans, and examines the historical, political and cultural significance of horse racing’s most famous event. Few festivals and gatherings have maintained such a delicate balance between exuberant glamor and local approachability as the Kentucky Derby—the brightest jewel of the Triple Crown.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Nicholson is also the author of the recently published <em><a href=\"http://www.kentuckypress.com/live/title_detail.php?titleid=3395\">Never Say Die: A Kentucky Colt, the Epsom Derby, and the Rise of the Modern Thoroughbred Industry</a></em>, also from University Press of Kentucky.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The University Press of Kentucky is the scholarly publisher for the Commonwealth of Kentucky, representing a consortium that now includes all of the state universities, five private colleges, and two historical societies. Led by Director Stephen Wrinn, its editorial program focuses on the humanities and the social sciences. Offices for the administrative, editorial, production and marketing departments of the press are found at UK, which provides financial support toward the operating expenses of the publishing operation.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>MEDIA CONTACT:&nbsp;</strong>Whitney Hale,&nbsp;(859) 257-8716<a href=\"http://uknow.uky.edu/content/uk-libraries-celebrates-asia-center%E2%80%99s-10th-anniversary-origami#\" title=\"Call: (859) 257-8716\"><img src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" style=\"border:currentcolor;width:16px;height:16px;vertical-align:middle;float:none;\" title=\"Call: (859) 257-8716\" /></a>;&nbsp;<a href=\"mailto:whitney.hale@uky.edu\">whitney.hale@uky.edu</a></p>',1366990469,'30020 at http://uknow.uky.edu'),(55,1,'College of Education Honors Teachers','http://uknow.uky.edu/content/college-education-honors-teachers','Jenny Wells','<span class=\"sw_img_wrap\"><a class=\"sw_img_a\" href=\"http://uknow.uky.edu/sites/default/files/dsc_0761.jpg\"><img class=\"sw_img\" src=\"http://uknow.uky.edu/sites/default/files/imagecache/ctac_thumb/dsc_0761.jpg\" /></a></span> <!--break--><p><strong>LEXINGTON, Ky. (April 30, 2013) —</strong> Since 1998, Mary Ann Vimont has overseen a program that has honored nearly 1,900 educators throughout the Commonwealth of Kentucky and across the United States. The idea was born one day when she visited a local school where she saw a large group of the school’s students sitting on the floor listening to then-University of Kentucky Head Basketball Coach Tubby Smith. Coach Smith told the students how important education and their teachers were and that if they needed anything, they could go to them. He said that they would make a difference in their lives. Vimont returned to the College of Education that day and began working on the first Teachers Who Made a Difference Program.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Fifteen years later, after honoring so many meaningful educators, Vimont was honored herself for creating a program that has meant so much to so many over the years.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>“I don’t do this for me,” Vimont said. “Tubby’s words those years ago stuck with me, and he was right. Teachers are important to us all, whether we know it or not. I knew we needed to come up with a way to let anyone honor those who have helped so much. But it means so much that my daughter, Kathryn, was here today. For the first time in my life, I’m speechless.”</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>For the 15<span style=\"font-size: 11px;\">th</span>&nbsp;anniversary program, assisted for the second consecutive year by UK Women’s Head Basketball Coach Matthew Mitchell, the UK College of Education honored more than 150 educators from 12 states for the significant influence they have had in the lives of their students.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>“The University of Kentucky College of Education prides itself on preparing great teachers,” Vimont added. “As part of our mission, we also think it is important to honor those teachers who are making a difference in the lives of their students, here in Kentucky and across the country.”</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Teachers Who Made a Difference is not a competition. Each year, all submissions are accepted up to a predetermined limit with each being honored that year. Also each year, the program is assisted by a spokesperson who helps get the word out. In the past, Dermontti Dawson, Tubby Smith, former UK President Lee T. Todd, Jr., Kyle Macy, Dan and Cheri Issel, and UK Men’s Basketball Coach John Calipari have led the charge.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Educators were invited to a breakfast reception and program at the UK Student Center Great Hall and Center Theater. Entertainment was provided by the cast of <em>Les Miserables</em> from the School for the Creative and Performing Arts in Lexington, Ky. Honorees and their guests also were treated to remarks from UK President Eli Capilouto and Coach Mitchell. The program was rounded out by the recognition of the honorees and the presentation of certificates to those in attendance.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>If you are interested in nominating a teacher for the 2014 program, submissions will be accepted beginning in December 2013 at <a href=\"http://education.uky.edu/Community/TWMAD\" title=\"http://education.uky.edu/Community/TWMAD\">http://education.uky.edu/Community/TWMAD</a>.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>The 2013 Teachers Who Made a Difference Honorees</strong></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Kentucky</strong></p><p>Robert J. Saylor, Rose Hill</p>',1367248072,'30066 at http://uknow.uky.edu'),(56,1,'Stowe Named Director of UK Ag Equine Programs','http://uknow.uky.edu/content/stowe-named-director-uk-ag-equine-programs','Carl Nathe','<span class=\"sw_img_wrap\"><a class=\"sw_img_a\" href=\"http://uknow.uky.edu/sites/default/files/167637457.jpg\"><img class=\"sw_img\" src=\"http://uknow.uky.edu/sites/default/files/imagecache/ctac_thumb/167637457.jpg\" /></a></span> <!--break--><p><strong>LEXINGTON, Ky. (April 30, 2013)</strong>&nbsp;— Jill Stowe has been named director of University of Kentucky Ag Equine Programs and Dickson Professor of Equine Science and Management effective May 1. Stowe, an associate professor within the College of Agriculture’s Department of Agricultural Economics, follows Ed Squires as the leader of the multidisciplinary equine program that serves as a gateway to all equine activities in the college.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Since her arrival at UK in 2008, Stowe has taught in the recently established and rapidly growing equine undergraduate degree program and conducted equine economic research. She led the 2012 Kentucky Equine Survey, the first comprehensive equine industry study done in Kentucky since 1977, which was implemented inpartnership with dozens of organizational partners. The project inventoried the state’s equine industry and is in the final stages of determining an economic impact of the industry to the state. Stowe also serves as faculty advisor for UK’s Dressage and Eventing Team and has served as part of the faculty leadership for UK Ag Equine Programs for the past several years.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>“It is a privilege to have the opportunity to serve this program, which has already given so much to me both professionally and personally,” Stowe said. “I am excited to be able to work alongside others on the Equine Programs team to help the program continue to reach its potential.”</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>“Having a leader such as Jill Stowe, a horsewoman and a scholar of big picture issues, such as the Kentucky Equine Survey, represents another milestone in the college’s efforts to dedicate more programs to the horse,” said Nancy Cox, associate dean for research in UK’s College of Agriculture, Kentucky Agricultural Experiment Station director and administrative leader for UK Ag Equine Programs. “Dean Smith’s original call to enhance programs for our signature industry will realize an even greater potential through Jill’s leadership.”</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Prior to joining UK, Stowe was an assistant professor in The Fuqua School of Business at Duke University. She earned her bachelor’s degree in mathematics, summa cum laude, from Texas Tech University and her doctorate in economics from Texas A&amp;M University. Her research areas of interest include equine markets, incentives in individualdecision making, decision making under risk and ambiguity and sports economics.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>“I have a number of goals that I hope to help the UK Ag Equine Programs achieve during the course of my term, and many of them focus on leveraging our rich equine opportunities, not only in this area, but also abroad. Ultimately, doing so will help UK’s equine program achieve excellence, both nationally and internationally,” Stowe said.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Stowe has been actively involved in the horse industry since she was a child, starting with local Quarter Horse show circuits, 4-H, Pony Clubs and later hunter/jumper, combined training and dressage. She currently competes in dressage shows and horse trials with her off-the-track Thoroughbred and is on the board of directors for the Lexington-based Masterson Equestrian Trust.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>“The appointment of Dr. Stowe as director of Ag Equine Programs and Dickson Professor of Equine Science and Management indicates the tremendousdiversity, and highest levels of expertise, available to the horse industry from the University of Kentucky,” said Norm Luba, executive director of the North American Equine Ranching Information Council and chair of the College of Agriculture’s UK Equine Advisory Committee.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>CONTACT</strong>:&nbsp; Holly Wiemers, (859) 257-2226.</p><p>&nbsp;</p>',1367268559,'30070 at http://uknow.uky.edu'),(57,1,'Student Parking Applications Accepted Beginning May 1','http://uknow.uky.edu/content/student-parking-applications-accepted-beginning-may-1','Carl Nathe','<span class=\"sw_img_wrap\"><a class=\"sw_img_a\" href=\"http://uknow.uky.edu/sites/default/files/2013-14_permit_collage.jpg\"><img class=\"sw_img\" src=\"http://uknow.uky.edu/sites/default/files/imagecache/ctac_thumb/2013-14_permit_collage.jpg\" /></a></span> <!--break--><p><strong>LEXINGTON, Ky. (April 30, 2013) —</strong> Student parking permit sales will begin May 1 for the 2013-2014 academic year for all University of Kentucky and Bluegrass Community and Technical College students.&nbsp;Application dates vary depending on the permit type and the student’s classification.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Students are encouraged to apply for a permit early, as permits are issued on a first-come, first-served basis. For a detailed list of application and enforcement dates, please visit the student permit calendar at <a href=\"http://www.uky.edu/pts/parking-permits_permit-calendar\">www.uky.edu/pts/parking-permits_permit-calendar</a>.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Students may apply for permits online at <a href=\"http://www.uky.edu/pts\">www.uky.edu/pts</a>, through the mail or in person at University of Kentucky Parking and Transportation Services (PTS) in Parking Structure #6 (721 Press Avenue). Printable application forms can be found at <a href=\"http://www.uky.edu/pts/help-and-resources_forms\">www.uky.edu/pts/help-and-resources_forms</a>.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Student permits will remain the same price for the upcoming academic year. Student C, R and K permits are $248 for the 2013-2014 academic year, while evening permits are $120. Students who require a motorcycle permit in addition to their vehicle permit should contact PTS directly after purchasing their permit.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>New this year, students who choose to purchase K or C6 permits will have the option of purchasing their parking permit by the semester, rather than for the entire year. The single semester permits are $124.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>All outstanding parking citations must be paid before a permit application is accepted. Citations may be paid online at <a href=\"http://www.uky.edu/pts\">www.uky.edu/pts</a>.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>To complete an online application, applicants should have on hand their correct home address, a credit card, and their license plate number. UK students must log in with their link blue ID and password; BCTC students must use their KCTCS username and password.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>If the initial permit type requested is no longer available, eligible students may submit a lottery request online for C and R permits. Eligibility criteria must be met to purchase the desired permit. Lottery drawings are typically held two to three weeks after the beginning of the semester, based on the availability of R or C spaces, and notification is sent via electronic mail.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>For more information on permits, parking on campus or to receive forms, visit <a href=\"http://www.uky.edu/pts\">www.uky.edu/pts</a>, visit Parking and Transportation Services at 721 Press Avenue (Parking Structure No. 6) or call 859-257-5757. To stay up-to-date on campus parking and transit news, follow UK Parking on Twitter at <a href=\"http://twitter.com/UKParking\">http://twitter.com/UKParking</a>, subscribe to the Parking E-News e-mail newsletter at <a href=\"http://www.uky.edu/pts\">www.uky.edu/pts</a> or tune into 1700 AM.</p><p align=\"center\">&nbsp;</p><p><strong>CONTACT: </strong>Chrissie Balding Tune, 859-257-3512; <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mHXqOP7178Y\"><img src=\"/sites/default/files/emvideo-youtube-mHXqOP7178Y.jpg\" alt=\"See video\" title=\"See video\"  width=\"425\" height=\"350\" /></a>  </object>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div></div></p><p>Video by Jenny Wells/UK Public Relations and Marketing. <a href=\"http://uknow.uky.edu/sites/default/files/matching_uk_students_with_educational_opportunities.doc \">Transcript available for download</a>.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>LEXINGTON, Ky. (April 30, 2013) —</strong>&nbsp;Each year several University of Kentucky students are recognized on a national, and even international stage, for their excellence in the classroom and research labs at the university with a variety of prestigious scholarships, internships and fellowships.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Helping UK students and recent alumni garner such honors is the mission of an office devoted to matching students to and preparing them for such valuable opportunities. The <a href=\"http://www.uky.edu/Provost/ChellgrenCenter/ExternalScholarships/index.html\">UK Office of External Scholarships</a>, under the direction of Pat Whitlow, is dedicated to working with young scholars on the application process for large scholastic prizes.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>\"My role is to listen and offer some advice, to make students aware of opportunities, to help them think about and improve their writing skills, to help them practice for interviews, so I do all of the activities that help polish them and help them present themselves in the best possible way,\" said Whitlow.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>One of the primary responsibilities of the office is to administer the campus nomination process for 12 major awards that require an institutional endorsement. For these particular opportunities, like the Truman and Rhodes Scholarships, students must apply first to a campus review committee, which will then select the students who will represent UK. Nominees receive feedback on their application and are officially nominated by the institution.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>UK\'s <a href=\"http://uknow.uky.edu/content/uk-junior-josiah-hanna-named-goldwater-scholar\">2013 Goldwater Scholar Josiah Hanna</a>, a junior majoring in <a href=\"http://www.cs.uky.edu/\">computer science</a> and <a href=\"http://math.as.uky.edu/\">mathematics</a>, felt his work with the Office of External Scholarships was invaluable in receiving his honor. \"I met with Dr. Whitlow after UK was going to nominate me. I felt like I was the only student they were working with and their only goal was for me to get this award. And, I know that is not true, because I know lots of the students working for awards and they get the same type of attention.\"</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Third year <a href=\"http://med.uky.edu/\">medical</a> student Juliana Odetunde, who is a <a href=\"http://us.fulbrightonline.org/fulbright-fogarty-fellowships-in-public-health\">Fulbright-Fogarty Fellowship</a> winner, agrees with Hanna. \"They really helped me gather all of my recommendation letters together, helped me make sure I had all the proper transcripts.\"</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>But the Office of External Scholarships doesn\'t just work with those 12 awards alone, the primary goal of the office is to recruit and prepare UK students with strong academic and extracurricular records to help them be successful in pursuing nationally competitive opportunities. They share their knowledge of the process by helping UK students find scholarships and fellowships that match their particular study and research interests funded by non-profit groups, government agencies and companies. Criteria for these honors vary but generally include academic performance, financial need, community affiliations and elements important to the sponsoring organization.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>\"There are scholarships in every field and lot of them you don\'t even know about, but that\'s one of the great things they are there for. They can definitely help you connect with opportunities in whatever field you are interested in. I wouldn\'t have even known about the Udall Scholarship if it weren\'t for Pat Whitlow and everyone at the office,\" said <a href=\"http://uknow.uky.edu/content/uk-junior-named-udall-scholar\">2013 Udall Scholar Sam Beavin</a>, a junior majoring in <a href=\"http://chem.as.uky.edu/\">chemistry</a> with an emphasis in <a href=\"http://chem.as.uky.edu/bs-degree-chemistry-biochemistry-emphasis\">biochemistry</a>.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The Office of External Scholarships can help you determine if you are eligible for a particular award, assist you in crafting a personal essay, practice for an interview, and shepherd you through the application and/or nomination process. The office\'s goal is to increase the number of UK students and alumni who apply for, and receive, these national and international awards.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>There are many scholarship opportunities that allow direct application.&nbsp;For those awards, the UK Office of External Scholarships provides advice and assistance to students preparing an application.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The process of applying for a nationally competitive scholarship is, in itself, a learning experience. It challenges the student to think through his or her career plans, to set ambitious long-term goals, and to imagine how they can use their talents to shape and change the world. In order to be a successful candidate for one of these highly competitive awards, the Office of External Scholarships recommends students begin to consider opportunities as early as freshman year, building extracurricular and leadership background, as well as participating in community and public service while maintaining a high grade point average.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>It is important to begin the scholarship preparation well before national deadlines. For the scholarships requiring university endorsement, there will be a campus deadline for receipt of materials that is typically one month prior to the final submission date.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>\"Any student in any field can think about applying for some of these awards, most of them are open to all disciplines. But, it is definitely a benefit to come in early in your academic career, and probably even early in the academic year, although we do publish all of the deadlines on our website and on <a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/ukexternalscholarships\">Facebook</a>,\" said Whitlow.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Located in 221 <a href=\"http://ukcc.uky.edu/cgi-bin/dynamo?maps.391+campus+0054\">Funkhouser Building</a>, the Office of External Scholarships is part of the <a href=\"http://www.uky.edu/UGE/\">UK Division of Undergraduate Education</a>. Students who are interested in these opportunities are encouraged to contact Whitlow, director of the Office of External Scholarships, and begin work with her well in advance of the scholarship deadline. The office plans to change its name in the coming year to Office of Nationally Competitive Awards.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>MEDIA CONTACT:&nbsp;</strong>Whitney Hale,&nbsp;(859) 257-8716<a href=\"http://uknow.uky.edu/content/play-eugene-o%E2%80%99neil%E2%80%99s-passion-love-career-wins-women-playwrights-prize#\" title=\"Call: (859) 257-8716\"><img src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" style=\"border:currentcolor;width:16px;height:16px;vertical-align:middle;float:none;\" title=\"Call: (859) 257-8716\" /></a>;&nbsp;<a href=\"mailto:whitney.hale@uky.edu\">whitney.hale@uky.edu</a></p>',1367270409,'30071 at http://uknow.uky.edu'),(59,1,'Celebrating our Newest Alumni: 146th Commencement Ceremonies','http://uknow.uky.edu/content/celebrating-our-newest-alumni-146th-commencement-ceremonies','Sarah Geegan','<span class=\"sw_img_wrap\"><a class=\"sw_img_a\" href=\"http://uknow.uky.edu/sites/default/files/20120506_166_1.jpg\"><img class=\"sw_img\" src=\"http://uknow.uky.edu/sites/default/files/imagecache/ctac_thumb/20120506_166.jpg\" /></a></span> <!--break--><p><strong>LEXINGTON, Ky. (May 1, 2012) —&nbsp;</strong>UK students will celebrate a different kind of victory in Rupp Arena on Sunday, May 5. Donning the newly adopted UK blue Commencement robes, these students will walk across the stage and officially become UK alumni. All ceremonies– the graduate and professional ceremony as well as the two undergraduate ceremonies– will take place in Rupp Arena. Graduate and professional degrees will be conferred at 9 a.m.; undergraduate degrees will be conferred at 1 p.m. and 6 p.m.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>9 a.m. —</strong> Graduate and Professional Ceremony</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>1 p.m. —</strong> Undergraduate Ceremony for the Colleges of: Agriculture; Business and Economics; Education; Engineering; and Nursing.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>6 p.m. —</strong> Undergraduate Ceremony for the Colleges of: Arts and Sciences; Communication and Information; Design; Fine Arts; Health Sciences; and Social Work.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>More than 2000 undergraduates and 500 graduate and professional students are expected to participate in Friday\'s exercises; approximately 2840 undergraduate,1040 graduate and 460 professional degrees have been submitted to the UK Board of Trustees for approval.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>All Commencement ceremonies will be live-streamed online at <a href=\"file:///C:/Users/sageeg2/Desktop/Commencement/www.uky.edu/uknow\">www.uky.edu/uknow</a>, the university’s daily news website. Videos of each ceremony will also be uploaded to the university\'s YouTube channel, during the week following Commencement.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>UK President Eli Capilouto will deliver remarks at all three ceremonies. In addition and keeping with university tradition, a student will also address the crowd at the each of the undergraduate ceremonies.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Mercedes Rosado,</strong> from Marquette, Michigan, is a graduating with a degree in kinesiology from the <a href=\"http://education.uky.edu/\">College of Education</a>. A pilot candidate in <a href=\"http://afrotc.as.uky.edu/\">Air Force ROTC</a>, she will be commissioned after graduation and begin pilot training in February at Columbus Air Force base in Mississippi. She will be giving the Commencement address at the 1 p.m. ceremony.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Rosado joined the Air Force ROTC program at UK partly because of her father\'s 20-year experience in the Air Force. She considers her future career to be ideal because it will allow her to see the world while she works.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>\"I grew up seeing my dad in the Air Force, but I never imagined that I would be the one flying the planes when I heard him talk through Air Traffic Control,\" Rosado said. \"I\'m very honored to represent my class as Commencement speaker.\"</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Luke Glaser</strong> is graduating with degrees in <a href=\"http://english.as.uky.edu/\">English</a> and <a href=\"http://hs.as.uky.edu/\">Hispanic Studies</a>, from the <a href=\"http://www.as.uky.edu/\">College of Arts and Sciences</a>. From Louisville, Kentucky, he is also a <a href=\"http://www.uky.edu/gainescenter/\">Gaines Fellow</a>, <a href=\"http://www.uky.edu/Honors/\">Honors Program</a> student, <a href=\"http://uksga.org/\">Student Government</a> senator and College of Arts and Science ambassador. He will give the Commencement address in the 6 p.m. ceremony.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>As a senior fellow with the <a href=\"http://www.uky.edu/gainescenter/\">Gaines Center for Humanities</a>, Glaser completed a two-year fellowship, working on a community jury project to create an anti-bullying play to be performed in elementary schools. As a Teach for America (TFA) Campus Community Coordinator, he works to recruit students for the Teach For America Program. He also served as an editor at <a href=\"http://kykernel.com/\">The Kentucky Kernel</a> and wrote weekly satirical column &nbsp;titled “The Lukewarm Truth.\"</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>\"It is a privilege to represent the Class of 2013 as the Commencement Speaker,\" Glaser said. \"A large portion of my speech is devoted to the accomplishments of my classmates and the magnitude of our collective impact on campus. I only hope I can do it the justice it deserves.\"</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The University of Kentucky will also award honorary doctorates to two individuals.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Robert Milton Huffaker</strong>, a native of Wayne County, Kentucky, has spent more than a half century in a varied and distinguished career as a physicist, a company founder and CEO, and a philanthropist positively impacting a number of charitable activities and organizations in the United States and abroad. He earned his Bachelor of Science in physics at the University of Kentucky in 1957, and&nbsp; worked for NASA\'s Marshall Space Flight Center where for 15 years beginning in 1961.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>In 2006, Huffaker founded Coherent Investments, LLC, where he serves as manager.&nbsp; Always eager to help others, Huffaker, a Colorado resident, is founder and chair of the board of the Forward Steps Foundation, a public charity which supports the population of youth between the ages of 18 and 21 emerging from the Colorado Foster Care System.&nbsp; While devoting his time and sharing his expertise to various charitable&nbsp; endeavors, Huffaker also has donated well over $3 million to a variety of nonprofit agencies.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Jamal Mashburn</strong> is best known for his success on the basketball court.&nbsp; An All-America selection at the University of Kentucky, Mashburn helped lead the Wildcats to the NCAA Final Four in 1993.&nbsp; He then went on to play for more than a decade in the NBA with the Dallas Mavericks, Miami Heat, and New Orleans Hornets.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>However, outside of the basketball realm, Mashburn is committed to helping others and giving back to the community.&nbsp; In 1993, before he ever signed his first professional basketball contract, he donated $500,000 to establish and endow the Jamal Mashburn Scholarship Fund at the University of Kentucky.&nbsp; The scholarship identifies ninth grade students in the Lexington, area, tracks them through high school, and then awards them a full scholarship to attend the University of Kentucky or Bluegrass Community and Technical College provided they achieve their academic and personal goals.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Mashburn also is a founding member, officer, and director of The MAP Foundation, focused on youth mentoring, and The Mashburn Family Foundation.&nbsp; This foundation offers program and support for latch-key children, as well as for children of alcoholics and single mothers.&nbsp; Both of these foundations are nonprofit 501(c)(3) corporations.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Receptions</strong></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The <a href=\"http://www.ukalumni.net/s/1052/start.aspx\">UK Alumni Association</a> will host a Commencement Reception on Sunday, May 5, from 8 a.m. - 6 p.m. in Thoroughbred Rooms 5, 6, 7.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Several colleges are holding individual receptions as well.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Receptions include:</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>College of Social Work:</strong> Honors &amp; Awards Ceremony and Graduate Recognition Program on Friday, April 26, beginning at 6 p.m. in the Student Center Ballroom</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>College of Communication &amp; Information:</strong> Sunday, May 5, from 8 p.m.-10 p.m. in the Thoroughbred Pre-Function Area</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>College of Engineering:</strong> Sunday, May 5, from 10:30 a.m.-12 p.m. in the Thoroughbred Pre-Function Area &amp; (May 1, 2013) —</strong>&nbsp;Josh Nadzam knows firsthand what it\'s like to grow up in \"the projects,\" surrounded by crime, poverty, and drug abuse.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Faced with circumstances growing up that many people can\'t imagine, Nadzam is taking his life experience and the education he has received at the University of Kentucky to build his dream of helping others in similar situations realize a better life.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Growing up in the small town of Manaca, Penn., Nadzam dreamed of escape. Entrenched in poverty, he was raised by a single mom who fought hard to give her son as normal a life as possible despite battling a mental illness that often left her hospitalized for months at a time. His father, who battled alcohol and drug addictions, was in and out of his life.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Nadzam was a three-sport athlete in high school and decided his way out was through his athletic ability. He applied to numerous Division 1 schools in hopes of receiving a scholarship. One by one, he was turned down until an offer of a walk-on position on the track and field team came from UK.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Nadzam has excelled in both academics and sports while at UK and is set to graduate May 5 with academic honors and a master\'s degree in social work from the UK <a href=\"http://www.uky.edu/SocialWork/\">College of Social Work.</a> One of his final projects in graduate school came about after a friend recommended that he read a book called <em>Make the Impossible Possible </em>by Bill Strickland, the founder and CEO of Manchester Bidwell, a nonprofit empowerment program that began in Pittsburgh and has been replicated so far in San Francisco, Cincinnati, Cleveland, Grand Rapids, and New Haven.&nbsp; Strickland has received innumerable accolades for his work. Among his honors include the Goi Peace Award, the MacArthur Fellowship, and an appointment to President Obama\'s White House Council on Community Solutions.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>\"After I read his book I had to the opportunity to meet him and exchange information,\" Nadzam said. \"After some conversation through email, I told him I wanted to make this happen in Lexington. Since then, I have worked extensively with him and his team in Pittsburgh to bring this project to reality.\"</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>There are two components of the program: a youth component and an adult component.&nbsp; The youth component is a visual arts afterschool program where at-risk and impoverished youth can enroll in various arts classes to ensure they graduate high school, empower their lives, and inspire their imaginations along the way. The adult component is a workforce development job training program for unemployed, underemployed, and displaced workers.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>\"Each of the centers are built with beautiful aesthetics and decorated with art, fresh flowers, and hand-crafted furniture with the belief that environment shapes lives,\" Nadzam said. \"If you put people in a world-class environment, they will start to feel like world-class people and aspire for the sky.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>\"At first this was just a raw dream that I was chasing.&nbsp; However, after meeting with many community leaders and organizations, I started to realize that it was very possible. A replicated version of Manchester Bidwell can fit perfectly with the compassionate organizations that already exist in Lexington.\"</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>As Nadzam\'s dream grew and his work progressed, Strickland agreed to come to Lexington to speak to community leaders, people in business and the arts, social service workers, school officials, and funders about the Manchester Bidwell project on May 21 at the Lyric Theatre in downtown Lexington.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>\"I believe so much in this type of center because I know firsthand what happens when there is no intervention, no opportunities, and no hope,\" Nadzam said. \"While I escaped, since I graduated high school in 2007, eight people I grew up with have already died from heroin overdose.&nbsp;I made it out, not everyone does. I want to do everything I can to help others avoid a life of drug abuse, rise out of the oubliettes of poverty, and unlock their potential.\"</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Although the event on May 21 is filled to capacity and now closed, a follow-up event is planned for June. For more information about this project or if you would like to donate, please visit <a href=\"http://www.gofundme.com/JoshNadzam\">www.gofundme.com/JoshNadzam</a></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>MEDIA CONTACT:</strong> Ann Blackford, 859-312-3587; <a href=\"mailto:ann.blackford@uky.edu\">ann.blackford@uky.edu</a> &nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p>',1367350244,'30080 at http://uknow.uky.edu'),(61,1,'Wing Design Competition to be Held at Lake Cumberland Regional Airport','http://uknow.uky.edu/content/wing-design-competition-be-held-lake-cumberland-regional-airport','Keith Hautala','<span class=\"sw_img_wrap\"><a class=\"sw_img_a\" href=\"http://uknow.uky.edu/sites/default/files/hrc_4531.jpg\"><img class=\"sw_img\" src=\"http://uknow.uky.edu/sites/default/files/imagecache/ctac_thumb/hrc_4531.jpg\" /></a></span> <!--break--><div><strong>LEXINGTON, Ky. (May 1, 2013) — </strong>The University of Kentucky College of Engineering will hold the third annual Kentucky Wing Design Competition on May 7, with a rain date set for May 10. The event will be held at the Lake Cumberland Regional Airport, marking the first time the competition will be open to the public.&nbsp;</div><div>&nbsp;</div><div>The competition challenges teams of high school students to design and construct a wing for a remote-controlled airplane suitable for meeting various speed and strength challenges. Schools within the Kentucky Institute for Aerospace Education (KIAE) network create teams through formal class offerings and student clubs. There are currently 15 schools within KIAE, and this will be the first year that schools can enter multiple teams in the event. Teams have been working on their aircraft since January and approximately 150 students are expected to compete.</div><div>&nbsp;</div><div>For the third straight year, the event will be coordinated by the UK College of Engineering and sponsored by NASA Kentucky. UK engineering professors supply teaching modules on aerodynamics and stability to assist teams with their wing design.&nbsp;</div><div>&nbsp;</div><div>“The hope is that the students who learn the material from the teaching modules this year will pass it on to new students next year, creating an accumulated body of knowledge that grows as it is handed down year after year,” said Jesse Hoagg, professor of mechanical engineering at UK.</div><div>&nbsp;</div><div>Tim Smith, director of KIAE, appreciates the ways in which the competition helps high school students learn engineering principles outside the classroom.</div><div>&nbsp;</div><div>“This competition inspires students with flight, but gives them a great hands-on opportunity to apply math, science and problem solving in ways they don\'t get in a classroom,” said Smith. “For NASA and Kentucky, these students are the future—whether they decide to pursue careers specifically in aviation and aerospace engineering or whether they choose another field—they will have tried something very difficult, succeeded at some aspects and learned a lot along the way.”&nbsp;</div><div>&nbsp;</div><div>For more information, please contact Tim Smith, 502-320-9490; Kellie Baker, airport manager, Lake Cumberland Regional Airport, 606-679-7908; or Jesse Hoagg, 859-218-0641.</div><div>&nbsp;</div>',1367357088,'30098 at http://uknow.uky.edu'),(62,1,'WUKY Brings Wacky NPR News Quiz to the Cinema','http://uknow.uky.edu/content/wuky-brings-wacky-npr-news-quiz-cinema','Carl Nathe','<span class=\"sw_img_wrap\"><a class=\"sw_img_a\" href=\"http://uknow.uky.edu/sites/default/files/wuky_rocks_cropped_82.jpg\"><img class=\"sw_img\" src=\"http://uknow.uky.edu/sites/default/files/imagecache/ctac_thumb/wuky_rocks_cropped.jpg\" /></a></span> <!--break--><p><strong>LEXINGTON, Ky. (May 2, 2013)</strong>&nbsp;— Rupp Arena takes on a new meaning for three members of the University of Kentucky men’s basketball team Sunday, May 5, as they participate in UK\'s 146th May&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.uky.edu/Commencement/\">Commencement</a>. Twany Beckham, Jon Hood and Jarrod Polson, all Kentucky natives, can add having a college degree to their already long list of accomplishments.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Beckham, who grew up in Louisville, will graduate with a degree in <a href=\"http://comm.uky.edu/about-us/\">communication</a> and a 3.4 grade point average. Beckham spent two years at Mississippi State before transferring to UK for his final two years of school.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>“My experience at UK has been great,” Beckham said. “I just want to thank all the coaches, especially Coach Cal (Calipari), for giving me the opportunity to come here.”</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Moving closer to home allowed him to spend more time with his mom and brothers, who he is really close to. You have to put the same time that you put into basketball into the classroom if you really want to be successful.”</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Beckham said that he prides himself on being a good student.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>“It wasn’t easy,” Hood said. “The first two years, I had a hard time with managing my time, as far as schoolwork and separating it from basketball.”</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The Madisonville native will be graduating with a degree in community <a href=\"http://www.uky.edu/Ag/CLD/\">and leadership development</a>.
