(May 2, 2013)</strong> ― University of Kentucky President Eli Capilouto Thursday announced that Dr. Christine Riordan ― current dean of the Daniels College of Business at the University of Denver ― has accepted an offer to become UK\'s next Provost.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Dr. Riordan, 48, will begin at UK this fall, subject to approval from the university\'s Board of Trustees at its May 14 meeting. She was one of three finalists for the position of Chief Academic Officer, who visited the campus last week for a series of meetings and public forums. Interim Provost Tim Tracy will return full time to his role as Dean of the College of Pharmacy.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>\"Dr. Riordan’s candidacy stood out for so many people I talked with for a number of reasons,\" Capilouto said in making the announcement. \"Her compelling communications skills, her deep understanding of higher education’s future and how she has led a college to prominence, and the sense of excitement her candidacy generated as she discussed her commitment to working collaboratively as we build upon our missions of education, research and service.\"</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Dr. Riordan will replace Kumble Subbaswamy, who left UK last year to assume the position of Chancellor at the University of Massachusetts Amherst.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>“I am honored to work with President Capilouto whose ambitious vision for the University of Kentucky and Commonwealth brought me here,” said Dr. Riordan. “The energy, strength, and commitment of the UK community are clear. It will be a privilege to serve the distinguished UK faculty, staff, students, and alumni, and become part of this outstanding institution and community.”</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>In addition to praising Tracy, who has led UK\'s efforts to implement a new values-based financial model, Capilouto also thanked the Provost Search Committee, which has led search efforts for 10 months, for its collaborative approach that \"exemplified the best of what we are as an institution – a group of scholars, professionals and outstanding students, working across disciplines in partnership to achieve an outstanding result.\"</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Provost Search Committee Co-Chairs Charley Carlson and Mike Reid said Riordan \"has both the compelling vision and the track record as a scholar and academic administrator to join President Capilouto in leading UK during both a time of tremendous challenge and opportunity. The fact that we attracted three incredibly qualified candidates is a testament to who we are as an institution and what has already been accomplished. President Capilouto has selected someone who we believe can help us build on that history to chart a new and exciting path forward for UK and the Commonwealth we serve.\"</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Dr. Britt Brockman, chairman of the university\'s Board of Trustees, said he was struck by Riordan\'s \"commitment to higher education and UK\'s potential to lead as well as her ability to help articulate a compelling vision as we move forward with a continued revitalization of our campus and transformation of how we provide education, research and service in the 21st century.\"</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>“The Provost Search Committee put in an incredible amount of collaborative work and effort, and we were gratified by the caliber of candidates who came forward, attracted to the institution and the quality of the faculty, staff and students,” said Lee Blonder, a search committee member and chair of the University Senate Council. “In Dr. Riordan, I believe we have someone who will engage with the faculty in a spirit of partnership that honors our commitment to shared governance and our shared goal to move the university forward as an institution of choice for the best undergraduate and graduate students as well as outstanding faculty researchers and teachers.”</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Dr. Riordan has experience as both a leading scholar in her discipline and as an administrator, who has excelled in creating innovative programs domestically and internationally along with sustained excellence in fundraising. Under her direction, Daniels now raises over $14 million each year in private and corporate funds. Additionally, the Daniels endowment has increased over 50 percent from $70 million (2008) to over $106 million (2013). And, they are completing a $100 million campaign for the college in 2014. She is a frequent national commentator on leadership development and workplace diversity, and was recently elected to the board of AACSB, the international accrediting association for business schools. Her articles and interviews have appeared in <em>Forbes, CNBC, Wall Street Journal, MarketWatch, CareerBuilder, Huffington Post, Politico</em>, and the <em>Harvard Business Review</em>.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The Daniels College of Business is the eighth oldest business school in the country with a global network of over 33,000 faculty, alumni, students and staff, and is internationally ranked as one of the top business schools in publications such as <em>Businessweek, The Financial Times, U.S. News &amp; World Report</em> and <em>Forbes</em>.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Founded in 1864, only a few years after the city of Denver itself, the University of Denver is one of the country\'s premier private universities and one of the oldest universities in the country.&nbsp; DU has 11,600 students, is ranked No. 83 among national universities and No. 13 for up-and-coming universities by <em>U.S. News &amp; World Report</em>, and is classified as a high research activity university by the Carnegie Foundation.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The University has more than 50 centers and institutes at DU performing highly focused research and scholarship, and is home to a broad range of colleges including the internationally ranked Korbel School of International Studies, the Sturm College of Law, the Graduate School of Social Work, the Morgridge College of Education, as well as engineering and natural sciences.&nbsp; In 2012, DU hosted the first of four presidential debates, internationally televised with over 67 million viewers throughout the world.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p>',1367509077,'30111 at http://uknow.uky.edu'),(66,1,'Six UK Students Awarded NSF Graduate Research Fellowships','http://uknow.uky.edu/content/six-uk-students-awarded-nsf-graduate-research-fellowships','Whitney Hale','<span class=\"sw_img_wrap\"><a class=\"sw_img_a\" href=\"http://uknow.uky.edu/sites/default/files/1nsflogo600_0.jpg\"><img class=\"sw_img\" src=\"http://uknow.uky.edu/sites/default/files/imagecache/ctac_thumb/1nsflogo600.jpg\" /></a></span> <!--break--><p><strong>LEXINGTON, Ky. (May 3, 2013)</strong> — Five University of Kentucky students and one recent graduate have been selected to receive government-funded National Science Foundation (NSF) Graduate Research Fellowships. The fellowships will present the students with more than $100,000 to use toward research-based master\'s or doctoral degrees.</p><p>&nbsp;<br /> The&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.nsfgrfp.org/\">NSF Graduate Research Fellowship Program</a>&nbsp;helps ensure the vitality of the human resource base of science and engineering in the United States and reinforces its diversity. The program recognizes and supports outstanding graduate students in NSF-supported science, technology, engineering and mathematics disciplines who are pursuing research-based master\'s and doctoral degrees in the U.S. and abroad.&nbsp;NSF fellows receive a three-year annual stipend of $30,000 along with a $12,000 cost of education allowance for tuition and fees, opportunities for international research and professional development, and the freedom to conduct their own research at any accredited U.S. institution of graduate education they choose.</p><p>&nbsp;<br /> UK’s newest NSF fellows are:</p><p>· Sean Michael Ehlman, a 2011 <a href=\"http://bio.as.uky.edu/biology-undergraduate-program\">biology</a> graduate;</p><p>· Paul Michael Hime, a doctoral candidate studying <a href=\"http://bio.as.uky.edu/grad-program\">biology</a>;</p><p>· Catherine \"Katie\" Nicole Kaminski, a doctoral candidate studying <a href=\"http://biochemistry.med.uky.edu/\">molecular and cellular biochemistry</a>;</p><p>· Anastasia Marie Kruse, a doctoral candidate studying <a href=\"http://www.engr.uky.edu/cme/students/graduate/\">chemical engineering</a>;</p><p>· Luis Sordo Vieira, a doctoral candidate studying <a href=\"http://math.as.uky.edu/\">mathematics</a>; and</p><p>· David Stephen Spencer, a graduating senior studying <a href=\"http://www.engr.uky.edu/cme/students/undergraduate/cme/\">chemical engineering</a>.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Ehlman, the son of Barbara and Richard Ehlman of Erlanger, Ky., is a St. Henry District High School alumnus. A graduate of UK, he is currently pursuing graduate studies in animal behavior at University of California, Davis. At UK, Ehlman was a College of Arts and Sciences Student Ambassador and an undergraduate researcher. Ehlman began to see his future in behavioral ecology as a sophomore, when he worked on a study on sparrow plumage patterns in <a href=\"http://bio.as.uky.edu/users/biodfw\">Professor David Westneat</a>’s lab. During the summer after his junior year, he had the opportunity to work as a field researcher at the <a href=\"http://www.rmbl.org/\">Rocky Mountain Biological Laboratory</a>.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>As a senior, Ehlman studied with <a href=\"http://www.uky.edu/Centers/TFCE/crowley.htm\">Professor Phil Crowley</a>, and eventually worked with Crowley and <a href=\"http://www.ca.uky.edu/forestry/cox.php\">Assistant Professor John Cox</a>, of the UK Department of Forestry, to design and implement a computer model that helps to understand the etiology of a deadly disease — White Nose Syndrome — affecting bat populations across the U.S. and Canada. \"Dr. Crowley was and continues to be a driving force in my academic career as well as a fine example of the character to which scientists should aspire,\" said Ehlman.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>After graduating from UK, Ehlman traveled to Costa Rica and worked at <a href=\"http://www.ots.ac.cr/index.php?option=com_content&amp;task=view&amp;id=162&amp;Itemid=348\">La Selva Biological Station</a> where he spent four months observing populations of the long-billed hermit hummingbird, measuring aspects of morphology and song quality. There he gained a bigger appreciation for the work of tropical field biologists.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Using his NSF Graduate Research Fellowship, Ehlman will explore how organisms may behaviorally adjust to new, human-induced changes in their environment, the subject of his dissertation. \"I aim to study how selection pressures in populations’ evolutionary histories shape current adaptability and behavior in response to human disturbance, invasive species and deforestation using the Trinidadian guppy as a study system. This small fish lives in the streams and rivers of Trinidad just north of Venezuela. Being awarded the NSF fellowship will allow me to complete extensive field studies on this small Caribbean island while still participating in science outreach and education both at my home institution and abroad.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>After graduate school, Ehlman plans on pursuing a career as a researcher and teacher while always finding balance for science outreach.<br /> &nbsp;<br /> Hime, the son of Beth and Michael Hime of Nashville, Tenn., is a 2004 biology graduate of Washington University, located in St. Louis. Before coming to UK, he served as a herpetologist and geneticist at Washington University for three years. Hime also served as an amphibian and reptile keeper and conservation biologist at <a href=\"http://www.stlzoo.org/\">St. Louis Zoological Park</a>, where he conducted field and laboratory research with amphibians.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>\"I have been passionate about studying and understanding nature from a very early age. My parents fostered this curiosity at every turn. In my undergraduate tenure, expeditions collecting lizards across the Caribbean solidified my desire to pursue evolutionary research. Four years spent working as a reptile and amphibian keeper at the St. Louis Zoo further focused the research interests I am pursuing at UK,\" Hime said.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Working with <a href=\"https://bio.as.uky.edu/users/dweis2\">Assistant Professor David Weisrock</a>, in the UK Department of Biology, Hime now has opportunities to apply recent advances in evolutionary biology and genome sequencing technologies to answer long-standing questions about the origins of biodiversity.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Hime will use his NSF Graduate Research Fellowship to support his research investigating why certain groups of organisms have many more species than other groups. \"Specifically, I aim to understand the ways in which genome evolution has constrained and promoted biodiversity in amphibians, with a special emphasis in salamanders. I am also working to use genetic analyses to help conserve the endangered hellbender salamander across Kentucky and eastern North America.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>After completing his doctorate at UK, Hime plans to pursue a career as a researcher and professor of evolutionary biology in an academic setting.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Kaminski, the daughter of Glenda and Stephen Kaminski, of Lakeland, Fla., is a 2011 biochemistry graduate of Asbury College. Prior to coming to UK, she participated in the NSF-Research Experience for Undergraduates (REU) at New Mexico Institute of Technology, where she was first exposed to biomedical research. \"I applied to and participated in this program in order to have research experience to enhance the competitiveness of my medical school application. However, as a result of this internship, which was my first exposure to biomedical research, I decided to pursue a Ph.D. degree rather than an M.D.\"</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>In the summer of 2010, Kaminski gained more research experience thanks to a Summer Undergraduate Research Fellowship at the University of Cincinnati.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Kaminski\'s work at UK has already garnered the doctoral student several accolades. She has been the recipient of a 2013 Graduate Travel Award from the American Society for Biochemistry and Molecular Biology Meeting; the 2013 Daniel R. Reedy Quality Achievement Award from the UK Graduate School; the 2013 Max Steckler Award from the UK Molecular and Cellular Biochemistry Program; a 2012 UK Graduate School Travel Award; and a 2012 NIH (National Institutes of Health) T32 Interdisciplinary Cardiovascular Training Grant.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>With her NSF Graduate Research Fellowship, Kaminski will be able to continue pursuing her research regarding the function of a family of G-proteins in regulating cardiac calcium channels under the mentorship of <a href=\"http://www.mc.uky.edu/cvrc/faculty/andres-doug/\">Douglas Andres</a>, chair of the Department of Molecular and Cellular Biochemistry. \"In the future, this award will allow me to apply for more competitive post-doctoral positions and moves me a step closer to pursuing a degree in academic science,\" said Kaminski.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>After finishing her doctoral degree in biochemistry, Kaminski will apply for a postdoctoral research position where she hopes to train future scientists.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Kruse, the daughter of Edward and Stasia Kruse of Lexington, is a Tates Creek High School alumna and 2012 graduate of UK. As an undergraduate, she served as president of the university chapter of the American Institute of Chemical Engineers (AIChE), vice president of the university chapter of Phi Sigma Rho sorority for females in engineering and the sciences, and a UK College of Engineering Ambassador. As a student, Kruse has earned more than 10 awards and fellowships including the 2012 NSF IGERT (Integrative Graduate Education and Research Traineeship) Graduate Fellowship; the 2012 Dr. Jennifer S. and Mr. Jeffery N. Quinn Graduate Fellowship; the 2012 Daniel R. Reedy Quality Achievement Fellowship; the 2012 Maurice A. Clay Leadership Award; and the 2012 UK Chemical Engineering Outstanding Senior Award. &nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>As an undergrad, Kruse\'s interest in research and graduate school was influenced by her undergraduate research experience at UK and an internship with Alltech Inc., in Nicholasville, Ky. \"This internship in an industrial laboratory helped me to gain skills and knowledge outside of traditional chemical engineering and solidified my decision to attend graduate school.\"</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The NSF Graduate Research Fellowship will allow Kruse to be independently funded throughout graduate school and to conduct research in the field of chemical engineering. Her current research project, started as part of her <a href=\"http://www.nsf.gov/funding/pgm_summ.jsp?pims_id=12759\">NSF IGERT Fellowship</a>, is in the synthesis and characterization of targeted peptide-conjugated nanoparticles for the enhancement of radiation via hyperthermia for lung cancer applications. Under the direction of <a href=\"http://www.cntc.uky.edu/faculty/kanderson/\">Gill Eminent Professor Kimberly W. Anderson</a> and <a href=\"http://www.engr.uky.edu/research/researchers/james-hilt/\">William Bryan Associate Professor J. Zach Hilt</a>, Kruse develops methods for synthesizing and characterizing iron oxide magnetic nanoparticles and mentors undergraduate research students.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>After graduate school, Kruse plans to pursue a career in drug delivery or drug development in academia or industry.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Sordo Vieira, the son of Luis F. Sordo and Nayarit Vieira of Sterling Heights, Mich., is a 2012 mathematics graduate of Wayne State University. During his undergraduate studies, he participated in an NSF-REU program at Williams College and served as a tutor to younger students in math. His interest in the field came from a grandfather who only had a fourth grade education. \"My grandfather always used to show me math tricks when I was little.\"</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Now pursuing a doctoral degree, Sordo Vieira\'s passion for mathematics only continues to grow. \"With the challenges and puzzles in mathematics, there is always one more question to be asked,\" said the Venezuelan scholar.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>At UK, Sordo Vieira has already begun to earn recognition winning a Kentucky Opportunity Fellowship and a Daniel Reedy Quality Achievement Award. As a recipient of the NSF Graduate Research Fellowship, he will use the fellowship to help fund his studies and research in number theory.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Upon completion of his doctoral degree, Sordo Vieira plans to become a professor.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Spencer, the son of Malinda and Stephen Spencer, is a 2009 Lone Oak High School graduate. A member of the <a href=\"http://www.uky.edu/Honors/\">UK Honors Program</a>&nbsp;and Alpha Phi Omega, he has served as president of the university chapter of AIChE and treasurer of the university chapter of Tau Beta Pi. A member of the 2013 Engineering Leadership Class, he was named the 2013 Outstanding Chemical Engineering Senior and received&nbsp; honorable mention recognition in 2012 by the Goldwater Scholarship organization. Spencer was a Presidential Scholarship&nbsp;and College of Engineering Scholarship recipient.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The chemical engineering senior credits his dad for sparking his interest in the field. \"My dad’s career as a chemical engineer really opened my eyes to the types of problems that chemical engineers are involved in. In addition, I have always wanted to use my abilities to help solve medical/health related problems. When my dad was diagnosed with cancer in high school, this even further cemented my desire to use my technical abilities to pursue ways to enhance therapies for diseases with low survival rates/no known cure.\"</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>In addition to his classes, Spencer was involved in undergraduate research for three years at UK under the direction of William Bryan Associate Professor J. Zach&nbsp;Hilt, of the Department of Chemical and Materials Engineering. He participated in research in the functionalization and characterization of gold and iron oxide nanoparticles in biodegradable hydrogels for biomedical applications.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Spencer plans to use his NSF Graduate Research Fellowship to fund his doctoral studies in chemical engineering at the University of Texas at Austin.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Upon completion of his doctoral studies, Spencer plans to pursue a career improving therapies for diseases with low survival rates.</p><p><br /> The NSF Graduate Research Fellowship Program is the country’s oldest graduate fellowship program directly supporting graduate students in social science and various STEM (Science, Technology, Engineering and Mathematics) fields. Since 1952, NSF has funded 48,500 Graduate Research Fellowships.&nbsp;More than 30 of them have become Nobel laureates.&nbsp;In addition, the Graduate Research Fellowship Program has a high rate of doctoral degree completion, with more than 70 percent of students completing doctorates within 11 years.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Students interested in applying for the NSF Graduate Research Fellowship can find out more information on the award at the <a href=\"http://www.uky.edu/Provost/ChellgrenCenter/ExternalScholarships/\">UK Office of External Scholarships</a>, part of the <a href=\"http://www.uky.edu/UGE/\">UK Division of Undergraduate Education</a>.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>MEDIA CONTACT</strong>:&nbsp;Whitney Hale,&nbsp;<span style=\"white-space: nowrap;\" class=\"baec5a81-e4d6-4674-97f3-e9220f0136c1\">(859) 257-8716<a style=\"margin: 0px; border: currentColor; left: 0px; top: 0px; width: 16px; height: 16px; right: 0px; bottom: 0px; overflow: hidden; vertical-align: middle; float: none; display: inline; white-space: nowrap; position: static !important;\" title=\"Call: (859) 257-8716\" src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" /></a></span><a title=\"Call: (859) 257-8716\" href=\"http://uknow.uky.edu/content/uk-libraries-celebrates-asia-center%E2%80%99s-10th-anniversary-origami#\"><img title=\"Call: (859) 257-8716\" src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" /></a>;&nbsp;<a href=\"mailto:whitney.hale@uky.edu\">whitney.hale@uky.edu</a></p>',1367521912,'30113 at http://uknow.uky.edu'),(67,1,'Final Details in Place for UK Appreciation Day','http://uknow.uky.edu/content/final-details-place-uk-appreciation-day','Gail Hairston','<span class=\"sw_img_wrap\"><a class=\"sw_img_a\" href=\"http://uknow.uky.edu/sites/default/files/fun_nite_family_3.jpg\"><img class=\"sw_img\" src=\"http://uknow.uky.edu/sites/default/files/imagecache/ctac_thumb/fun_nite_family_3.jpg\" /></a></span> <!--break--><p><strong>LEXINGTON, Ky. (May 3, 2013)</strong> — The University of Kentucky Appreciation Day Commission invites the campus community to attend UK Appreciation Day (UKAD) to demonstrate the university’s gratitude for the hard work and dedication of the staff, faculty and their families.</p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p>“In celebration of UK’s vibrant community, the commission has combined the former Staff Appreciation Day and Fun Night into UKAD to reflect the unity of our institution that we all hold so dear,” said commission Chair Jann Burks.&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>This year’s event will be held Thursday, May 16, at Commonwealth Stadium.&nbsp; Festivities will run from 1 to 4 p.m. on the stadium’s concourse and from 3 to 7 p.m. in the Blue Lot.&nbsp; Activities will include a UK T-shirt giveaway; a performance from the UK Dance Team; vendor and department prize drawings; special guest appearances, including Miss UK and Miss Kentucky; tours of the stadium suites; a carnival; live music; food and more as University Sound and Lights cranks 96.9 KISS FM.&nbsp; Plus, UK’s own Carl Nathe — voice of the Wildcats — will emcee the event.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Supervisors are encouraged to adjust schedules accordingly without requiring leave to be utilized.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>For those who enjoy the traditional exhibit fair, it will be offered again featuring displays from vendors and university departments from 1 to 4 p.m. on the concourse.&nbsp; Food will be served by Dining Services during that time at concession windows.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>At 3 p.m., the carnival, magic acts and other activities will be held in the Blue Lot.&nbsp; Dining Services will grill burgers, including a veggie option, and offer their famous BBQ pulled pork with trimmings and sides.&nbsp; At 4 p.m., live music will be performed by The Twiggenburys, a band that includes UK faculty. &nbsp;Finally, the day will close with a concert by Superfecta from 5 to 7 p.m.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>This year the commission will bring back the opportunity for people to contribute to God’s Pantry for local families in need.&nbsp; Blue bins will be available for non-perishable food items to be donated in three locations from 1 to 6 p.m.at Gate 4 and Gate 9 of the concourse and the area adjacent to Appreciation Day Commission HQ in the Blue Lot.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Parking will be available in the Blue Lot and Red Lot at no charge all day.&nbsp; Bus information is listed below with an attached map for those who choose to use PTS services. &nbsp;For UK Appreciation Day, two no-fare buses will run the following route every 15 minutes from 12:30 to 7:30 p.m. &nbsp;Signs with the Appreciation Day logo and balloons (weather permitting) will mark the stops and the special buses.</p><p style=\"margin-left: 0.75in;\">·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In front of Chandler Hospital under the clinic-hospital walkway</p><p style=\"margin-left: 0.75in;\">·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Huguelet at flashing stop sign, near clinic parking structure</p><p style=\"margin-left: 0.75in;\">·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Huguelet at University Drive</p><p style=\"margin-left: 0.75in;\">·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; University Drive at Complex Drive</p><p style=\"margin-left: 0.75in;\">·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Chandler Hospital at bus shelter between Emergency Department entrance and College of Agriculture Building</p><p style=\"margin-left: 0.75in;\">·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Commonwealth Stadium, Gate 4</p><p>A third bus — an express bus — will run between the Chandler Hospital Emergency Department bus shelter and the stadium only, between 12:30-3:30 p.m.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p align=\"center\"><strong>Appreciation Day Activities at a Glance</strong></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Welcome by President Capilouto&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; (May 5, 2013) —</strong> UK students will celebrate a different kind of victory in Rupp Arena today. Donning the newly adopted UK blue Commencement robes, students will walk across the stage and officially become UK alumni. All ceremonies – the graduate and professional ceremony as well as the two undergraduate ceremonies – will take place in Rupp Arena. Graduate and professional degrees will be conferred at 9 a.m.; undergraduate degrees will be conferred at 1 p.m. and 6 p.m.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>All Commencement ceremonies will be streamed live here, and videos of each ceremony will be uploaded to the university\'s YouTube channel, during the week following Commencement. UK cable channel 16 will also have rebroadcasts of the ceremonies.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Today\'s ceremonies are:</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>9 a.m. —</strong> Graduate and Professional Ceremony</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>1 p.m. —</strong> Undergraduate Ceremony for the Colleges of: Agriculture; Business and Economics; Education; Engineering; and Nursing.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>6 p.m. —</strong> Undergraduate Ceremony for the Colleges of: Arts and Sciences; Communication and Information; Design; Fine Arts; Health Sciences; and Social Work.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>More than 2,000 undergraduates and 500 graduate and professional students are expected to participate in today\'s exercises; approximately 2,840 undergraduate,1,040 graduate and 460 professional degrees have been submitted to the UK Board of Trustees for approval.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>UK President Eli Capilouto will deliver remarks at all three ceremonies. In addition and keeping with university tradition, a student will also address the crowd at the each of the undergraduate ceremonies.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Mercedes Rosado,</strong> from Marquette, Mich., is graduating with a degree in kinesiology from the <a href=\"http://education.uky.edu/\">College of Education</a>. A pilot candidate in <a href=\"http://afrotc.as.uky.edu/\">Air Force ROTC</a>, she will be commissioned after graduation and begin pilot training in February at Columbus Air Force base in Mississippi. She will be giving the Commencement address at the 1 p.m. ceremony.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Rosado joined the Air Force ROTC program at UK partly because of her father\'s 20-year experience in the Air Force. She considers her future career to be ideal because it will allow her to see the world while she works.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>\"I grew up seeing my dad in the Air Force, but I never imagined that I would be the one flying the planes when I heard him talk to Air Traffic Control,\" Rosado said. \"I\'m very honored to represent my class as Commencement speaker.\"</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Luke Glaser</strong> is graduating with degrees in <a href=\"http://english.as.uky.edu/\">English</a> and <a href=\"http://hs.as.uky.edu/\">Hispanic studies</a>, from the <a href=\"http://www.as.uky.edu/\">College of Arts and Sciences</a>. From Louisville, Ky., he is also a <a href=\"http://www.uky.edu/gainescenter/\">Gaines Fellow</a>, <a href=\"http://www.uky.edu/Honors/\">Honors Program</a> student, <a href=\"http://uksga.org/\">Student Government</a> senator and College of Arts and Sciences ambassador. He will give the Commencement address in the 6 p.m. ceremony.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>As a senior fellow with the <a href=\"http://www.uky.edu/gainescenter/\">Gaines Center for Humanities</a>, Glaser completed a two-year fellowship, working on a community jury project to create an anti-bullying play to be performed in elementary schools. As a Teach for America (TFA) Campus Community Coordinator, he works to recruit students for the Teach For America Program. He also served as an editor at <a href=\"http://kykernel.com/\">The Kentucky Kernel</a> and wrote a&nbsp;weekly satirical column &nbsp;titled “The Lukewarm Truth.\"</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>\"It is a privilege to represent the Class of 2013 as the Commencement speaker,\" Glaser said. \"A large portion of my speech is devoted to the accomplishments of my classmates and the magnitude of our collective impact on campus. I only hope I can do it the justice it deserves.\"</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The University of Kentucky will also award honorary doctorates to two individuals.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Robert Milton Huffaker</strong>, a native of Wayne County, Ky., has spent more than a half century in a varied and distinguished career as a physicist, a company founder and CEO, and a philanthropist positively impacting a number of charitable activities and organizations in the United States and abroad. He earned his Bachelor of Science in physics at the University of Kentucky in 1957, and&nbsp;worked for NASA\'s Marshall Space Flight Center for 15 years beginning in 1961.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>In 2006, Huffaker founded Coherent Investments, LLC, where he serves as manager.&nbsp; Always eager to help others, Huffaker, a Colorado resident, is founder and chair of the board of the Forward Steps Foundation, a public charity that supports the population of youth between the ages of 18 and 21 emerging from the Colorado Foster Care System.&nbsp; While devoting his time and sharing his expertise to various charitable&nbsp;endeavors, Huffaker also has donated well over $3 million to a variety of nonprofit agencies. &nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Huffaker will receive his honorary degree at the 9 a.m. ceremony.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Jamal Mashburn</strong> is best known for his success on the basketball court.&nbsp; An All-America selection at the University of Kentucky, Mashburn helped lead the Wildcats to the NCAA Final Four in 1993.&nbsp; He then went on to play for more than a decade in the NBA with the Dallas Mavericks, Miami Heat, and New Orleans Hornets.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>However, outside of the basketball realm, Mashburn is committed to helping others and giving back to the community.&nbsp; In 1993, before he ever signed his first professional basketball contract, he donated $500,000 to establish and endow the Jamal Mashburn Scholarship Fund at the University of Kentucky.&nbsp; The scholarship identifies ninth grade students in the Lexington area, tracks them through high school, and then awards them a full scholarship to attend the University of Kentucky or Bluegrass Community and Technical College provided they achieve their academic and personal goals.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Mashburn also is a founding member, officer, and director of The MAP Foundation, focused on youth mentoring, and The Mashburn Family Foundation.&nbsp; (May 6, 2013)</strong> — University of Kentucky President Eli Capilouto announced Tuesday a broad-based workgroup to examine and make recommendations on issues regarding student health and safety, including UK\'s alcohol policy.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>\"Colleges have a duty and responsibility to translate new knowledge into the creation and implementation of effective best practice policies to facilitate responsible alcohol use and reduce the harmful effects of alcohol misuse,\" Capilouto said in forming the 15-member workgroup. \"Universities cannot alone resolve the alcohol problems among students. Comprehensive and coordinated interventions at the individual, campus and community level are the most effective strategies.\"</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The workgroup, which will be developing a timeline for making recommendations, will be co-chaired by Robert Mock, UK\'s vice president for student affairs, and Eric Monday, the university\'s executive vice president for finance and administration.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Representatives from the city include Lexington Fayette County Councilwoman Diane Lawless and Derek Paulsen, commissioner of planning for Mayor Jim Gray. Neighborhood leader Lee Thomas, from South Hill, also is on the committee as well as representatives from Bluegrass Community and Technical College system. A list of the committee members and their charge from Capilouto can be found at <a href=\"http://www.uky.edu/President/files/Alcohol_Memo_Final.pdf\">http://www.uky.edu/President/files/Alcohol_Memo_Final.pdf</a></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Capilouto is charging the workgroup to focus on four key areas, including:</p><p>·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Assessing individual and environmental factors contributing to misuse of alcohol by students on and off campus;</p><p>·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Assessing current campus policies designed to promote the responsible use of alcohol and prevent its abuse;</p><p>·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Reviewing and evaluating new evidence and best practices to prevent alcohol abuse and reduce associated harm on and off campus; and</p><p>·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Providing summary evaluations about alternative strategies designed to prevent alcohol abuse and mechanisms for assessing the effectiveness of those strategies.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Alcohol is currently prohibited in most places on the UK campus, a longstanding policy. In recent months, as UK has undertaken an extensive process of working with neighborhood groups to form a new master plan, Capilouto was asked by some neighborhood groups and representatives to re-examine the institution\'s alcohol policy. He pledged to do so, involving a broad-based group of campus and community constituencies impacted by the current policies.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>MEDIA CONTACT: Gail Hairston, <span style=\"white-space: nowrap;\" class=\"baec5a81-e4d6-4674-97f3-e9220f0136c1\">859-257-3302<a style=\"margin: 0px; border: currentColor; left: 0px; top: 0px; width: 16px; height: 16px; right: 0px; bottom: 0px; overflow: hidden; vertical-align: middle; float: none; display: inline; white-space: nowrap; position: static !important;\" title=\"Call: 859-257-3302\" href=\"#\"><img style=\"margin: 0px; border: currentColor; left: 0px; top: 0px; width: 16px; height: 16px; right: 0px; bottom: 0px; overflow: hidden; vertical-align: middle; float: none; display: inline; white-space: nowrap; position: static !important;\" title=\"Call: 859-257-3302\" src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" /></a></span>, <a href=\"mailto:gail.hairston@uky.edu\">gail.hairston@uky.edu</a> </strong></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p>',1367593601,'30126 at http://uknow.uky.edu'),(71,1,'New Structure for Commercialization and Economic Development Units','http://uknow.uky.edu/content/new-structure-commercialization-and-economic-development-units','jay blanton','<span class=\"sw_img_wrap\"><a class=\"sw_img_a\" href=\"http://uknow.uky.edu/sites/default/files/front_gate_flowers_13.jpg\"><img class=\"sw_img\" src=\"http://uknow.uky.edu/sites/default/files/imagecache/ctac_thumb/front_gate_flowers.jpg\" /></a></span> <!--break--><p><strong>LEXINGTON, Ky. (May 6, 2013)</strong> ― University of Kentucky President Eli Capilouto has announced an administrative structure for the units previously operating under the Office of Commercialization and Economic Development.&nbsp; In streamlining the administrative structure last year to make it more efficient and effective, President Capilouto eliminated the position of vice president for commercialization and economic development.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Following that, he asked a workgroup to evaluate both the strengths and challenges of efforts in the areas of intellectual property, commercialization and economic development.&nbsp; The committee, chaired by Vice President for Research Jim Tracy, was charged with creating the administrative structure -- and reporting lines -- to focus these efforts and enhance them.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>\"These functions are a critical part of our research and land-grant mission,\" Capilouto said. \"And after several months of examination, I am pleased to announce we are moving forward with several key initiatives even as the process of evaluation and further development in these areas will continue.\"</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;Steps the president has authorized include:</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>•&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>Coldstream Research Campus will report to Executive Vice President for Finance and Administration Eric Monday.</strong> The 735-acre research park is now home to more than 65 companies, employing in excess of 1,000 employees in areas as diverse as biotechnology and equine health. The campus also plays an integral role in the city’s landscape with a 225-acre city park and nearly 2-mile section of the Legacy Trail, which connects downtown Lexington to the Kentucky Horse Park. Perhaps as important, Coldstream is self-sustaining with ground lease revenues covering operating expenses and no debt. Its potential for further real estate and business development, which will add to the healthy financial portfolio of the institution, clearly align it with UK\'s finance and administration responsibilities.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>•&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>Centers for intellectual property (IP) incubation and commercialization will report to Vice President for Research Jim Tracy.</strong> Reflecting a robust research enterprise, UK is home to a series of incubators and development vehicles for the intellectual property created by stellar faculty and staff. The question is how best to move that IP toward the commercial marketplace, benefiting both the inventor and the institution. The Advanced Science and Technology Commercialization Center (ASTeCC) comprises more than 37,000 square feet of office and laboratory space, which is designed to house research faculty and private companies. Moreover, the licensing and marketing arm for these commercialization efforts is Kentucky Technology, Inc. (KTI). Both KTI and the Intellectual Property Development Office will report to Tracy as well. Capilouto asked Tracy, as part of this alignment, to study and provide recommendations for how UK can further maximize these important efforts. The overarching questions include: do we have the appropriate staffing levels and resources identified and targeted to adequately assist our inventors in the development of their intellectual property? Are we ensuring the most appropriate mechanisms for commercial development of our intellectual property and in a way that maximizes the return on the investment the university is making?</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>•&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>Key initiatives and programs that help foster entrepreneurial efforts and small business development will report to the Gatton College of Business &amp; Economics and to the College of Agriculture.</strong> Specifically, the Von Allmen Center for Entrepreneurship will report directly to Gatton Dean David Blackwell. Von Allmen activities are supported by federal and state awards in close conjunction with the Kentucky Science and Technology Corporation. The Small Business Development Center, which administers nearly $4 million annually in local, state and federal awards, will join the Department of Agricultural Economics in the College of Agriculture to be coordinated with current community and economic development programs in Cooperative Extension.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>\"These changes create clearer reporting lines and, I believe, an administrative structure that will develop stronger synergies among all of these critical efforts,\" Capilouto said. \"But structure is only part of the equation. In the coming months, I expect recommendations that we can act upon that will further underscore our commitment in the areas of intellectual property, commercialization and economic development.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>\"These areas reflect yet one more way that the land-grant mission, so central to our identity as a university, continues to evolve and renew itself over time. In that way, and in so many others, our vibrant institution continues honor the promise that undergirded our founding nearly 150 years ago and that continues to guide us today.\"</p><p>&nbsp;</p>',1367620154,'30133 at http://uknow.uky.edu'),(72,1,'New UK Provost Named, Expected by Fall Semester','http://uknow.uky.edu/content/new-uk-provost-named-expected-fall-semester','jay blanton','<span class=\"sw_img_wrap\"><a class=\"sw_img_a\" href=\"http://uknow.uky.edu/sites/default/files/riordan_christine_headshot_1381_2_0.jpg\"><img class=\"sw_img\" src=\"http://uknow.uky.edu/sites/default/files/imagecache/ctac_thumb/riordan_christine_headshot_1381_2.jpg\" /></a></span> <!--break--><p><strong>LEXINGTON, Ky. (May 6, 2013)</strong> ― A new provost for the University of Kentucky as Christine Riordan, current dean of the Daniels College of Business at the University of Denver, has accepted UK President Eli Capilouto\'s offer to become UK\'s next <a href=\"http://www.uky.edu/Provost/\">provost</a>.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><a href=\"http://daniels.du.edu/faculty-staff/christine-riordan/\">Riordan</a>, 48, will begin at UK this fall, subject to approval from the university\'s Board of Trustees at its May 14 meeting. She was one of three finalists for the position of chief academic officer who visited the campus last week for a series of meetings and public forums. Interim Provost Tim Tracy will return full time to his role as dean of the College of Pharmacy.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>\"Dr. Riordan’s candidacy stood out for so many people I talked with for a number of reasons,\" Capilouto said in making the announcement. \"Her compelling communications skills, her deep understanding of higher education’s future and how she has led a college to prominence, and the sense of excitement her candidacy generated as she discussed her commitment to working collaboratively as we build upon our missions of education, research and service.\"</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Riordan will replace Kumble Subbaswamy, who left UK last year to assume the position of chancellor at the University of Massachusetts Amherst.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>“I am honored to work with President Capilouto whose ambitious vision for the University of Kentucky and Commonwealth brought me here,” Riordan said. “The energy, strength, and commitment of the UK community are clear. It will be a privilege to serve the distinguished UK faculty, staff, students, and alumni, and become part of this outstanding institution and community.”</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>In addition to praising Tracy, who has led UK\'s efforts to implement a new values-based financial model, Capilouto also thanked the Provost Search Committee, which has led search efforts for 10 months, for its collaborative approach that \"exemplified the best of what we are as an institution – a group of scholars, professionals and outstanding students, working across disciplines in partnership to achieve an outstanding result.\"</p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p>Provost Search Committee Co-Chairs Charley Carlson and Mike Reid said Riordan \"has both the compelling vision and the track record as a scholar and academic administrator to join President Capilouto in leading UK during both a time of tremendous challenge and opportunity. The fact that we attracted three incredibly qualified candidates is a testament to who we are as an institution and what has already been accomplished. President Capilouto has selected someone who we believe can help us build on that history to chart a new and exciting path forward for UK and the Commonwealth we serve.\"</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Dr. Britt Brockman, chairman of the university\'s Board of Trustees, said he was struck by Riordan\'s \"commitment to higher education and UK\'s potential to lead as well as her ability to help articulate a compelling vision as we move forward with a continued revitalization of our campus and transformation of how we provide education, research and service in the 21st century.\"</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>“The Provost Search Committee put in an incredible amount of collaborative work and effort, and we were gratified by the caliber of candidates who came forward, attracted to the institution and the quality of the faculty, staff and students,” said Lee Blonder, a search committee member and chair of the University Senate Council. “In Dr. Riordan, I believe we have someone who will engage with the faculty in a spirit of partnership that honors our commitment to shared governance and our shared goal to move the university forward as an institution of choice for the best undergraduate and graduate students as well as outstanding faculty researchers and teachers.”</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Riordan has experience as both a leading scholar in her discipline and as an administrator, who has excelled in creating innovative programs domestically and internationally along with sustained excellence in fundraising. Under her direction, Daniels now raises over $14 million each year in private and corporate funds. Additionally, the Daniels endowment has increased over 50 percent from $70 million (2008) to over $106 million (2013). And, they are completing a $100 million campaign for the college in 2014. She is a frequent national commentator on leadership development and workplace diversity, and was recently elected to the board of AACSB, the international accrediting association for business schools. Her articles and interviews have appeared in <em>Forbes, CNBC, Wall Street Journal, MarketWatch, CareerBuilder, Huffington Post, Politico, and the Harvard Business Review</em>.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The Daniels College of Business is the eighth oldest business school in the country with a global network of over 33,000 faculty, alumni, students and staff, and is internationally ranked as one of the top business schools in publications such as <em>Businessweek, The Financial Times, U.S. News &amp; World Report and Forbes.</em></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Founded in 1864, only a few years after the city of Denver itself, the University of Denver is one of the country\'s premier private universities and one of the oldest universities in the country.&nbsp; DU has 11,600 students, is ranked No. 83 among national universities and No. 13 for up-and-coming universities by <em>U.S. News &amp; World Report</em>, and is classified as a high research activity university by the Carnegie Foundation.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p> The University of Denver has more than 50 centers and institutes performing highly focused research and scholarship, and is home to a broad range of colleges including the internationally ranked Korbel School of International Studies, the Sturm College of Law, the Graduate School of Social Work, the Morgridge College of Education, as well as engineering and natural sciences.&nbsp; (May 7, 2013)</strong> <strong>— </strong>Earlier this semester a University of Kentucky delegation led by Interim Provost Tim Tracy visited Jilin University – one of the most prestigious “Top Ten” universities in China – with an aim to expand UK’s name recognition in China, and create new collaborative opportunities. This trip builds upon President Capilouto’s trip to Jilin University last May.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Like the University of Kentucky, Jilin University is a large comprehensive institution that includes several health care colleges, creating numerous opportunities between the two institutions.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><a href=\"http://www.uky.edu/international/node/290\">Huajing Xiu Maske</a>, director of the <a href=\"http://www.uky.edu/international/confucius_institute\">UK Confucius Institute</a>, worked closely with Jilin University to design and implement “UK Week” at Jilin University. Administrators’ Forum and various departments during the exchange week, giving Jilin University faculty the opportunity to experience UK from a disciplinary, academic vantage point.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>\"By working with China’s top comprehensive university, and identifying it as a strategic partner, UK will be able to enter a more extensive collaboration with Jilin University involving more disciplines and studies,” Maske said. “By working together in areas of faculty exchange, research collaborations and student exchange, value is added to both sides.”</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Maske was recognized with a Special Contribution Award at Jilin University for the work she has done to promote collaboration and exchanges between Chinese and American universities.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>During the visit, the UK delegation explored the ways in which a university-wide system of agreements and partnerships can be more effective than individual collaborations.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>This ties into UK’s efforts to identify strategic priorities for its international work by creating fewer but deeper partnerships according to <a href=\"http://www.uky.edu/international/node/274\">Susan Carvalho</a>, associate provost for international programs. “Partnering with Jilin University enables UK to achieve its strategic priorities for partnerships in China by focusing on a few institutions, building synergies among all players.”</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Carvalho went on to describe how this visit will also increase the number of funded research opportunities that are based on a U.S. researcher having a Chinese partner. “We hope to have our faculty get to know their counterpart faculty there, see where our strengths match up and identify new or expanded research opportunities.“</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Interim Provost Tim Tracy and the Chairman of Jilin’s University Council, Professor Chen Dewen of Jilin University, signed a memorandum of understanding laying the groundwork for a joint collaborative framework between the two universities.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>This collaborative framework opens the way for agreements between Jilin’s undergraduate public health program and UK’s graduate program in public health, a 2+2 agreement with their physics program and other potential collaborations with the colleges of Public Health, Education, Arts &amp; Sciences and Business &amp; Economics.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>“The visit underscores a partnership that will encompass a wide range of UK colleges and programs, at both the undergraduate and graduate levels,” said Carey Cavanaugh, director of the Patterson School of Diplomacy and International Commerce. “Such new academic opportunities are essential to ensure that UK students are competitive in today\'s global economy.”</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The UK delegation consisted of five deans (College of Arts and Sciences, Gatton College of Business and Economics, College of Communication and Information, College of Pharmacy, College of Education), the director of the Patterson School, the vice president for development, the associate provost for international programs and the director of the UK Confucius Institute.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>“The greatest outcome was that we cemented our status as a major U.S. partner for Jilin University,” said Gatton Dean David Blackwell. “The fact that we assembled such a large delegation from UK created a lot of synergy and accomplishment from the visit and showed our deep interest and commitment. This obviously impressed the leadership of Jilin University. If we stay focused on the relationship, I predict a strong relationship potentially involving joint academic programs, student exchanges, and faculty exchanges.”</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>MEDIA CONTACT:</strong> Sarah Geegan, <span style=\"white-space: nowrap;\" class=\"baec5a81-e4d6-4674-97f3-e9220f0136c1\">(859) 257-5365<a style=\"margin: 0px; border: currentColor; left: 0px; top: 0px; width: 16px; height: 16px; right: 0px; bottom: 0px; overflow: hidden; vertical-align: middle; float: none; display: inline; white-space: nowrap; position: static !important;\" title=\"Call: (859) 257-5365\" href=\"#\"><img style=\"margin: 0px; border: currentColor; left: 0px; top: 0px; width: 16px; height: 16px; right: 0px; bottom: 0px; overflow: hidden; vertical-align: middle; float: none; display: inline; white-space: nowrap; position: static !important;\" title=\"Call: (859) 257-5365\" src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" /></a></span>; <a href=\"mailto:sarah.geegan@uky.edu\">sarah.geegan@uky.edu</a></p>',1367855861,'30170 at http://uknow.uky.edu'),(74,1,'UK Journalism Sophomore Recipient of 2013 David Dick Storytelling Award','http://uknow.uky.edu/content/uk-journalism-sophomore-recipient-2013-david-dick-storytelling-award','Ann Blackford','<span class=\"sw_img_wrap\"><a class=\"sw_img_a\" href=\"http://uknow.uky.edu/sites/default/files/ashley_lalie2.jpg\"><img class=\"sw_img\" src=\"http://uknow.uky.edu/sites/default/files/imagecache/ctac_thumb/ashley_lalie2.jpg\" /></a></span> <!--break--><p><strong>LEXINGTON, Ky. (May 7, 2013) </strong>— Ashley Scoby, a University of Kentucky journalism sophomore from Barren County, and Meaghan Downs of <em>The Anderson News</em> in Lawrenceburg, were selected as the recipients of the 2013 David Dick \"What a Great Story!\" Storytelling Awards.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Scoby was honored for her story, “Wayne Ridge Provides Rider Programs for Autistic Children.”&nbsp; Scoby wrote the story while interning with the <em>LaRue County Herald</em> during the summer of 2012.&nbsp;&nbsp;The internship was part of an annual program sponsored by the Kentucky Press Association.&nbsp; Scoby’s winning story can be read here:&nbsp; <a href=\"http://www.laruecountyherald.com/content/wayne-ridge-provides-riding-program-autistic-children\">http://www.laruecountyherald.com/content/wayne-ridge-provides-riding-program-autistic-children</a>.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Downs won for her story “A Promise to God,” which tells the story of a Kentucky couple raising three sets of twins, all conceived through in vitro fertilization.&nbsp; Downs’ story can be read here:&nbsp; <a href=\"http://www.theandersonnews.com/content/promise-god\">http://www.theandersonnews.com/content/promise-god</a>.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Scoby and Downs were recognized prior to the annual Joe Creason Lecture in Journalism on April 23.&nbsp; David Dick’s co-author and widow, Lalie Dick, participated in the award presentation.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The UK&nbsp;<a href=\"http://jat.uky.edu/\">School of Journalism and Telecommunications</a>&nbsp;established the David Dick \"What a Great Story!\" Storytelling Award to honor the memory of David Dick, professor emeritus and former director of the school, who died in July 2010.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Dick was a champion of great journalistic storytelling. The award honors outstanding storytelling.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>In selecting the winner, the judges were looking for the best in storytelling — that which enlightens and informs while captivating the audience so they get the full story. Great storytelling can break a heart or inspire it. It can be sublime or ridiculous, but it is always memorable.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Entries could be hard news, features, advocacy journalism, personality profiles, columns and even obituaries. No matter what the form, the story needed to be well-developed and free from errors, possess sound journalistic mechanics and exhibit high ethical standards.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Two awards are given, one for a UK student journalist and the other for a professional journalist working in Kentucky.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The student award was open to UK journalism majors for work published or completed through student media, at an internship or at any recognized media outlet (radio, TV, newspaper, magazine or independently edited website).&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The professional award was for work done for any bona fide Kentucky media outlet (radio, TV, newspaper, magazine or independently edited website).</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Work published during 2012 was eligible for the 2013 awards.&nbsp; Entries for the 2014 award will be accepted through January 31, 2014 at this web address:&nbsp; <a href=\"http://jat.uky.edu/awards/daviddickstorytellingawards.html\">http://jat.uky.edu/awards/daviddickstorytellingawards.html</a>. &nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>MEDIA CONTACT:</strong>&nbsp;Ann Blackford at <span style=\"white-space: nowrap;\" class=\"baec5a81-e4d6-4674-97f3-e9220f0136c1\">859-323-6442<a style=\"margin: 0px; (May 8, 2013)</strong> — Kentucky may be horse-racing and basketball country, but when it comes to your taste buds, the Bluegrass State is a foodie haven with a rich culinary tradition. From the famed mint juleps of the Kentucky Derby to slow-smoked mutton in the western part of the state, bourbon and barbecue have deep roots in the Bluegrass State. Kentucky may be America’s first frontier, but its flavors and food traditions have lured a new wave of travelers to the region.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Three new books from the <a href=\"http://www.kentuckypress.com/\">University Press of Kentucky</a> explore the traditions and dining experiences of the Commonwealth. <em>The Kentucky Barbecue Book</em> by Wes Berry, <em>Kentucky Bourbon Whiskey: An American Heritage </em>by Michael R. Veach, and <em>The Old Fashioned: An Essential Guide to the Original Whiskey Cocktail</em> by Albert W. A. Schmid deliver a barbecue feast for readers washed down with a bourbon whiskey cocktail. This trio offers an inside look into the history of barbecue and bourbon in the state and serves as a travel guide for those in search of a taste of Kentucky.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Everyone loves a good road trip, but a quest is even better. And what quest could be more meaningful than the search for great American barbecue? In<em> <a href=\"http://www.kentuckypress.com/live/title_detail.php?titleid=3093\">The Kentucky Barbecue Book</a></em>, <a href=\"http://www.wku.edu/english/staff/wes_berry\">Wes Berry</a> does just that. A Western Kentucky University English professor by day and barbecue junkie by night, Berry hits the trail in search of the best smoke, flavor and pitmasters in Kentucky. Dining at long-established restaurants, mom and pop joints, and new barbecue dives from the Mississippi River to the Appalachian Mountains, Berry discovers the best barbecue establishments in the state and uncovers the lesser-known barbecue frontier. <em>The Kentucky Barbecue Book </em>takes readers on a belt-loosening tour of the Kentucky barbecue landscape and is a handy guide to the most succulent menus and colorful personalities in the Commonwealth.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Bourbon is known as “America’s Native Spirit,” and Kentucky folks are proud to be associated with some of the finest bourbon around. Recently named one of National Geographic’s top 10 Best Spring Trips for 2013, the Kentucky Bourbon Trail tour is a guaranteed way to experience the state’s unbridled spirit. The seven distilleries comprising the tour — Four Roses, Heaven Hill Distilleries, Jim Beam, Maker’s Mark, Wild Turkey Bourbon, Woodford Reserve and Town Branch — produce about 95 percent of the world’s bourbon. Guided tours and tastings are included at most stops, many of which are tucked away on Bluegrass State back roads.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><em><a href=\"http://www.kentuckypress.com/live/title_detail.php?titleid=2905\">Kentucky Bourbon Whiskey</a></em> and <em>The Old Fashioned </em>are perfect companions while traveling the Kentucky Bourbon Trail. In <em>Kentucky Bourbon Whiskey, </em>historian Michael R. Veach explores the history of bourbon, today’s only spirit designated by Congress as a distinctive product of the United States. Veach traces the beverage through history and explores the legends surrounding the Whiskey Rebellion, Scotch-Irish settlers, and Kentucky’s first distilling families. <em>Kentucky Bourbon Whiskey </em>shines a light on bourbon’s pivotal place in our national heritage, presenting the most complete and wide-ranging history of bourbon available.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>In <em><a href=\"http://kentuckypress.com/live/title_detail.php?titleid=3422\">The Old Fashioned</a>, </em>multi-Gourmand Award winning author <a href=\"http://albertschmid.com/\">Albert A. Schmid</a> delivers a must-read for cocktail connoisseurs. Schmid explores the history of the “original whiskey cocktail,” rumored to have originated in Louisville, Ky. The author describes the Old Fashioned’s ingredients and accessories and uncovers its curious connection to the Waldorf-Astoria Hotel, the Broadway musical scene, and the SAT college entrance examination. Schmid profiles the many people and places that have contributed to the drink’s legend since its start, and offers tips and recipes for making classic and modern variations of the Old Fashioned whiskey cocktail.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>These books offer an appetizing food and cocktail tour of Kentucky. The authors draw on personal travel experiences, extensive research and storytelling to highlight the often overlooked celebrity of Kentucky bourbon and barbecue.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The University Press of Kentucky is the scholarly publisher for the Commonwealth of Kentucky, representing a consortium that now includes all of the state universities, five private colleges, and two historical societies. Led by Director Stephen Wrinn, its editorial program focuses on the humanities and the social sciences. Offices for the administrative, editorial, production and marketing departments of the press are found at the <a href=\"http://www.uky.edu/\">University of Kentucky</a>, which provides financial support toward the operating expenses of the publishing operation.</p>',1367873386,'30173 at http://uknow.uky.edu'),(76,1,'Annual UK Shoe Drive Goes Through Friday, May 10','http://uknow.uky.edu/content/annual-uk-shoe-drive-goes-through-friday-may-10','Carl Nathe','<span class=\"sw_img_wrap\"><a class=\"sw_img_a\" href=\"http://uknow.uky.edu/sites/default/files/shoes_in_a_pile.jpg\"><img class=\"sw_img\" src=\"http://uknow.uky.edu/sites/default/files/imagecache/ctac_thumb/shoes_in_a_pile.jpg\" /></a></span> <!--break--><p><strong>LEXINGTON, Ky. (May 8, 2013)</strong> — The third annual University of Kentucky Track and Field Shoe Drive continues through Friday, May 10.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Founded by former Wildcat track competitor Josh Nadzam and current standout Luis Orta, the first two years (2011, 2012) of the drive have resulted in 5,000 pairs of shoes being collected in Lexington for people in developing countries.&nbsp; And by expanding the program throughout the Southeastern Conference last year, an additional 13,000 pairs were collected.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>\"We are collecting any kind of shoes in any condition, any size, and any gender,\" Nadzam added.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>There are on-campus collection sites at the Johnson Recreation Center, the Center for Academic and Tutorial Services (CATS, located in Memorial Coliseum), Shively Training Center (next to Cliff Hagan Baseball Stadium), and the Patterson Office Tower on the sixth floor.&nbsp; There also is an off-campus collection site at the Lexington Fayette Urban County Government (LFUCG) Center located at 200 East Main Street.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>For additional information, log on to <a href=\"http://www.uktrackandfieldshoedrive.com/\">www.uktrackandfieldshoedrive.com</a>.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p align=\"center\">&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>MEDIA CONTACT</strong>: Carl Nathe, <span style=\"white-space: nowrap;\" class=\"baec5a81-e4d6-4674-97f3-e9220f0136c1\">859-257-3200<a style=\"margin: 0px; border: currentColor; left: 0px; top: 0px; width: 16px; height: 16px; right: 0px; bottom: 0px; overflow: hidden; vertical-align: middle; float: none; display: inline; white-space: nowrap; position: static !important;\" title=\"Call: 859-257-3200\" href=\"#\"><img style=\"margin: 0px; border: currentColor; left: 0px; top: 0px; width: 16px; height: 16px; right: 0px; bottom: 0px; overflow: hidden; vertical-align: middle; float: none; display: inline; white-space: nowrap; position: static !important;\" title=\"Call: 859-257-3200\" src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" /></a></span>; <a href=\"mailto:carl.nathe@uky.edu\">carl.nathe@uky.edu</a>.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p>',1367936917,'30176 at http://uknow.uky.edu'),(77,1,'UK\'s Meilinger Named to College Football Hall of Fame','http://uknow.uky.edu/content/uks-meilinger-named-college-football-hall-fame','Carl Nathe','<span class=\"sw_img_wrap\"><a class=\"sw_img_a\" href=\"http://uknow.uky.edu/sites/default/files/meilinger.jpg\"><img class=\"sw_img\" src=\"http://uknow.uky.edu/sites/default/files/imagecache/ctac_thumb/meilinger.jpg\" /></a></span> <!--break--><p><strong>LEXINGTON, Ky. (May 8, 2013)</strong> — Steve Meilinger, a two-year first-team All-American who excelled at several positions on offense and defense for the Kentucky Wildcats, has been named to the College Football Hall of Fame as announced Tuesday by the National Football Foundation.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The event was held in New York City at the NASDAQ MarketSite.&nbsp; The ceremony was announced by Rece Davis of ESPN.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>“I thank the National Football Foundation for naming me to the Hall of Fame,” Meilinger said.&nbsp; “There are so many great players across the nation every year that don’t get honored, so I really appreciate it.”</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Meilinger played at Kentucky from 1951-53 under Coach Paul “Bear” Bryant. Meilinger helped the Wildcats to a record of 20-10-3, including an 8-4 mark in 1951 that was capped by a Cotton Bowl win over Texas Christian. UK was ranked in the nation’s top 20 all three seasons in the final Associated Press and United Press International rankings. He was a freshman (ineligible to play at that time because of NCAA rules regarding first-year players) on the 1950 Kentucky squad that went 11-1 and is the national champion according to the Sagarin Computer Ratings.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Known as “Mr. Anywhere” for the Wildcats, he split time between end, halfback and quarterback on offense; on defense, he played end, linebacker and defensive back – basically, every position on the field except the interior offensive and defensive lines, a remarkable combination.&nbsp; On special teams, he was a two-year starting punter and also returned punts and returned kickoffs.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Meilinger set Kentucky’s career records for pass receptions, receiving yardage and touchdowns with 75 catches for 1,210 yards and 16 touchdowns. He also rushed 134 times for 714 yards and five TDs and passed for 127 yards and a TD.&nbsp; On defense, no tackle stats were kept during that era but he made six pass interceptions.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Meilinger was a first-team All-American as a junior by the Newspaper Enterprise Association and the All-Players team.&nbsp; He was first-team All-America as a senior according to the NEA, American Football Coaches Association/<em>Colliers Magazine</em> and the All-America Board.&nbsp;</p><p>Ironically, the versatility that made him so valuable also hindered his bid for even more national recognition.&nbsp; As was noted in the 1953 Kentucky media guide before his senior season:</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>“One national magazine cited the Kentucky star as ‘Offensive Player of the Year.’ He missed some of the major selections apparently due to a lack of a clear majority of nominating ballots at any one position.”</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>On the league level, he was named first-team All-Southeastern Conference all three of his varsity seasons, the first of only five Wildcats in school history to be a three-time first-team All-SEC selection.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Meilinger played under Bryant, a College Football Hall of Famer, and was teammates with two Hall of Famers in quarterback Vito “Babe” Parilli and tackle Bob Gain.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>“Coach Bryant was one of the finest persons I ever met,” Meilinger said.&nbsp; “He helped me in many ways and, helped me understand the importance of all the positions I played.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>“When I came to Kentucky, he also told me that even though I was a hotshot freshman that he was in charge,” Meilinger joked.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Gain was a senior when Meilinger was a freshman, so they did not get to play in games together because of the freshman ineligibility rule.&nbsp; But Meilinger got on the field as a sophomore when Parilli was a senior, quickly becoming the Babe’s primary receiver.&nbsp; He caught a then-school-record 41 passes for 576 yards and eight TDs that season in taking the Cats to the Cotton Bowl.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>“Babe helped make me an All-American,” Meilinger said.&nbsp; “I guess I was his favorite target, and every time I see him I tell him how grateful I was for him to do that.”</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Meilinger had a wonderful ride during his four years with the Wildcats – a freshman on the Sugar Bowl champion team, a sophomore on the Cotton Bowl squad, then earning first-team All-America honors as a junior and senior.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>“I’d always dreamed of going to a bowl game, so my biggest thrill was playing in the Cotton Bowl and defeating TCU,” Meilinger said.&nbsp; “It was also a thrill to be named All-American two years in succession.&nbsp; There are so many great players, to receive that honor two years was something special.”</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Following his senior season, he played in four postseason contests, the Coaches All-America Game, College All-Star Game, East-West Shrine Game and Hula Bowl.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Meilinger was selected in the first round (eighth overall pick) of the 1954 National Football League draft.&nbsp; However, he went into the United States Army and spent two years as a Tank Commander in the 100<sup>th</sup> Tank Battalion of the 1<sup>st</sup> Armored Division.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>After missing two years of football because of military service, he returned to the gridiron in 1956 and spent six years in the NFL – 1956 and ’57 with Washington, 1958-60 for the Green Bay Packers and 1961 with the Pittsburgh Steelers – before injuries ended his career.&nbsp; In 1960, he played in the NFL Championship Game under Coach Vince Lombardi. His career stats include 60 catches for 863 yards and eight touchdowns.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Honors continued to roll in for Meilinger following his playing career. He was named to the SEC All-Quarter Century Team (1950-74) by the Birmingham Quarterback Club. He was chosen for the UK All-Time Teams for the 100<sup>th</sup> Year of Kentucky Football (1990) by the <em>Lexington Herald-Leader </em>and <em>Louisville Courier-Journal. </em>His jersey has been retired by the University of Kentucky and he was named a Living Legend of the SEC in 1999.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>In addition to his newest honor, Meilinger belongs to five other Halls of Fame:</p><ul><li>(State of) Kentucky Athletic Hall of Fame</li><li>University of Kentucky Athletic Hall of Fame</li><li>Fork Union Military Academy Hall of Fame</li><li>Lehigh Valley (Pennsylvania) Hall of Fame</li><li>Liberty High School Hall of Fame</li></ul><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Upon completion of his football days, Meilinger became a United States Marshal. He was one of the original six marshals who founded the U.S. Federal Witness Protection Program and eventually became Chief Deputy of the Eastern District of Kentucky.&nbsp; After retiring as a marshal, he became a Property Valuation Officer for the Commonwealth of Kentucky.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Originally from Bethlehem, Pa., Meilinger resides in Lexington with his wife Eileen and continues to support his alma mater.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Additional Wildcats in the College Football Hall of Fame include Gain (1947-50), Parilli (1949-51), Coach Bryant (1946-53), tackle Lou Michaels (1955-57) and Jerry Claiborne, who played at UK in 1946, ’48-49 and was head coach of the Cats from 1982-89.&nbsp; Bernie Shively, who was athletic director at UK from 1938-67 and head coach of the Cats in 1945, was inducted to the Hall of Fame in recognition of his playing days at Illinois.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Meilinger will be officially inducted into the Hall of Fame Dec. 10 in New York City during the National Football Foundation Annual Awards Dinner.&nbsp; He also will be&nbsp;honored during an enshrinement festival at the Hall of Fame in the summer of 2014.</p><p align=\"center\">&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>MEDIA CONTACTS</strong>: &nbsp;Tony Neely; <span style=\"white-space: nowrap;\" class=\"baec5a81-e4d6-4674-97f3-e9220f0136c1\">859-257-3838<a style=\"margin: 0px; border: currentColor; left: 0px; top: 0px; width: 16px; height: 16px; right: 0px;
