The Graduate and Professional Ceremony will air at 9 a.m., the Undergraduate Ceremony for the Colleges of Agriculture, Business &amp; Economics, Education, Engineering and Nursing will air at 1 p.m. and the Undergraduate Ceremony for the Colleges of Arts and Sciences, Communication and Information, Design, Fine Arts, Health Sciences and Social Work will air at 6 p.m. each of those days. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>UK Public Relations and Marketing would like to thank John Herbst and <a href=\"http://wildcatstudenttv.org/\">Wildcat Student TV</a> for their assistance in the video production and live streaming of these ceremonies.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p>',1367959781,'30186 at http://uknow.uky.edu'),(79,1,'Students Develop UK Dining App','http://uknow.uky.edu/content/students-develop-uk-dining-app','Carl Nathe','<span class=\"sw_img_wrap\"><a class=\"sw_img_a\" href=\"http://uknow.uky.edu/sites/default/files/13-05-09_uk_dining_app.jpg\"><img class=\"sw_img\" src=\"http://uknow.uky.edu/sites/default/files/imagecache/ctac_thumb/13-05-09_uk_dining_app.jpg\" /></a></span> <!--break--><p><strong>LEXINGTON, Ky. (May 9, 2013)</strong> — <a href=\"http://www.uky.edu/\">University of Kentucky</a> students now have access to nutrition information from <a href=\"http://www.uky.edu/DiningServices/\">UK Dining Services</a>, thanks to the work of students from <a href=\"http://www2.ca.uky.edu/\">UK’s College of Agriculture</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.cs.uky.edu/\">Department of Computer Science</a> in the <a href=\"http://www.engr.uky.edu/\">College of Engineering</a>.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Mallory Foster, a graduate student in the College of Agriculture’s <a href=\"http://www.ca.uky.edu/hes/?p=4\">Department of Dietetics and Human Nutrition</a>, and computer science students Keith Moyer of Vienna, Va., Rakesh Patel from India, Matt Seabold from Louisville and Randy Luecke of Marshall County have developed UK Food, a free nutrition app for menu items offered at UK’s major on-campus eateries: Ovid’s Cafe, Commons and Blazer.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Foster, from Teays Valley, W. Va., developed her idea during an undergraduate shadowing experience with Monica Fowler, a registered dietician who works with UK athletes. One of Foster’s tasks involved gathering nutrition information from campus dining and making it available to the athletes. Foster and Fowler began to wonder if they could do that for every student on campus.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>“For most students, college is the first time they are away from home, and they are going to develop habits that could potentially be with them for the rest of their lives,” Foster said. “Hopefully, this app will help them make healthier food choices.”</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>After Foster received her undergraduate degree in December 2011, she began pursuing her idea as a master’s thesis project under the advisement of Kelly Webber, assistant professor in the UK School of Human Environmental Sciences.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>“Mallory is a unique graduate student,” Webber said. “To conceptualize and implement a project of this scope in a year’s time is incredible.”</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>“Everyone eats, but the way we eat is very important to our overall health,” said Sandra Bastin, interim chair of the Department of Dietetics and Human Nutrition. “Mallory took valuable nutrition knowledge and, with the help of the computer science students, literally put the information at the fingertips of everyone on campus. It is also a perfect example of how collaborations and the use of specialty expertise can develop a worthwhile product.”</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>For the project, Foster contacted Ray Schmidt, associate director of UK Dining Services about her idea. He gave her access to the hundreds of recipes offered on campus. Foster used nutritional analysis software to get the nutritional value of each recipe, according to the appropriate serving size.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>“Mallory’s creativity and determination brought different areas of the university together for one reason, healthier students, faculty and staff, and I was impressed by the end product the computer science team created,” Schmidt said. “This app is going to increase internship possibilities in Dining Services and create student jobs as the app will have to be maintained, updated and eventually expanded to every campus dining unit.”</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Foster also contacted Jane Hayes, professor and associate chair of the UK Computer Science Department, who connected her with Moyer, Patel, Seabold and Luecke, students in her CS 499 Senior Design Project. Hayes said the goal of her class is to provide students with an experience that is as close as possible to software engineering projects they will undertake in their future careers, including interacting with clients who may or may not have computer expertise, designing interfaces for various platforms, keeping the interfaces consistent, working in numerous programming languages and environments and handling last minute changes and unexpected roadblocks.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>“Keith, Randy, Matt and Rakesh experienced many challenges throughout the semester but soldiered onward,” Hayes said. “I was particularly impressed by their determination to ensure that a working product was ready before the course ended. The payoff of their hard and excellent work can be seen in the quality of their finished product. We are very proud of this team, as well as our other CS 499 teams.”</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The computer science students wrote the code for the app. The UK Food app is available for iPhones on the App Store at <a href=\"https://myukdev.uky.edu/zAPPS/UkFoodOtaInstall/\">https://myukdev.uky.edu/zAPPS/UkFoodOtaInstall/</a>.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The goal for the app was for it to be easy to use and provide useful nutrition information to those dining on campus. The four also developed a web application to permit UK Dining Services to send announcements to students and to edit the food information.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>“Before this project, I worked on projects which had only one component,” said Patel, who graduated in December. “This project has four components. It was interesting to see how different components work&nbsp;together.”</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The app provides the nutrition information for most of the menu items in campus dining halls including calories, fat, protein, carbohydrates, vitamins and minerals. In addition, each user can put their personal health information, such as height, weight, age, gender and physical activity level into the app. It will then calculate body mass index and daily caloric needs. As students eat foods at UK Dining Services, they can select the menu item on the app and a line at the bottom of the screen, representing their daily caloric intake, will begin to fill up.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>For her master’s thesis, Foster gathered baseline data in fall 2012 from 500 students who eat in campus dining facilities concerning their knowledge, attitudes and behaviors about their diet. She’ll survey students again in the fall to see if the app has changed any of these.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p align=\"center\">&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>MEDIA CONTACT</strong>: Katie Pratt, <span style=\"white-space: nowrap;\" class=\"baec5a81-e4d6-4674-97f3-e9220f0136c1\">859-257-8774<a style=\"margin: 0px; border: currentColor; left: 0px; top: 0px; width: 16px; height: 16px; right: 0px; bottom: 0px; overflow: hidden; vertical-align: middle; float: none; display: inline; white-space: nowrap; position: static !important;\" title=\"Call: 859-257-8774\" href=\"#\"><img style=\"margin: 0px; border: currentColor; left: 0px; top: 0px; width: 16px; height: 16px; right: 0px; bottom: 0px; overflow: hidden; vertical-align: middle; float: none; display: inline; white-space: nowrap; position: static !important;\" title=\"Call: 859-257-8774\" src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" /></a></span>.</p><p>&nbsp;</p>',1368040529,'30190 at http://uknow.uky.edu'),(80,1,'Arrest Made in Indecent Exposure Case on UK Campus','http://uknow.uky.edu/content/arrest-made-indecent-exposure-case-uk-campus','Kathy Johnson','<span class=\"sw_img_wrap\"><a class=\"sw_img_a\" href=\"http://uknow.uky.edu/sites/default/files/police_all_black_unit_signature_1.jpg\"><img class=\"sw_img\" src=\"http://uknow.uky.edu/sites/default/files/imagecache/ctac_thumb/police_all_black_unit_signature.jpg\" /></a></span> <!--break--><p><strong>LEXINGTON, Ky. (May 13, 2013)</strong> ― May is National Bike Month, and University of Kentucky <a href=\"http://www.uky.edu/pts/\">Parking and Transportation Services</a> (PTS) is encouraging UK employees to take advantage of the many great activities going on with Bike Lexington.&nbsp; A great time to get involved is during National Bike to Work Week May 13-17.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Do you have hesitations about biking to work? PTS has put together a list of resources to help address common concerns:</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>I don’t know how to plan my route. Which roads have bike lanes?</strong></p><p>Review the <a href=\"http://www.lexingtonky.gov/index.aspx?page=577\">Lexington Bike Map</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.ppd.uky.edu/CampusMaps/BicycleMap_11x17.pdf\">UK Bike Facilities Map</a> (PDF) in selecting your route. You may also consider using interactive online maps, such as Google Maps and MapMyRide.com.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>I don’t feel comfortable bike commuting because I feel that the roads are unsafe. </strong></p><p>Cyclists and motorists have the same rights, rules and responsibilities on most Kentucky roads. Follow the guidelines from the state <a href=\"http://transportation.ky.gov/share-the-road/Pages/default.aspx\">Share the Road</a> campaign. Review the UK Bicycling Advisory Committee’s <a href=\"http://www.uky.edu/pts/sites/www.uky.edu.pts/files/pdfs/ukpts-bicycle-cycling-basics.pdf\">Bicycling Basics guide</a> (PDF) for a how-to guide on navigating campus on bike. If you don’t feel confident in your abilities, consider taking a bicycle commuting class before embarking on a bike commute.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>I don’t know where bike parking is located, or the existing bike parking is inconvenient.</strong></p><p>Check out the <a href=\"http://www.ppd.uky.edu/CampusMaps/BicycleMap_11x17.pdf\">Bike Parking Map</a> (PDF) to find the racks closest to your destination. Hochhalter, simply attending the <a href=\"http://www.sundance.org/festival/\">2013 Sundance Film Festival</a> was a thrill.&nbsp; He helped compose the music for the documentary <a href=\"http://www.bloodbrotherfilm.com/\"><em>Blood Brother</em>,</a> a contender in the U.S. Documentary category.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>\"I didn\'t expect for the film to even be in the Sundance because that\'s an honor in itself just to be entered,\" Hochhalter said.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>But as the ceremony began, his elation grew as <em>Blood Brother</em> won the <a href=\"http://www.sundance.org/festival/stories/award-winners/\">Audience Award for U.S. Documentary.</a></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>\"When it won that one first, honestly for me that one was more exciting because more people were voting, and I considered that as a better like-barometer of how the world was seeing this film and reacting to it,\" Hochhalter said.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>But the accolades did not end there.&nbsp; <em>Blood Brother</em> ended up <a href=\"http://www.sundance.org/festival/stories/award-winners/\">winning the grand prize, which</a> is the <a href=\"http://www.sundance.org/festival/stories/award-categories/\">Grand Jury Award for the festival.</a></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>\"It\'s still kind of unbelievable,\" Hochhalter said.&nbsp; \"It\'s exciting for me because the recent awards mean a lot of people will see it!\"</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The Louisville native composes film and commercial music from <a href=\"http://listendesignstudio.com/\">Listen Design Studio</a>, the business he started in downtown Lexington after graduating from UK\'s <a href=\"http://gatton.uky.edu/\">Gatton College of Business and Economics</a> with a <a href=\"http://gatton.uky.edu/Undergraduates/Content.asp?PageName=UMarketing\">marketing degree</a> in 2010.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>\"I earned a marketing degree because I thought ― you could be the best musician in the world or the best film composer, but if you don\'t understand the environment you are going to put yourself into then you\'re just going to stay in the basement being the best film composer that ever lived, and no one\'s going to hear about you.\" said Hochhalter.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Armed with a business background, he realized after college his passion rested with a hobby he started in high school.&nbsp; As a student at Louisville Christian Academy, he would spend hours playing and recording music.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>\"I kind of grew up in a time where computers were coming out where you didn\'t have to go to a big a studio,\" Hochhalter said.&nbsp; &nbsp;\"You could do it in your bedroom, so I always messed around with recording music.\"</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>But he says those who heard his recordings lamented that they sounded \"too much like the movies, too intense.\"</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>During his time on campus, he remembered the comment that seemed like a negative back when he was in high school.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>\"I met people at UK who started nonprofits and worked on documentaries either at my church or in class, and they would always put some \'Pirates of the Caribbean\' music in it, but then they could never use it,\" he said.&nbsp;&nbsp; \"They were looking for people to just take a crack at it, and I remembered back to high school when people told me my stuff sounded like a film. So, I decided to at least give it a try.&nbsp; &nbsp;I picked it up and I really enjoyed it.\"</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Hochhalter composed for free, just trying to get his name out there and developing a portfolio.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>\"I would ask people to let me write music for their movie trailers, and eventually I met the right people that kept calling back ― directors that ended up falling in love with my sound,\" he said. \"By that time I had a pretty large portfolio of stuff I\'d done so from there people could kind of hear my potential.\"</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Hochhalter says his time at UK working on a business degree helped him put his best foot forward as he made connections in the film industry.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>\"I felt very prepared and I knew what to expect, I knew the lingo,\" said Hochhalter. \"If you\'re new to it, just to learn even what some of these words mean is tough, but if you have studied them you can jump right in and talk confidently with a producer who runs on more of a business brain because he\'s talking about scheduling and budgets and money and meetings.\"</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>All of those connections led him to the opportunity to work on <em>Blood Brother</em>, <a href=\"http://filmguide.sundance.org/film/13095/blood_brother\">a documentary that captured a young American\'s experience working at an orphanage for children infected with HIV in India.</a> From the beginning, the film was unique because the director and producer could not pay what other films pay because they wanted money from the documentary to go toward efforts in India.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;\"As soon as I saw the film ― no matter if they wanted it for free ― I was going to say \'of course,\' because it was moving, and I was just happy to have music in it,\" said Hochhalter.&nbsp; \"It was very much a community collaborative because there are three other people that donated their music writing, so we all just kind of put our talents together and got it done.\"</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Beyond the award, he says the relationships he developed with those working on the film have already paved the way to future business.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>\"At the time I had no idea, but because of my work, it has turned into them calling me and saying, \'Hey, we have a big name client and we need music for this commercial.\'\" Hochhalter said.&nbsp; \"Because of our relationship, I\'ve been the one they come to, so it\'s been good.\"</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The husband and father of one doesn\'t plan on leaving Lexington for his career.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>\"Lexington is the perfect place for what I am doing, but when I tell people what I do, they are surprised I live in Lexington. They think I should be in LA or in New York, but because of technology, it\'s easy to work from here,\" Hochhalter said.&nbsp; \"In the past few years, Lexington has changed and there\'s an artistic feel to it.&nbsp; I have learned that this is the perfect place to be.\"</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>He hopes more documentary work is in his future, too.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>\"I like documentaries … because they\'re true stories and something inherently powerful when you know it\'s true, and the music is a little closer to the actual story.\" Hochhalter said.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>But fame and money are not what motivates this young composer.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>\"There are a lot of people in the world that are oppressed or struggling and don\'t have the life or luxury that I have,\" Hochhalter said.&nbsp; \"I\'ve been blessed with this ability to be able to help and use it as a tool and weapon to fight against these awful things that happen to people, so that\'s my underlying motivation.\"</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>To view other video stories about University of Kentucky alumni, watch the \"see success.\" <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/course?list=EC1855FFD4D160498B\">YouTube playlist</a> below:</p><p>&nbsp;</p><div class=\"media_embed\"><iframe height=\"315\" src=\"http://www.youtube.com/embed/videoseries?list=EC1855FFD4D160498B\" frameBorder=\"0\" width=\"560\" allowfullscreen=\"\"></iframe></div><p>&nbsp;</p>',1368025700,'30188 at http://uknow.uky.edu'),(87,1,'University of Kentucky’s iwin Hosts 11th Semiannual Roundtable Meeting','http://uknow.uky.edu/content/university-kentucky%E2%80%99s-iwin-hosts-11th-semiannual-roundtable-meeting','Ann Blackford','<span class=\"sw_img_wrap\"><a class=\"sw_img_a\" href=\"http://uknow.uky.edu/sites/default/files/iwin_may_2013_roundtable_meeting_small_group.jpg\"><img class=\"sw_img\" src=\"http://uknow.uky.edu/sites/default/files/imagecache/ctac_thumb/iwin_may_2013_roundtable_meeting_small_group.jpg\" /></a></span> <!--break--><p><strong>LEXINGTON, Ky. (May 14, 2013)</strong>&nbsp;— Approximately 40 of Kentucky’s most innovative employers met May 8-9 at the University of Kentucky’s&nbsp;Hilary J. Boone Center at the 11<sup>th</sup> semiannual Roundtable meeting sponsored by UK\'s Institute for Workplace Innovation (iwin). This year’s theme, “Rewards &amp; Recognition: Beyond the Dollar $ign,” was highlighted by nationally recognized researchers and practitioners to help attendees address and resolve workplace issues.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The semiannual meeting brings together some of Kentucky’s best employers to learn cutting edge practices, network with each other, as well as highlight iwin partners’ achievements.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The event kicked off as Lee Todd, former UK president, presented his namesake award, the Dr. Lee T. Todd, Jr. Bridging the Gap Between Workplace Research and Practice Award, to Fazoli’s Restaurants. Winners of this annual award enjoy a complimentary membership to the Roundtable for one year.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>“We find that employers who engage in this face-to-face meeting come away with proven workplace practices that will help strengthen their organizations,” said Lisa Williams, acting co-executive director of iwin.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Attendees enjoyed a variety of speakers, including keynote speaker, Christine Porath of Georgetown University, who educated attendees on the benefits of rewarding and recognizing their employees. Ritu Furlan, a partner at Ernst &amp; Young shared how to integrate flexibility into a company’s culture, while&nbsp;John Randolph offered insight on the new field of neuroleadership. A Roundtable favorite, “Speed Geeking,” offered partners the chance to learn from each other about what attracts, engages, and retains talent in their own organizations.&nbsp;&nbsp;Lt. Governor Jerry Abramson closed the meeting with insight on how his 20 years of public service have been filled with rewards and recognition beyond the dollar sign.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The next Roundtable meeting will be held October 9-10, 2013, Brown-Forman in Louisville.</p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p>Rose Douglass, executive vice president and director of Human Resources of Central Bank, said&nbsp;“iwin provides something new and exciting at each Roundtable.&nbsp; It’s always something tangible that I can take back to the office and implement to engage our employees and help boost the bottom line.”</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>To become a Partner of the UK iwin Innovative Employer Roundtable contact <a href=\"mailto:Shannon.holbrook@uky.edu\">Shannon.holbrook@uky.edu</a>. (May 14, 2013) </strong>— The 2013 Kalam Scholars Conference for Indian Business and Economic Research recently hosted by the <a href=\"http://www.uky.edu/\">University of Kentucky\'s</a> <a href=\"http://gatton.uky.edu/\">Gatton College of Economics</a> is drawing rave reviews from participants and observers.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>“Dr. M.S. Viji and (former Gatton) Dean D. Sudharshan showed great vision when they conceived the India studies program several years ago,\" said Dave Blackwell, dean of the Gatton College. \"India is an emerging economic power, and it is important that we explore through our scholarship how best to strengthen economic ties between the U.S. and India.&nbsp;This first Kalam Scholars conference is an important step in this process and represents a tangible impact of Dr. Viji’s philanthropy in establishing the program.”</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The conference is an outgrowth of the <a href=\"http://gatton.uky.edu/economics/kalamscholars/about.asp\">The A.P.J. Kalam India Studies Research Program</a><u>,</u> funded through a generous gift from Viji, a Lexington physician. The program&nbsp;supports research in the Gatton College examining the country of India\'s role in international commerce, as well as providing the opportunity for intellectual interaction between scholars in India and here at UK.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Rohini Somanathan, a development economist at the Delhi School of Economics and one of the visiting scholars at the conference, reported on her research examining how the banking sector in India is attempting to deal with problems of poverty and inequality impacting her nation\'s economy.&nbsp; \"The exchange of ideas at this conference provided some wonderful business perspectives,\" Somanathan said.&nbsp; \"It gets everyone thinking about things in new and different ways.\"</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Mukta Kulkarni, an expert in organizational behavior and human resource management at the Indian Institute of Management in Bangalore, praised the collaborative spirit of the conference.&nbsp; \"The interconnectivity of the global economy today truly makes it \'a small world,\'\" Kulkarni said.&nbsp; \"The ability to be in the same room with faculty from the Gatton College and share information in a seminar-type environment is wonderful.\"</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Viji, who attended all of the sessions, was enthused by what he saw and heard.&nbsp; \"This conference is enabling Kentucky to learn more about India and vice versa. The scientific research resulting from this program not only informs people from a global business perspective, but also educates people about more subtle aspects of international relationships, such as adapting to cultural differences and the like.\"</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>One of the Gatton faculty members who presented at the conference is Daniel Halgin, assistant professor in the Department of Management and part of <a href=\"https://sites.google.com/site/uklinkscenter/\">LINKS, the International Center for Research on Social Networks in Business</a>.&nbsp; \"This conference has laid the groundwork for future collaborations between scholars here at UK and scholars in India,\" said Halgin.&nbsp; \"For instance, Professor Kulkarni and I just met yet we already are planning a meeting in India later this month to discuss the possibility of working together on a new research project.&nbsp; I\'m grateful to the Kalam India Studies Endowment Fund for supporting these collaborative activities.\"</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Another presenter, Gatton College Professor of Economics Jenny Minier, said the conference covered a wide range of topics, all centered on the vibrant, fast-growing Indian economy.&nbsp; \"It was an excellent opportunity to interact with two well-known scholars from India and learn about their research. The comments I received from conference participants on my presentation were very helpful and will help shape this research moving forward,\" Minier said.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>And a third presenter from UK, Gatton Endowed Professor Krish Muralidhar, Department of Finance and Quantitative Methods, added, \"It was a great opportunity to listen to a wide range of interesting and important topics from a diverse group of U.S. and Indian researchers in an intimate setting.\"</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The conference coordinator, Gatton Endowed Professor and director of <a href=\"http://cber.uky.edu/\">UK\'s Center for Business and Economic Research</a>, Chris Bollinger, came away very encouraged by the gathering.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>\"My goal for the conference was to have researchers from the Gatton College interacting with each other and with outstanding scholars from India about important research questions focused on the Indian economy and business practices,\" Bollinger said. \"I think we all learned a lot from each other and it was exciting to be a part of that. This dialogue definitely set a positive tone for continuing research collaboration and analytical discussion.\"</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p align=\"center\">&nbsp;</p><p><strong>MEDIA CONTACTS</strong>: Carl Nathe, <span style=\"white-space: nowrap;\" class=\"baec5a81-e4d6-4674-97f3-e9220f0136c1\">859-257-3200<a style=\"margin: 0px; (May 14, 2013)</strong> — Applications are now being accepted for the University of Kentucky <a href=\"http://www.uky.edu/womensforum/\">Women’s Forum</a> Employee Educational Assistance Award. The deadline for employee-students enrolled in the summer semesters is May 17 for Summer Session I and June 7 for Summer Session II.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The award is a $250 reimbursement to eligible UK employees to assist with the cost of books and/or other materials, supplies and fees related to their UK coursework, complementing the existing tuition waiver program (Employee Education Program, EEP) for UK employees.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><a href=\"https://uky.qualtrics.com/SE/?SID=SV_3sZqBusyxmC5KLi\">Apply here for the EEAA for summer sessions 2013.</a></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Eligibility requirements include:</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Applicants must be regular full-time employees (0.75 FTE and greater)</p><p>·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Applicants must have submitted an EEP form</p><p>·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Applicants must be currently enrolled in UK classes, excluding independent study program courses</p><p>·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Previously enrolled students are required to have a cumulative grade point average of 2.0 or better. First-time college enrollees are encouraged to apply.</p><p>·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Applicants are required to take all courses for a letter grade unless the course is offered only as pass/fail.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Employees taking classes through EEP at any educational institution aside from the University of Kentucky cannot be considered for this award.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The UK Women’s Forum Educational Assistance Award is a competition in which applications will be evaluated and ranked by committee members. The decisions of the selection committee are final. UK Women’s Forum Board are ineligible for awards.</p>',1368481156,'30247 at http://uknow.uky.edu'),(90,1,'UK, Lexington Theological Seminary Considering Property Sale','http://uknow.uky.edu/content/uk-lexington-theological-seminary-considering-property-sale','Beth Goins','<span class=\"sw_img_wrap\"><a class=\"sw_img_a\" href=\"http://uknow.uky.edu/sites/default/files/lexington_theological_seminary.jpg\"><img class=\"sw_img\" src=\"http://uknow.uky.edu/sites/default/files/imagecache/ctac_thumb/lexington_theological_seminary.jpg\" /></a></span> <!--break--><p><strong>Lexington, Ky. (May 14, 2013)</strong> – The University of Kentucky Board of Trustees today will consider a recommendation to purchase the current grounds and facilities of the Lexington Theological Seminary (LTS).</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The seminary -- which has been undergoing an exciting transformation in how and where students are shaped for ministry -- is making plans to relocate its administration and educational operations to another location in Lexington.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>At its meeting today, the UK BOT will consider purchasing the 63-year-old campus for $13.5 million. The sale and stewardship of these resources “will provide for a sustainable business plan for the long-term future of the seminary,” said LTS Board Chairman Gary Kidwell.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The LTS Board is actively considering the seminary’s next location, which could include existing facility space or the construction of a new, right-sized campus in Lexington, Kidwell said.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>“Just as we have transformed our curriculum, the board recognizes that we must also transform our site to better represent who we are and who we serve, now and in the future,” LTS President Charisse L. Gillett said. “We honor the history of this place by continuing the spirit of what it represents – our mission to further God’s work in the world by preparing our students to be the best ministry leaders they can be.”</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>For the university, the space and facilities represent an opportunity to gain access to potential classroom space within the existing campus footprint at a critical time, said UK President Eli Capilouto. For example, with the pending renovation and expansion of the Gatton College of Business and Economics, there will be a pressing need for \"swing\" or transitional space for faculty, staff and students.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>\"When high-quality space adjacent to your campus becomes available, the responsible thing is to explore the possibilities,\" Capilouto said. \"The Lexington Theological Seminary space represents great potential for the university as we grapple with how to grow and manage within our existing footprint.\"</p><p>\"Opportunities to purchase high-quality property and buildings adjacent to our campus don\'t come along very often,\" said Britt Brockman, chair of UK\'s Board of Trustees. \"As we are contemplating how we will grow and develop over the next several years, we should, in my judgment, take advantage of opportunities such as this one that will bolster our ability to provide for our students, faculty and staff.\"</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>LTS students, alumni, supporters and ministry partners were all considered with utmost care in making the decision to move, Kidwell said. “We will maintain and honor our historic presence in Lexington,” he said.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Founded in 1865, LTS is the oldest seminary affiliated with the Christian Church (Disciples of Christ) and has been a part of the Lexington community since its early days at Bacon College. The seminary moved to the current campus on South Limestone in 1950. At the time, LTS was a residential seminary.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>In recent years, however, the seminary has transformed its curriculum, focusing on congregation-based settings for theological formation of students, taking advantage of 21<sup>st</sup> century technology to connect students and faculty without requiring students to move to campus to pursue a master’s degree, doctorate or certificate program. Students converge on campus twice a year for about two weeks at a time and maintain community through online communications, peer groups, mentorships and events throughout the year.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>“We have recognized the changing demographics – especially with geography, age, and stage of life – and how to meet students where they are,” said Leslie L. Geoghegan, chairwoman of the Advancement Committee. “We have embraced technology as a tool to transcend any barriers of the seminary’s location or the perceived isolation of a student’s location, as we focus on the importance of the relationship with the congregation in the life and educational process of the student.”</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Because of this shift, the LTS no longer needs to maintain its residential facilities as well as the large administration and classroom buildings. Geoghegan noted that the seminary needs facilities which support the institution’s focus on four key areas: academic excellence and relevance; financial equilibrium and growth; sustaining pastors in ministry; and developing a quality place to study and work.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Under the agreement with UK if approved by the university\'s board, the seminary would relocate its administration offices by December, with the option to use the classroom space in January 2014. The library would be moved by August 2014.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Julie Richardson Brown, who earned a Master of Divinity degree from LTS in 2002, said that she believes relocation will not have an impact on the legacy of the seminary, which is looking forward to celebrating its 150<sup>th</sup> birthday in 2015.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>“I think the spirit of a place can remain, even if moved elsewhere.&nbsp; Always.&nbsp; My love for that ‘place’ runs deep – and so if I can say, ‘Let’s move forward,’ anyone can.&nbsp; I can also say that I am fiercely proud to be a graduate,” Richardson Brown said.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Updates about the move will be available at <a href=\"http://www.lextheo.edu/transformation\">www.lextheo.edu/transformation</a>.</p><p>&nbsp;</p>',1368534372,'30248 at http://uknow.uky.edu'),(91,1,'Farm Road on UK\'s Campus to Close Temporarily Beginning May 15','http://uknow.uky.edu/content/farm-road-uks-campus-close-temporarily-beginning-may-15','Kathy Johnson','<span class=\"sw_img_wrap\"><a class=\"sw_img_a\" href=\"http://uknow.uky.edu/sites/default/files/farm_road.jpg\"><img class=\"sw_img\" src=\"http://uknow.uky.edu/sites/default/files/imagecache/ctac_thumb/farm_road.jpg\" /></a></span> <!--break--><p><strong>LEXINGTON, Ky. (May 14, 2013)</strong> — The University of Kentucky Board of Trustees today approved the continuation of Phase II of a plan to expand and modernize student housing, authorizing the president to develop three additional residence halls with 1,610 undergraduate beds at the Cooperstown site by August 2015. These additions to campus, to be developed and managed by Education Realty Trust, Inc. (EdR), will bring the total number of modern student accommodations to 4,592.</p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p>The transformation of UK’s undergraduate student housing began in February 2012 with the construction on Haggin Field of Central Hall I and II, which will house 601 students beginning this upcoming fall semester. Phase II-A includes the current construction of five new residence halls, Champions Court I and II on the north end of campus, Woodland Glen I and II behind William T. Young Library, and Haggin Hall. Plans were later amended for Haggin Hall to include approximately 12,000 square feet of shell space for a dining venue plus 64 additional beds. In total, the five halls of Phase II-A will add 2,381 beds to the university’s portfolio by August 2014. Development cost of Phase II-A is estimated at $138 million.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>With a scope of $101.2 million, today’s board action will allow Phase II-B to commence with three new halls, Woodland Glen III, IV and V, adding another 1,610 beds and completing the transformation of the Cooperstown site by August 2015.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Recognizing that the average age of UK’s current student housing is 45 years, UK President Eli Capilouto said, “This public private partnership has allowed the university to fulfill our promise of modern student housing in an astoundingly brief time frame while also reserving our debt capacity for other projects to modernize our classrooms.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>“Not only will the student experience at the University of Kentucky be transformed, but the impact on our state and local economies is not to be underestimated. The university’s growth is not happening at the expense of Kentucky, but at its enrichment.”</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The economic impact of this widespread construction will total approximately $163.8 million, with Phase I, Phase II-A and Phase II-B, supporting 7,384 direct and indirect jobs. (May 17, 2013</strong>) — The best learning — and the most profound educational experiences — often take place outside the traditional classroom.<br />&nbsp;<br />For Charles Black, such experiences have guided him as he has taken his education at the University of Kentucky to frequent appearances on New York stages and TV shows.<br />&nbsp;<br />As a student, Black said, he traveled with <a href=\"http://finearts.uky.edu/theatre\">theatre</a> department professors and fellow students to New York.<br />&nbsp;<br />“It was my very first trip to New York, where I learned that I really wanted to move here,\" Black said. \"It all came from being at the University of Kentucky.\"<br />&nbsp;<br />During the trip, Black and his fellow students got a behind-the-scenes look at life in the theater on the biggest of stages.<br />&nbsp;<br />“It prepared me and opened the doors and made me feel really confident that I could come here and try,” he said.<br />&nbsp;<br />Black now routinely appears on those same stages as an actor. He also has had roles on the long-running soap opera <em>One Life To Live </em>and has landed several commercials and guest spots on many of TV’s most popular shows.<br />&nbsp;<br />Much of Black\'s success, he says, ties directly to his experiences at UK, where professors nurtured and encouraged his interest in the theater — with playwriting workshops, coursework and numerous plays that brought real-life, practical experiences into the classroom.<br />&nbsp;<br />“You really realize how valuable the education is at UK, because of the professors there,” he said. “Some of them have been here in New York — lived here and worked here — and they know what they’re doing. (May 17, 2013)</strong> ― More than 800 University of Kentucky students&nbsp;have left&nbsp;the U.S. during the 2012-2013 academic year to pursue UK Education Abroad opportunities throughout the world. &nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>As UK <a href=\"http://www.uky.edu/international/educationabroad\">Education Abroad</a> Director Anthony Ogden describes, Education Abroad opportunities have taken on a new meaning, one that reflects a more academic vision. “It’s not about where you want to go,” Ogden said. “It’s about what you want to do. Education Abroad now includes study abroad, research abroad and intern abroad. As educators, we are here to help students find the right academic fit.”</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>From independent research projects in Turkey, to service projects in Ecuador, to internships in China, Education Abroad carries a variety of programs just as diverse as the student population on campus. Through the selection process, EA helps students view these programs as an investment that can significantly advance one’s academic and professional aspirations.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>These students will receive more than just stamps in their passports. In fact, students who enroll in Education Abroad programs are exploring their disciplines and interests in ways that they couldn’t do on campus or even in the U.S.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Through UK-sponsored summer programs, many faculty members are also exploring international topics in their fields along with UK students, including Dr. Beth Barnes, director of the <a href=\"http://jat.uky.edu/\">School of Journalism and Telecommunications</a> and an integrated strategic communications professor leading a summer program in Cape Town, South Africa. Barnes believes the program will equip students with an international perspective that will change how they view the U.S.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>“It\'s a part of the world they might not see otherwise, and learning about the past and ongoing racial and socioeconomic tensions in South Africa can help students view the U.S. in a different light,” she said.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Education Abroad programming is a cornerstone of UK’s mission as the state’s flagship university to promote a “diversity of community and ideas” throughout the state.&nbsp; As President Eli Capilouto has stated, “A philosophy of openness and inclusivity free from ignorance assures that we educate and prepare students to work and live in a global society.” Education Abroad programs fuel this philosophy by equipping students with an international perspective and experiences that will last a lifetime.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Interested in pursuing an Education Abroad opportunity? (May 24, 2013) </strong>— University of Kentucky alum (\'12) Sabrina Hounshell has always been known for her spontaneity and plans for the next big adventure.&nbsp; She loved sharing her ideas and career plans with her parents, whether it was deep sea fishing off the coast of Australia, photographing the African jungle, or announcing that she would study abroad and was leaving in mere weeks.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Hounshell\'s parents never knew if their daughter was actually going to follow through with her plans, and their canned response became \"Seriously, Sabrina? Really?\" The nickname \"Seriously Sabrina\" stuck and even spread among her friends.&nbsp; Today, just one year after graduating from UK, \"Seriously Sabrina\" is a legally recognized enterprise named for the 24-year-old dynamo who made a career out of her passion for travel and photography.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>When Hounshell came to UK in 2007, she was an agriculture communications student and although she changed her major several times, and graduated with a degree in integrated strategic communication (ISC),&nbsp;she always knew she wanted to be a photographer.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>\"In high school, I pursued leadership opportunities and traveled as a member of the 4-H organization, which is most well-known for its agriculture background. I did many photography contests, taught photography classes at 4-H summer camp, and always loved documenting my life since I got my first digital camera at age 14.\"</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Documenting life became a theme in her photography that followed Hounshell throughout her academic career at UK.&nbsp; She enrolled in darkroom photography classes and wanted to work for the Kernel, but the editor turned her down because she didn\'t own a professional camera. After months of convincing her parents to help her buy a camera, she went back to the Kernel and started shooting assignments.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Hounshell attended the Kernel\'s photography workshop called Picture Kentucky, where she worked with seasoned photojournalists on how to tell a story with images in an interesting way. After months of shooting as a self-described fledgling photographer, her first published photo was taken at Greek Sing in 2008.&nbsp; Hounshell\'s interests also spread outside the Kernel. She was a member of the Student Activities Board and the K Book Editorial Board; she participated in Alternative Service Breaks, and was a Dance Blue coordinator.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>In 2009, Hounshell decided to leave the Kernel to study abroad and spend the next semester in the United Kingdom. It was here that she fell in love with travel photography and knew that whatever avenue of photography she took, travel was a non-negotiable must.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>When Hounshell returned to the states and resumed her studies at UK, her photographs from the 2010 Dance Blue marathon had caught the eye of Kelley Bozeman, director of Marketing at UK, who offered her a job as photographer for UK Public Relations and Marketing, which Hounshell did from February 2010 until she graduated in May 2012.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>\"I took photos of everything from award ceremonies and receptions to being the only photographer in the room when Bill Clinton came to UK,\" Hounshell said.&nbsp; \"I photographed Homecoming, huge concerts and even the press conference when the Cats came back to Rupp with their National Championship win. It was an absolutely amazing experience, but I knew deep down that my real passion for photography wasn\'t in documenting events.\"</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>She had been following wedding blogs for years&nbsp;and&nbsp;developed a huge&nbsp;interest in the creativity, angles and editing techniques that wedding photographers were using in California.&nbsp;After booking&nbsp;a few weddings and attending photography workshops across the country, Hounshell&nbsp;traveled to&nbsp;Louisiana, California, Las Vegas and Chicago to learn from photographers she admired.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>\"I was hooked. Portrait and wedding photography had stolen my heart,\" Hounshell said. \"I grew up with a lot of European influence from my mother, who\'s German, and the inside of my childhood home is seriously decorated like a castle, complete with tin knights, stained glass windows, a&nbsp;spiral staircase, tapestries and medieval touches. I was fascinated by fairytales. I began combining the skills I was learning from the photography workshops with whimsical, fairy tale inspired shoots and editing style.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p> \"My biggest influences for my work come from wedding photographers in Southern California, fairy tales, and the drive to document a day in the most beautiful and complete way that I possibly can. I fell in love not only with weddings, but as a hopeless romantic, I was in love with love. As I shot more weddings the light bulb went off —&nbsp;dream job: destination wedding photographer. I would get to document love, get paid to travel and be doing something I love in the process. I now had a goal.\"</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>In April 2012, just weeks before graduation, Hounshell experienced the tragic loss of her only sister, which left her feeling depressed.&nbsp; Rather than allowing it to derail her, she used her sadness as a fuel to fire her dreams and in the summer of 2012 <a href=\"http://seriouslysabrinaphotography.com/\">Seriously Sabrina Photography</a> became an LLC (limited liability company).</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>\"While working another job, I used free time and knowledge I gained while earning my ISC degree to advertise and market myself through social media to begin booking clients,\" Hounshell said. \"By January 2013 I had started booking enough weddings and getting enough inquiries that I was able to quit my day job to be a full-time photographer. I am beyond proud and privileged to be photographing 30 weddings and countless other portrait sessions in 2013. My jobs are taking me coast to coast in the United States, to Vancouver Island in Canada and I am photographing a wedding this summer in Austria.\"</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Hounshell\'s work has caught the attention of many blogs and publishers, including <em>Kentucky Bride Magazine</em> and blogs such as <em>Style Me Pretty, Poptastic Bride, Offbeat Families, Evoking You, Borrowed and Blue, Trendy Bride, DIY Bride, WedLoft, and Fab You Bliss</em>. Last month, Hounshell opened her photography studio, a space that she uses to hold workshops for amateur and seasoned photographers on improving their photography skills, building their portfolios, and improving their businesses.&nbsp; She also hosted her first wedding photographer workshop this past April.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>\"I am living and thriving in a creative profession. I\'m able to pay my bills, travel, create, and feel fulfilled on a daily basis,\" Hounshell said. \"I created a successful business in less than a year and am sharing the experience with so many incredible people who push me to be better every day. My success is largely based on the success of those who surround me, their success is my success. I am living the dream and rising with my friends; what better success is there than that?\"</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>MEDIA CONTACT:</strong> Ann Blackford at <span style=\"white-space: nowrap;\" class=\"baec5a81-e4d6-4674-97f3-e9220f0136c1\">859-323-6442<a style=\"margin: 0px; border: currentColor; left: 0px; top: 0px; width: 16px; height: 16px; right: 0px; bottom: 0px; overflow: hidden; vertical-align: middle; float: none; display: inline; white-space: nowrap; position: static !important;\" title=\"Call: 859-323-6442\" href=\"#\"><img style=\"margin: 0px; border: currentColor; left: 0px; top: 0px; width: 16px; height: 16px; right: 0px; bottom: 0px; overflow: hidden; vertical-align: middle; float: none; display: inline; white-space: nowrap; position: static !important;\" title=\"Call: 859-323-6442\" src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" /></a></span> or <a href=\"mailto:ann.blackford@uky.edu\">ann.blackford@uky.edu</a></p>',1369063617,'30326 at http://uknow.uky.edu'),(105,1,'UK Hosting Teachers From Ecuador as Part of International Partnership','http://uknow.uky.edu/content/uk-hosting-teachers-ecuador-part-international-partnership','Sarah Geegan','<span class=\"sw_img_wrap\"><a class=\"sw_img_a\" href=\"http://uknow.uky.edu/sites/default/files/ecuador_teachers_holding_flag.png\"><img class=\"sw_img\" src=\"http://uknow.uky.edu/sites/default/files/imagecache/ctac_thumb/ecuador_teachers_holding_flag.png\" /></a></span> <!--break--><p><strong>LEXINGTON, Ky. (May 24, 2013)</strong> ― If you can read this sentence, it’s likely you owe your understanding of English to one of your many language teachers. Given your fluency, how well could you teach English to another person? Now imagine English isn’t your first language – how well would you be able to teach it then?</p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p>This is the challenge faced by 42 teachers studying at the University of Kentucky as part of the <a href=\"http://esl.as.uky.edu/ecuador\">Go Teacher </a>program sponsored by the Ecuadorian government. The scholarship program recruits teachers in Ecuador and sends them to the U.S. for intensive training.</p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p>Participants in the seven-month program are public school English teachers from every corner of Ecuador.</p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p>“During this time they will do two things,” explained Tom Clayton, executive director of UK\'s <a href=\"http://esl.as.uky.edu/\">Center for English as a Second Language</a> (CESL). “They study English to improve their skills and they also study contemporary techniques for English language teaching.”</p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p>“The whole idea of the program is to increase their English skills so when they go back to Ecuador they will be better teachers,” added Tina Durbin, assistant director of CESL.</p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p>The first half of this newly developed curriculum puts participants in the intensive English program in CESL, taking courses focusing on the four language skills – reading, writing, listening and speaking. The second half focuses on language instruction, engaging the visiting teachers in courses on contemporary techniques for English language teaching, second language acquisition and sociolinguistics.</p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p>“In the second phase they study methods, how to teach language, also applied linguistics, culture and language,” said Jill Cargile, Teaching English as a Second Language (TESL) director for the Go Teacher program.</p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p>As Ecuador continues to emerge as part of the global economy, its government has placed increased priority on improving English language skills for its students and citizens.</p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p>“Ecuador is one of the big players in South America, and they’re trying to raise the level of English teaching,” Cargile explained. “They see English as an avenue to help them compete globally. This is all funded by Ecuador. It’s very unusual and special. We’re happy to be a part of it. “I think it will have a real positive effect on Ecuador and the progress of their students.”</p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p>Participants in the <a href=\"http://esl.as.uky.edu/ecuador\">Go Teacher</a> program have a lot to say about the benefits offered by their time at UK.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>“I appreciate being here to improve my English and my knowledge of technologies and methodologies for being a teacher,\" Susana Auquilla said. \"After these seven months our English will be better and we can find better jobs and teach our students in a better way.”</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Carla Cadena said her entire experience has been beneficial -- even outside the classroom. “You are going to grow emotionally because you are living in a new culture. We are not just learning English, we are learning a new lifestyle and culture. We will transmit these things to our students.”</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Meanwhile, teachers and administrators in CESL value having the visiting Ecuadorian teachers in the classroom, pointing out that these adult learners are model students, bringing energy and diversity to CESL courses.</p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p>“They study really hard and raise the bar in our classes. They are teachers and are more motivated than the average student because they have more at risk. They have a positive effect and other students want to participate and be part of the energy of the classroom. It’s almost like having student colleagues in your classes,” Cargile explained.</p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p>“It has truly increased our diversity, which raises the level of using English as a foreign language,” Durbin said. “They’ve been great role models for our younger students.”</p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p>The Go Teacher scholarship program is a three-year contract with the University of Kentucky and other participating American institutions, administered through Kansas State University. The group of 42 Ecuadorian teachers that arrived in Lexington in January will be followed by a second cohort coming in late May.</p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p>In addition to their in work in the classroom and community at large, participants in the Go Teacher program play a vital role in helping CESL achieve its goals of increasing international development work and expanding the role of CESL in teacher training.</p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p>“That’s an important turn because we haven’t done so much in the past with teaching ESL,” Clayton explained. “It pushes us to make that transition to improve students’ skills as English language teachers.”</p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p>This program, then, not only gives visiting teachers the chance to learn new skills and make a contribution to their native Ecuador but also expands the limits for the CESL, offering exciting learning opportunities for students.</p><p>&nbsp;</p>',1369335787,'30399 at http://uknow.uky.edu'),(106,1,'UK Student Reflects on Medical Rotation in South Africa','http://uknow.uky.edu/content/uk-student-reflects-medical-rotation-south-africa','Sarah Geegan','<span class=\"sw_img_wrap\"><a class=\"sw_img_a\" href=\"http://uknow.uky.edu/sites/default/files/south_africa_presentation_epatterson-1_page_30_image_0001_2.jpg\"><img class=\"sw_img\" src=\"http://uknow.uky.edu/sites/default/files/imagecache/ctac_thumb/south_africa_presentation_epatterson-1_page_30_image_0001_2.jpg\" /></a></span> <!--break--><p><strong>LEXINGTON, Ky. (May 24, 2013)</strong> <strong>— </strong>As one University of Kentucky graduate prepared to leave campus, she reflected on one of her favorite experiences during her eight years at UK — traveling to South Africa on a medical rotation.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><a href=\"http://med.uky.edu/\">UK College of Medicine</a> student Elaine Patterson was accustomed to <a href=\"http://www.uky.edu/international/educationabroad\">studying abroad</a>, having traveled to Ecuador and Denmark while in college. However, there was one other place she had always wanted to see.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>“I was interested in South Africa because my grandmother was born in Swaziland, and her parents were missionaries there,\" Patterson said. \"So I’ve wanted to go to South Africa and see what the area was like.”</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>When an opportunity to study family medicine in South Africa arose through the Child Family Health International (CFHI) program, Patterson took the leap.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>“The program helps medical students receive experience in places around the world that really need medical assistance, like South Africa,” Patterson said.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Medical rotations are four-week blocks of on-site training during which medical students experience specific parts of the hospital. Rotations include surgical procedures, emergency room and internal medicine.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Patterson primarily worked in a community hospital in Athlone, a district just outside of Cape Town. There, she chose to work in her specialty of internal medicine, which allowed her to explore various aspects of the hospital environment.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>“I worked in the public sector in an observational capacity, so I spent a lot of time in a public hospital that served a rural community —&nbsp;simply observing how the hospital operated and what went on there,” Patterson said.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>As a student, one of Patterson’s goals was to closely examine South Africa’s health care system and understand how it differs from that of the U.S. One thing that struck her was the larger roles that medical students and residents play in South Africa.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>“The medical students have a much more hands-on role there,” Patterson said. “They don’t have the technology that we do here in the U.S., but they know everything about the equipment they have and are really conscious about the patient and how much each additional procedure will cost the patient, because in most cases they don’t have the best health insurance.”&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Patterson also noted the dichotomy of health care in South Africa, divided into public and private sectors.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>“The private sector gets the majority of the doctors, but only those with excellent insurance can afford to visit them, so their physician density is incredibly low in the public sector,” Patterson said.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Her experience in South Africa led Patterson to realize that the only way to truly learn about another country is to experience it firsthand.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>“I think seeing their health care system up close and being in the hospital seeing everything for myself allowed me to better understand how it works and what makes it different from ours,” Patterson said. “And I don’t think I could have gotten that same experience in a classroom.”</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Though Apartheid was abolished, South Africa still faces a huge socioeconomic gap between the wealthy and the poor. Experiencing a new culture and seeing that gap firsthand stands out as one of Patterson’s favorite experiences outside the hospital. During her stay, Patterson saw some of the poorest districts of South Africa—districts still struggling with basic services like waste management and hygiene.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>For Patterson, seeing those areas was one of the most humbling parts of her time abroad. It allowed her to understand the intricacies of the South African culture.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>“If I was just there as a tourist, I wouldn’t have understood so much about their culture and how Apartheid still manifests itself throughout their society,” Patterson said.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Living and learning abroad is an experience Patterson believes everyone should have; she hopes her story encourages more people to take a similar leap.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>“I feel like when you immerse yourself in a culture, you get to experience it in a completely new perspective,” she said, “You can’t get that in a classroom or as a tourist. You have to go out and experience it for yourself.”</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>MEDIA CONTACT: </strong>Sarah Geegan, <span style=\"white-space: nowrap;\" class=\"baec5a81-e4d6-4674-97f3-e9220f0136c1\">(859) 257-5365<a style=\"margin: 0px; border: currentColor; left: 0px; top: 0px; width: 16px; height: 16px; right: 0px; bottom: 0px; overflow: hidden; vertical-align: middle; float: none; display: inline; white-space: nowrap; position: static !important;\" title=\"Call: (859) 257-5365\" href=\"#\"><img style=\"margin: 0px; border: currentColor; left: 0px; top: 0px; width: 16px; height: 16px; right: 0px; bottom: 0px; overflow: hidden; vertical-align: middle; float: none; display: inline; white-space: nowrap; position: static !important;\" title=\"Call: (859) 257-5365\" src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" /></a></span>; <a href=\"mailto:sarah.geegan@uky.edu\">sarah.geegan@uky.edu</a></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p>',1369319003,'30394 at http://uknow.uky.edu'),(107,1,'Stream Restoration Project Produces \'Real-World\' Results','http://uknow.uky.edu/content/stream-restoration-project-produces-real-world-results','Keith Hautala','<span class=\"sw_img_wrap\"><a class=\"sw_img_a\" href=\"http://uknow.uky.edu/sites/default/files/130423acp323mb022.jpg\"><img class=\"sw_img\" src=\"http://uknow.uky.edu/sites/default/files/imagecache/ctac_thumb/130423acp323mb022.jpg\" /></a></span> <!--break--><p><strong>LEXINGTON, Ky. (May 28, 2013) —</strong> At the University of Kentucky’s North Farm, a stream reach runs between two horse paddocks on the Maine Chance/Spindletop Farm. Newly planted trees and wildflowers align the banks of the stream, which contains a modest amount of water. Classified as an intermittent stream, it is fed from a spring at a nearby farm and flows about three months out of the year.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>In 2010, it was merely a forgotten rut in the earth, something that had once been a stream yet now was dry and largely void of vegetation and wildlife. That was when Carmen Agouridis, a&nbsp;biosystems engineering professor, saw the reach as an opportunity to get her Biosystems and Agricultural Engineering class (BAE 532) some real-world experience in all phases of the stream restoration process.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>“This was a fun project that had participation from undergraduate and graduate students as well as faculty in biosystems and agricultural engineering, civil engineering and forestry,” Agouridis said. “In the span of about two and a half years, we were able to restore a stream on UK’s property.”</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The first part of the project involved a stream assessment. Students surveyed the bed, noting its width, depth and shape, and they accounted for the materials in the bed as well as nearby vegetation. After submitting a formal analysis, they developed a conceptual design plan proposing the best way to fix the stream.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Around that time, Agouridis received a Natural Resources Conservation grant that would allow the class’s proposal to become a reality. First, however, Agouridis needed to secure permits from the federal government and the Kentucky Division of Water in order to move forward — a task that took six months to complete.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>“Both agencies were primarily concerned with whether our work would make the water quality and habitat better,” Agouridis said. As a result, she will submit reports for the next three years that compare the current water quality and habitat to what it was before.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Once the permits were granted, Agouridis and her spring 2011 BAE 532 students were ready to bring in the heavy equipment for digging. Unfortunately, it rained. And rained.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>And rained.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>In fact, 2011 was the wettest year on record for Lexington. The dump trucks could not get to the restoration site and the project had to be temporarily shelved; however, the summer of 2012 offered favorable conditions and the work resumed.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Sam Lee contributed to the proposed design as an undergraduate student in 2010. When Agouridis was able to start digging, Lee was a civil engineering graduate student. Agouridis recalls he was eager to participate in the construction process as much as possible.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>“The contractor we used, Eric Dawalt, was an alumnus of the Department of Biosystems and Agricultural Engineering, so he helped teach Sam how to use some of the university’s equipment,” she said. “He got to be quite good on it.”</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>In all, the class restored approximately 900 feet of stream. The project represents UK’s dedication to classroom learning that produces real-world results.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>“Students got to participate in all phases of the project,” confirms Agouridis. “They did what anyone would have to do: survey, design, obtain permits, build and provide a post-construction assessment. When the flowers are in bloom this summer, it will look great.”</p><br /><p>&nbsp;</p>',1369343862,'30407 at http://uknow.uky.edu'),(108,1,'UK Advisors Give Back in Fourth Annual Day of Service','http://uknow.uky.edu/content/uk-advisors-give-back-fourth-annual-day-service','Sarah Geegan','<span class=\"sw_img_wrap\"><a class=\"sw_img_a\" href=\"http://uknow.uky.edu/sites/default/files/img_4840.jpg\"><img class=\"sw_img\" src=\"http://uknow.uky.edu/sites/default/files/imagecache/ctac_thumb/img_4840.jpg\" /></a></span> <!--break--><p><strong>LEXINGTON, Ky. (May 28, 2013)</strong> <strong>— </strong>&nbsp;Approximately 40 members of the <a href=\"http://www.uky.edu/UGE/advising_network/\">University of Kentucky Advising Network</a> took a day to give back to the Lexington community on Friday, May 10. As part of its fourth annual Day of Service, the Advising Network chose to support the <a href=\"http://beyondtheviolence.com/\">Bluegrass Domestic Violence Program, Inc</a>. (BDVP).</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>BDVP is an advocacy agency with a commitment to end intimate partner abuse and its impact on families and communities. The program provides a holistic approach to meeting the needs of victims of intimate partner abuse as they strive to heal and rebuild their lives as survivors.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Advisors assisted on the organization’s 40-acre working farm and helped clean and organize the BDVP shelter. &nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>“We are so fortunate at the Bluegrass Domestic Violence Program to be situated on 40 acres of beautiful farm land,” Diane Fleet, assistant director of the BDVP, said. “It provides us with an amazing healing environment for the families we serve. However, without great community volunteers such as the UK Advising Network, it would be impossible for us to maintain and care for our land and shelter facility. For several hours, UK advisors scrubbed, mulched, weeded and decorated our space so that families in the Bluegrass will always know they are loved and cared for.”</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>After the service portion of the day, the advisors returned to campus for a luncheon and to hear remarks from Corissa Phillips, director of communication and development for the BDVP, about the services the organization provides to 17 counties in the central Kentucky region.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>“The Advising Network Day of Service has always been my favorite event of the year,” said Matt Waitkus, chair of the Advising Network. “The teamwork and camaraderie that everybody shows while we are helping out our community really demonstrates the spirit of what we do in working with our students year-round.”</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>For more information about the Bluegrass Domestic Violence Program, Inc., please visit <a href=\"http://beyondtheviolence.com/\">http://beyondtheviolence.com</a>.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>MEDIA CONTACT: </strong>Sarah Geegan, <span style=\"white-space: nowrap;\" class=\"baec5a81-e4d6-4674-97f3-e9220f0136c1\">(859) 257-5365<a style=\"margin: 0px; <a href=\"mailto:sarah.geegan@uky.edu\">sarah.geegan@uky.edu</a></p>',1369402115,'30415 at http://uknow.uky.edu'),(109,1,'Ag Impact on State, Region is Worth Billions','http://uknow.uky.edu/content/ag-impact-state-region-worth-billions','Carl Nathe','<span class=\"sw_img_wrap\"><a class=\"sw_img_a\" href=\"http://uknow.uky.edu/sites/default/files/farm_and_barns_1.jpg\"><img class=\"sw_img\" src=\"http://uknow.uky.edu/sites/default/files/imagecache/ctac_thumb/farm_and_barns.jpg\" /></a></span> <!--break--><p><strong>LEXINGTON, Ky. (May 29, 2013)</strong> — The importance of Kentucky agriculture extends well beyond the farm. The total economic impact of agriculture production, inputs, processing and manufacturing is nearly $46.3 billion and represents 263,000 jobs in Kentucky, based on a recent analysis by the University of Kentucky College of Agriculture.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Kentucky is one of a growing number of Southern states where an emerging agbioscience industry is proving to be a boon to their economies, according to a recent survey conducted by Battelle, the world’s largest independent research and development organization. Agbioscience encompasses a broad continuum of development, production and value-added use of plants and animals for food, health, fuel and industrial applications.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Historically, employment associated with Kentucky agriculture has been limited to production agriculture, said Alison Davis, agricultural economist and director for the college’s Community and Economic Development Initiative of Kentucky. The value of this sector in Kentucky is $6.1 billion; this includes cash receipts from commodities as well as revenues from additional sources of farm income, such as custom work, machinery hire and farm rental values.&nbsp; Cash receipts totaled nearly $5 billion including $2 billion in agricultural exports in 2011. The largest agricultural export originating from Kentucky is soybeans followed by tobacco and corn.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>It’s important, however, to recognize food and fiber processing and manufacturing that value-added enterprises represent beyond the farm gate.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>“Ignoring these businesses underestimates the value of the agricultural sector,” Davis said.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Defining the Kentucky agriculture cluster to include these sectors adds 143,776 workers to the more than 90,000 individuals who work directly in agriculture production and $24 billion in direct revenues. This impact does not include service-based industries such as banking, insurance or legal sectors. In addition, this number does not include the nearly $10 billion impact of the forestry and wood products sector and the more than 51,000 jobs that support it, Davis noted.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The Battelle study, “Impact and Innovation: Agbioscience in the Southern United States,” finds that agriculture, forestry and fisheries production generates $240 billion in economic activity within the Southern region and supports more than 2.2 million jobs, with labor income totaling $62 billion.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Downstream processing of agriculture, forestry and fisheries output into value-added food and industrial products adds an additional $1 trillion in output to the South’s economy, and almost 4.6 million jobs with labor income totaling more than $200 billion.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>“In our science- and technology-based economic development practice at Battelle, we have observed the consistent rise of agbioscience as a core driver of economic growth and business expansion opportunities for the U.S.,” said Simon Tripp, co-author of the report. “This is an extremely dynamic sector, leveraging sustainable biobased resources to produce goods that meet large-scale market needs. The Southern region is a global leader in traditional agricultural economic activity and can count itself as one of a select few regions in the world that is also leading the charge in emerging areas of the modern bioeconomy.”</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The study’s findings show that agbioscience, its value-chain in production and the downstream industrial activity are vital to the country’s sustainable global and domestic economic future, with the Southern region helping drive that activity.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>“The current and future importance of the agbiosciences is hard to overstate,” Tripp said. “For instance, this science and industry sector is fundamental to the survival of the world’s expanding population, the food security of our nation and the health of our population.”</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Battelle conducted the report on behalf of the Southern Association of Agricultural Experiment Station Directors and the Association of Southern Regional Extension Directors.</p><p align=\"center\">&nbsp;</p><p align=\"center\">&nbsp;</p><p align=\"center\">&nbsp;</p><p><strong>MEDIA CONTACTS</strong>:&nbsp;
